title: Barefoot in the Park
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.

title: Barfly
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 nominations.

title: Barney's Version
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With a magnificent performance by Paul Giamatti, Barney's Version offers much comedy and insight to the complexities of modern romance.

title: Barnyard
tomato_consensus: Unimaginative and unfunny, this tale of barnyard mischief borders on 'udder' creepiness and adds little to this summer's repertoire of animated films.

title: Bart Got a Room
tomato_consensus: Just enough sweetness and good performances lighten up the high school-set tensions, creating a family-appropriate teen comedy.

title: Barton Fink
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Twisty and unsettling, the Coen brothers' satirical tale of a 1940s playwright struggling with writer's block is packed with their trademark sense of humor and terrific performances from its cast.

title: Basic
tomato_consensus: Basic gets so needlessly convoluted in its plot twists that the viewer eventually loses interest.

title: Basic Instinct
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Unevenly echoing the work of Alfred Hitchcock, Basic Instinct contains a star-making performance from Sharon Stone but is ultimately undone by its problematic, overly lurid plot.

title: Basic Instinct 2
tomato_consensus: Unable to match the suspense and titilation of its predecessor, Basic Instinct 2 boasts a plot so ludicrous and predictable it borders on "so-bad-it's-good."

title: Bastard Out of Carolina
awards: Won 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 5 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Batman: Mask of the Phantasm
tomato_consensus: Stylish and admirably respectful of the source material, Batman: Mask of the Phantasm succeeds where many of the live-action Batman adaptations have failed.

title: Batman & Robin
tomato_consensus: Joel Schumacher's tongue-in-cheek attitude hits an unbearable limit in Batman & Robin resulting in a frantic and mindless movie that's too jokey to care much for.

title: Batman: The Movie
tomato_consensus: Batman: The Movie elevates camp to an art form -- and has a blast doing it, every gloriously tongue-in-cheek inch of the way.

title: Batman
tomato_consensus: An eerie, haunting spectacle, Batman succeeds as dark entertainment, even if Jack Nicholson's Joker too often overshadows the title character.

title: Batman Begins
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 44 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Brooding and dark, but also exciting and smart, Batman Begins is a film that understands the essence of one of the definitive superheroes.

title: Batman Beyond: Return of the Joker
wiki_title: Batman Beyond: Return of the Joker

title: Batman Forever
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Loud, excessively busy, and often boring, Batman Forever nonetheless has the charisma of Jim Carrey and Tommy Lee Jones to offer mild relief.

title: Batman Returns
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Director Tim Burton's dark, brooding atmosphere, Michael Keaton's work as the tormented hero, and the flawless casting of Danny DeVito as The Penguin and Christopher Walken as, well, Christopher Walken make the sequel better than the first.

title: Battle Los Angeles
tomato_consensus: Overlong and overly burdened with war movie clich?s, Battle: Los Angeles will entertain only the most ardent action junkies.

title: Battle Royale
tomato_consensus: Battle Royale is a controversial and violent parable of adolescence, heightening teenage melodrama with life-or-death stakes.

title: Battle for Haditha
tomato_consensus: This narrative retelling of the real life tragedy in Haditha is gripping and immediate but may sacrifice the subtleties of history for dramatic impact.

title: Battle for Terra
tomato_consensus: Despite its earnest aspirations to be a thought-provoking sci-fi alternative, Battle for Terra lacks both a cohesive story and polished visuals, and fails to resonate.

title: Battle for the Planet of the Apes
wiki_title: Battle for the Planet of the Apes

title: Battle in Heaven
tomato_consensus: Though it tries to be provocative, Battle in Heaven is lethargic and mind-numbing.

title: Battle in Seattle
tomato_consensus: Well intentioned and passionate, this docu-drama about the 1999 WTO protests is heavier on politics than character development.

title: Battle of Britain
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win.

title: Battlefield Earth
tomato_consensus: Ugly, campy, and poorly acted, Battlefield Earth is a stunningly misguided, aggressively bad sci-fi folly.

title: Battleship
tomato_consensus: It may offer energetic escapism for less demanding filmgoers, but Battleship is too loud, poorly written, and formulaic to justify its expense -- and a lot less fun than its source material.

title: Be Cool
tomato_consensus: Be Cool is tepid, square, and lukewarm; as a parody of the music business, it has two left feet.

title: Be Kind Rewind
tomato_consensus: Slighter and less disciplined than Gondry's previous mind-benders.

title: Beaches
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Beastly
tomato_consensus: Fundamentally misguided, poorly written, and badly acted, Beastly adds little to the legacy of its timeless source material.

title: Beasts of the Southern Wild
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 66 wins & 66 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Beasts of the Southern Wild is a fantastical, emotionally powerful journey and a strong case of filmmaking that values imagination over money.

title: Beaufort
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Beaufort is a deeply observant and meditative war film, masterfully rendered by director Joseph Cedar.

title: Beautiful
tomato_consensus: Sally Field's directing debut suffers from an inconsistent tone, implausible script, and a protagonist that critics say is one of the most loathsome to come around in a long time.

title: Beautiful Creatures
tomato_consensus: Implausible, uneven, and gratuitously violent, this esotrogen-powered crime caper lacks the finesse of Thelma and Louise or Guy Ritchie's work.

title: Beautiful Creatures
tomato_consensus: Charming romantic leads and esteemed supporting cast aside, Beautiful Creatures is a plodding YA novel adaptation that feels watered down for the Twilight set.

title: Beautiful Girls
tomato_consensus: A warm, thoughtful dramedy about male insecurity, Beautiful Girls is buoyed by an excellent cast - particularly Natalie Portman in a stunning early role.

title: Beauty Shop
tomato_consensus: Despite a strong performance by Queen Latifah, Beauty Shop is in need of some style pointers.

title: Beauty and the Beast: The Enchanted Christmas
wiki_title: Beauty and the Beast: The Enchanted Christmas

title: Beauty and the Beast
tomato_consensus: Enchanting, sweepingly romantic, and featuring plenty of wonderful musical numbers, Beauty and the Beast is one of Disney's most elegant animated offerings.

title: Beavis and Butt-Head Do America
tomato_consensus: Beavis and Butt-Head Do America is unabashedly offensive, unapologetically stupid, and unexpectedly funny.

title: Because I Said So
tomato_consensus: Overly reliant on caricatures and lacking any human insight, Because I Said So is an unfunny, cliche-ridden mess.

title: Because of Winn-Dixie
tomato_consensus: An old-fashioned, if bland, adaptation of Kate DiCamillo's novel.

title: Becoming Jane
tomato_consensus: Although Becoming Jane is a well-crafted period piece, it lacks fresh insight into the life and works of Jane Austen. The film focuses too much on wardrobe and not enough on Austen's achievements.

title: Bedazzled
tomato_consensus: Though it has its funny moments, this remake is essentially a one-joke movie with too many flat spots.

title: Bedtime Stories
tomato_consensus: Though it may earns some chuckles from pre-teens, this kid-friendly Adam Sandler comedy is uneven, poorly paced, and lacks the requisite whimsy to truly work.

title: Bee Movie
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Bee Movie has humorous moments, but its awkward premise and tame delivery render it mostly forgettable.

title: Bee Season
tomato_consensus: Bee Season is an intelligent, but frustratingly distant and diffuse drama about family dysfunction.

title: Beerfest
tomato_consensus: Beerfest features some laugh-inducing gags, but is too long and the pacing too uneven to form a coherent, functioning comedy.

title: Before Midnight
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Building on the first two installments in Richard Linklater's well-crafted Before trilogy, Before Midnight offers intelligent, powerfully acted perspectives on love, marriage, and long-term commitment.

title: Before Night Falls
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An impressionistic, fragmented look at Reinaldo Arenas, Before Night Falls' imagery manages to evoke a sense of the writer's artistry, and Bardem's strong performance holds the film together. Finally, a biopic done well.

title: Before Sunrise
tomato_consensus: Thought-provoking and beautifully filmed, Before Sunrise is an intelligent, unabashedly romantic look at modern love, led by marvelously natural performances from Ethan Hawke and Julie Delpy.

title: Before Sunset
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Filled with engaging dialogue, Before Sunset is a witty, poignant romance, with natural chemistry between Hawke and Delpy.

title: Before the Devil Knows You're Dead
tomato_consensus: A tense and effective thriller, Before the Devil Knows You're Dead marks a triumphant return to form for director Sidney Lumet.
wiki_title: Before the Devil Knows You're Dead

title: Before the Fall
tomato_consensus: Despite a degree of predictability and cliches, the high production values and sincere performances by the leads elevate this coming-of-age story set in Nazi Germany.

title: Before the Rain
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Beginners
tomato_consensus: Wearing its twee heart on its sleeve, Beginners explores the depths of modern, multi-generational romance with wit and depth.

title: Behind Enemy Lines
tomato_consensus: The plot for Behind Enemy Lines is more jingoistic than credible, and the overload of flashy visual tricks makes the action sequences resemble a video game.

title: Behind Enemy Lines II: Axis of Evil
wiki_title: Behind Enemy Lines II: Axis of Evil

title: Behind the Sun
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Visually poetic, Behind the Sun is a powerful statement about cycles of violence.

title: Beijing Bicycle
tomato_consensus: Though rather repetitive in its plot, Beijing Bicycle provides an interesting look at the economic and social changes that have occurred in China.

title: Being Flynn
tomato_consensus: Robert De Niro gives a sincere, gripping performance, but Being Flynn is an uneasy mix of drama and comedy that fails to emotionally resonate as a whole.

title: Being John Malkovich
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 52 wins & 48 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Being John Malkovich is both funny and smart, featuring a highly original script.

title: Being Julia
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Annette Bening delivers a captivating performance in Being Julia, a sophisticated comedy that follows a 1930s stage diva who experiences an identity crisis at age 40.

title: Bela Lugosi Meets a Brooklyn Gorilla
wiki_title: Bela Lugosi Meets a Brooklyn Gorilla

title: Bella
tomato_consensus: Critics labeled Bella as a simplistic and mostly pedestrian, but positive word of mouth gave this tiny indie surprising theatrical legs.

title: Belle de Jour
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 5 wins.

title: Bellflower
tomato_consensus: This fevered, stylish vision of the end of the world stitches multiple genres together and marks writer/director/star Evan Glodell as a true talent to watch.

title: Glocken aus der Tiefe - Glaube und Aberglaube in Rußland
Beloved
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A powerful, emotional and successful film adaptation of the original novel.

title: Below
tomato_consensus: Below is a creepy, claustrophobic exercise in style.

title: Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ
Ben-Hur
tomato_consensus: Uneven, but in terms of epic scope and grand spectacle, Ben-Hur still ranks among Hollywood's finest examples of pure entertainment.

title: Ben X
tomato_consensus: Thoughtful and provocative Dutch film concerned with autism, online gaming and bullying, though loses steam in the final act.

title: Bend It Like Beckham
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 17 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Inspiring, compassionate, and with a sly undercurrent of social commentary, Bend It Like Beckham is a lively feel-good movie that genuinely charms.

title: Don't Tempt Me
tomato_consensus: More Hellish than it is Heavenly, Agust?n D?az Yanes' black comedy about the Earthly duel between two angels doesn't have enough genuine laughs to support its far-fetched premise.

title: Beneath the Planet of the Apes
wiki_title: Beneath the Planet of the Apes

title: Beneath the Valley of the Ultra-Vixens
wiki_title: Beneath the Valley of the Ultra-Vixens

title: Benny & Joon
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 nominations.

title: Beowulf & Grendel
tomato_consensus: Despite the impressive Icelandic scenery, Beowulf And Grendel fails to find its footing in the transition from epic tale to the big screen.

title: Beowulf
tomato_consensus: Featuring groundbreaking animation, stunning visuals, and a talented cast, Beowulf has in spades what more faithful book adaptations forget to bring: pure cinematic entertainment.

title: Berlin: Symphony of a Great City
wiki_title: Berlin: Symphony of a Great City

title: Bernie
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Richard Linklater's Bernie is a gently told and unexpectedly amusing true-crime comedy that benefits from an impressive performance by Jack Black.

title: Best in Show
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 13 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though not as good as Waiting for Guffman, the movie's lively cast and hilarious script have the critics laughing. Fred Willard, in particular, steals the show.

title: Better Luck Tomorrow
tomato_consensus: A promising work by Lin, the energetic Better Luck Tomorrow is disturbing and thought-provoking.

title: Better Off Dead...
tomato_consensus: Better Off Dead is an anarchic mix of black humor and surreal comedy, anchored by John Cusack's winsome, charming performance.

title: Betty Blue
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Beverly Hills Chihuahua
tomato_consensus: Despite hitting some sweet notes, Beverly Hills Chihuahua is little more than disposable family entertainment.

title: Beverly Hills Cop
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Beverly Hills Cop II
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Bewitched
tomato_consensus: Bewitched is haunted by scattered laughs and a lack of direction.

title: Beyond Borders
tomato_consensus: Beyond Borders is good-intentioned, but the use of human suffering as a backdrop for a romance comes across as sanctimonious and exploitative.

title: Beyond a Reasonable Doubt
tomato_consensus: Hackneyed and over dramatic, this undercooked courtroom drama suffers from bad dialogue and a twist ending you'll see from a distance.

title: Beyond the Mat
tomato_consensus: Even if you aren't a fan, Beyond the Mat provides a riveting, perceptive look into the world of professional wrestling by taking a closer look at the people beneath the personas.

title: Beyond the Sea
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kevin Spacey's bio of singer Bobby Darin is either a fearless piece of showmanship or an embarrassing vanity project, according to critics.

title: Beyond the Valley of the Dolls
wiki_title: Beyond the Valley of the Dolls

title: Bicentennial Man
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Bicentennial Man is ruined by a bad script and ends up being dull and mawkish.

title: Big
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Refreshingly sweet and undeniably funny, Big is a showcase for Tom Hanks, who dives into his role and infuses it with charm and surprising poignancy.

title: Big Daddy
tomato_consensus: Adam Sandler acquits himself admirably, but his charm isn't enough to make up for Big Daddy's jarring shifts between crude humor and mawkish sentimentality.

title: Big Deal on Madonna Street
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Big Eden
tomato_consensus: Though unrealistic, Big Eden has all the charm and sweetness of a fairy tale.

title: Big Fat Liar
tomato_consensus: Though there's nothing that offensive about Big Fat Liar, it is filled with Hollywood cliches and cartoonish slapstick, making it strictly for kids.

title: Big Fish
tomato_consensus: A charming father-and-son tale filled with typical Tim Burton flourishes.

title: Big Miracle
tomato_consensus: Big Miracle uses real-life events as the basis for a surprisingly satisfying family drama.

title: Big Momma's House
tomato_consensus: Big Momma's House is funny in some parts, but it is essentially a one-joke movie.

title: Big Momma's House 2
tomato_consensus: Unfunny and unoriginal. In other words, a perfect piece of evidence for opponents of pointless movie sequels.

title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son
tomato_consensus: Unnecessary, unfunny, and generally unwelcome, Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son offers more of the same for fans of Martin Lawrence's perplexingly popular series.
wiki_title: Big Mommas: Like Father, Like Son

title: Big Night
tomato_consensus: The performances in Big Night are wonderful, and the food looks delicious.

title: Big Trouble
tomato_consensus: With its large cast and frantic comic pacing, Big Trouble labors for slapstick-style hilarity, but it never really gains steam.

title: Big Trouble in Little China
tomato_consensus: Brimming with energy and packed with humor, Big Trouble in Little China distills kung fu B-movies as affectionately as it subverts them.

title: Biker Boyz
tomato_consensus: Waste of a good cast. For a movie about bike racing, it never gets up to speed.

title: Bill & Ted's Excellent Adventure
tomato_consensus: Keanu Reeves and Alex Winter are just charming, goofy, and silly enough to make this fluffy time-travel Adventure work.

title: Billy Bathgate
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins.

title: Billy Budd
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.

title: Billy Elliot
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 55 wins & 56 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Billy Elliot is a charming movie that can evoke both laughter and tears.

title: Billy Jack
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.

title: Billy Liar
awards: Nominated for 6 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 nomination.

title: Billy Madison
tomato_consensus: Billy Madison is typical early immature fare from Adam Sandler, even if it finds moments of inspired lunacy.

title: Birdman of Alcatraz
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Birth
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A well-mounted production is undermined by a muddled, absurd storyline of questionable taste.

title: Birthday Girl
tomato_consensus: Kidman shows her range in this quirky movie, but the shift in tone from romantic comedy to thriller may leave viewers unsatisfied.

title: Biutiful
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 33 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Javier Bardem's searing performance helps to elevate Biutiful, as does Alejandro Gonz?lez I??rritu's craftsmanship, but the film often lapses into contrivance and grimness.

title: Black Book
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 14 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A furious mix of sex, violence, and moral relativism, Black Book is shamelessly entertaining melodrama.

title: Black Cat, White Cat
country: Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, France, Germany, Austria, Greece, USA
tomato_consensus: Rambling and eccentric, Emir Kusturica's comedy captures the life and energy of the Gypsy family at the heart of the tale.

title: Black Death
tomato_consensus: Black Death delivers the fire and brimstone violence its subject matter warrants, while posing some interesting questions of faith and religion.

title: Black Dynamite
tomato_consensus: A loving and meticulous send-up of 1970s blaxsploitation movies, Black Dynamite is funny enough for the frat house and clever enough for film buffs.

title: Black Hawk Down
tomato_consensus: Though it's light on character development and cultural empathy, Black Hawk Down is a visceral, pulse-pounding portrait of war, elevated by Ridley Scott's superb technical skill.

title: Black Knight
tomato_consensus: Black Knight feels like a lazily constructed movie, filled with lame gags and constant mugging from Lawrence.

title: Black Mask
tomato_consensus: Stylish setting and masterfully choreographed fight scenes, but the story is low on credibility and high on excessive violence and gore.

title: Black Orpheus
tomato_consensus: Colorful, atmospheric, and infections, Black Orpheus takes an ancient tale and makes it fresh anew, thanks in part to its bewitching bossa nova soundtrack.

title: Black Rock
tomato_consensus: It springs from smarter ideas than your average chase thriller, but ultimately, Black Rock falls back on disappointingly familiar ingredients.

title: Black Snake Moan
tomato_consensus: Uninhibited performances, skillful direction, and a killer blues soundtrack elevate Black Snake Moan beyond its outlandish premise.

title: Black Swan
tomato_consensus: Bracingly intense, passionate, and wildly melodramatic, Black Swan glides on Darren Aronofsky's bold direction -- and a bravura performance from Natalie Portman.

title: Black and White
tomato_consensus: The atmosphere is affecting, and the story, at times, is compelling, but with a lean script and limp direction, Black and White doesn't add up to much.

title: Blade: Trinity
tomato_consensus: The latest Blade flick is getting a little long in the tooth; critics call it bloodless, dull, rusty, and an assortment of other puns.

title: Blade
tomato_consensus: Though some may find the plot a bit lacking, Blade's action is fierce, plentiful, and appropriately stylish for a comic book adaptation.

title: Blade II
tomato_consensus: Blade 2 takes what works in the original and gives us more. Unfortunately, plot and character development appear to have been left on the cutting room floor.

title: Blade Runner
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Misunderstood when it first hit theaters, the influence of Ridley Scott's mysterious, neo-noir Blade Runner has deepened with time. A visually remarkable, achingly human sci-fi masterpiece.

title: Blades of Glory
tomato_consensus: Thanks to the spirited performances of a talented cast - particularly Will Ferrell and Jon Heder as rivals-turned-teammates -- Blades of Glory successfully spoofs inspirational sports dramas with inspired abandon.

title: Blast from the Past
tomato_consensus: Cute idea, but not consistently funny.

title: Blaze
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Blazing Saddles
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Bless the Child
tomato_consensus: Bless the Child squanders its talented cast on a plot that's more likely to inspire unintentional laughs than shivers.

title: Blind Mountain
tomato_consensus: Li's characters are imperfectly drawn, and the film follows a somewhat problematic arc, but Blind Mountain is nonetheless deeply compelling viewing.

title: Blind Shaft
tomato_consensus: A taut, biting critique on the new economic conditions in China.

title: Blindness
tomato_consensus: This allegorical disaster film about society's reaction to mass blindness is mottled and self-satisfied; provocative but not as interesting as its premise implies.

title: BloodRayne
tomato_consensus: BloodRayne is an absurd sword-and-sorcery vid-game adaptation from schlock-maestro Uwe Boll, featuring a distinguished (and slumming) cast.

title: Blood and Chocolate
tomato_consensus: Cheap CG effects and laughable dialogue make Blood and Chocolate worse than the usual werewolf flick.

title: Blood & Orchids
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 1 nomination.

title: Blood Brothers: Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band
Blood Diamond
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Blood Diamond overcomes poor storytelling with its biting commentary and fine performances.

title: Blood Simple.
tomato_consensus: Brutally violent and shockingly funny in equal measure, Blood Simple offers early evidence of the Coen Brothers' twisted sensibilities and filmmaking ingenuity.

title: Blood Work
tomato_consensus: Blood Work is a routine, but competently made thriller marred by lethargic pacing.

title: Bloodbath at the House of Death
wiki_title: Bloodbath at the House of Death

title: Bloody Sunday
tomato_consensus: Bloody Sunday powerfully recreates the events of that day with startling immediacy.

title: Blow
tomato_consensus: With elements that seem borrowed from movies like Goodfellas and Boogie Nights, Blow is pretty much been-there-done-that despite another excellent performance from Johnny Depp. It, also, becomes too sentimental at the end.

title: Blow Dry
tomato_consensus: Heartwarming, but over-the-top and too formulaic.

title: Blow Out
tomato_consensus: With a story inspired by Antonioni's Blow Up and a style informed by the high-gloss suspense of Hitchcock, DePalma's Blow Out is raw, politically informed, and littered with film references.

title: Blow-Up
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Blue Car
tomato_consensus: A cautionary tale that rings true.

title: Blue Collar Comedy Tour: The Movie
wiki_title: Blue Collar Comedy Tour: The Movie

title: Blue Crush
tomato_consensus: Derailed by jarring plot turns, Crush is an implausible take on female friendships.

title: Blue Jasmine
tomato_consensus: Woody Allen's Blue Jasmine finds the director in peak late-period form -- and benefiting from a superb cast led by Cate Blanchett.

title: Blue Streak
tomato_consensus: Martin Lawrence lends his comedic touch, but the movie isn't much more than standard action-comedy fare.

title: Blue Thunder
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Blue Valentine
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 21 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This emotionally gripping examination of a marriage on the rocks isn't always easy to watch, but Michelle Williams and Ryan Gosling give performances of unusual depth and power.

title: Blue Velvet
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 22 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: If audiences walk away from this subversive, surreal shocker not fully understanding the story, they might also walk away with a deeper perception of the potential of film storytelling.

title: Boat Trip
tomato_consensus: Boat Trip is a lame, juvenile farce that's heavy on stereotypes and desperate antics but short on brains and laughs.

title: Bob & Carol & Ted & Alice
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Bob Roberts
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Bobby
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 5 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite best intentions from director Emilio Estevez and his ensemble cast, they succumb to a script filled with pointless subplots and awkward moments working too hard to parallel contemporary times.

title: Bobby Fischer Against the World
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Bobby Jones: Stroke of Genius
tomato_consensus: This earnest, monotonous biopic lacks dramatic tension and simplifies Jones' life.

title: Body Double
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Body Heat
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: Body of Lies
tomato_consensus: Body of Lies relies on the performances of Russell Crowe and Leonardo DiCaprio to elevate it beyond the conventional espionage thriller.

title: Boiler Room
tomato_consensus: Its ending is disappointingly tidy, but Boiler Room boasts just enough sharp writing and brisk pacing to make getting there worthwhile.

title: Bolt
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 21 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Bolt is a pleasant animated comedy that overcomes the story's familiarity with strong visuals and likable characters.

title: Bon voyage
tomato_consensus: It's froth, but stylish and giddily entertaining.

title: Bones
tomato_consensus: Slow to start, the sleek looking Bones is more silly than scary.

title: Boogeyman
tomato_consensus: The plot is been-there done-that generic, and none of the shock effects can do anything to build up suspense.

title: Boogie Nights
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 29 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Grounded in strong characters, bold themes, and subtle storytelling, Boogie Nights is a groundbreaking film both for director P.T. Anderson and star Mark Wahlberg.

title: Book of Shadows: Blair Witch 2
tomato_consensus: This sequel to Blair Witch Project is all formula and no creativity, mechanically borrowing elements from the original and other horror movies.

title: Borat: Cultural Learnings of America for Make Benefit Glorious Nation of Kazakhstan
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Jagshemash! Borat gets high-fives almost all-around for being offensive in the funniest possible way. Part satire, part shockumentary, Borat stars Sacha Baron Cohen as the gleefully sexist, homophobic, and anti-Semitic title character on a cross-country trek to learn more about our strange nation; along the way he dredges up the seamy underbelly of American prejudice and ignorance. Now the cat is out of the bag, what will Cohen do for an encore?
wiki_title: Borat: Cultural Learnings of America for Make Benefit Glorious Nation of Kazakhstan

tomato_consensus: Chronicle transcends its found-footage gimmick with a smart script, fast-paced direction, and engaging performances from the young cast.

title: Chéri
tomato_consensus: A too-short script and a romance lacking in heat detracts from an otherwise haughty charmer.

title: Cimarron
tomato_consensus: Cimarron is supported by a strong performance from Irene Dunne, but uneven in basically every other regard, and riddled with potentially offensive stereotypes.

title: Cinderella
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The rich colors, sweet songs, adorable mice and endearing (if suffering) heroine make Cinderella a nostalgically lovely charmer.

title: Cinderella III: A Twist in Time
wiki_title: Cinderella III: A Twist in Time

title: Cinderella Man
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With grittiness and an evocative sense of time and place, Cinderella Man is a powerful underdog story. And Ron Howard and Russell Crowe prove to be a solid combination.

title: Cirque du Freak: The Vampire's Assistant
tomato_consensus: This overstuffed, scattershot vampire flick suffers from poor characterization and an unwieldy mix of scares and chuckles.
wiki_title: Cirque du Freak: The Vampire's Assistant

title: Cirque du Freak: The Vampire's Assistant
tomato_consensus: This overstuffed, scattershot vampire flick suffers from poor characterization and an unwieldy mix of scares and chuckles.

title: Citizen Kane
tomato_consensus: Orson Welles's epic tale of a publishing tycoon's rise and fall is entertaining, poignant, and inventive in its storytelling, earning its reputation as a landmark achievement in film.

title: Citizen Toxie: The Toxic Avenger IV
wiki_title: Citizen Toxie: The Toxic Avenger IV

title: Citizen X
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 9 wins & 11 nominations.

title: City Island
tomato_consensus: Raymond De Felitta combines warmth, humanity, and a natural sense of humor, and is abetted by Andy Garcia and an excellent ensemble cast.

title: City Slickers II: The Legend of Curly's Gold
wiki_title: City Slickers II: The Legend of Curly's Gold

title: City by the Sea
tomato_consensus: Even though the movie is well acted, it sinks under an abundance of melodrama and cliches.

title: City of Angels
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 9 wins & 11 nominations.

title: City of Ember
tomato_consensus: City of Ember is visually arresting, and boasts a superb cast, but is sadly lacking in both action and adventure.

title: City of God
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 57 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A shocking and disturbing, but always compelling look at life in the slums of Rio de Janiero.

title: City of Men
tomato_consensus: Brutal and unflinching, City of Men is both a harrowing look at Brazil's favela life, and a touching tale of youths rushed into adulthood.

title: Claire's Knee
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins.

title: Clara's Heart
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 nominations.

title: Clash of the Titans
tomato_consensus: A goofy, old-school sword-and-sandal epic, Clash of the Titans mines Greek mythology for its story and fleshes it out with Ray Harryhausen's charmingly archaic stop-motion animation techniques.

title: Clash of the Titans
tomato_consensus: An obviously affectionate remake of the 1981 original, Louis Leterrier's Clash of the Titans doesn't offer enough visual thrills to offset the deficiencies of its script.

title: Clean
tomato_consensus: In one of her best roles, Cheung gives a believable and arresting performance as a recovering addict.

title: Clear and Present Danger
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Cleopatra
awards: Nominated for 4 Primetime Emmys. Another 1 nomination.

title: Clerks II
tomato_consensus: Clerks II dishes up much of the graphic humor and some of the insight that made the 1994 original a cult hit.

title: Click
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This latest Adam Sandler vehicle borrows shamelessly from It's A Wonderful Life and Back To The Future, and fails to produce the necessary laughs that would forgive such imitation.

title: Cliffhanger
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While it can't escape comparisons to the movies it borrows from, Cliffhanger is a tense, action-packed thriller and a showcase for the talents that made Sylvester Stallone a star.

title: Clockstoppers
tomato_consensus: A pleasant diversion for the young teens, but a waste of time for anyone older.

title: Close Encounters of the Third Kind
tomato_consensus: Close Encounters' most iconic bits (the theme, the mashed-potato sculpture, etc.) have been so thoroughly absorbed into the culture that it's easy to forget that its treatment of aliens as peaceful beings rather than warmongering monsters was somewhat groundbreaking in 1977.
wiki_title: Close Encounters of the Third Kind

title: Closed Circuit
tomato_consensus: Slick and well acted, Closed Circuit unfortunately never quite works up a full head of steam, with a plot that's alternately predictable and full of holes.

title: Closer
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 24 nominations.

title: Closet Cases of the Nerd Kind
wiki_title: Closet Cases of the Nerd Kind

title: Cloud Atlas
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its sprawling, ambitious blend of thought-provoking narrative and eye-catching visuals will prove too unwieldy for some, but the sheer size and scope of Cloud Atlas are all but impossible to ignore.

title: Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Quirky humor, plucky characters and solid slapstick make this family comedy a frenetically tasty time at the movies.
wiki_title: Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)

title: Cloverfield
tomato_consensus: A sort of Blair Witch Project crossed with Godzilla, Cloverfield is economically paced, stylistically clever, and filled with scares.

title: Club Dread
tomato_consensus: Comedy is too hit-or-miss is this slasher spoof.

title: Introducing the Dwights
tomato_consensus: Despite a predictable storyline, Introducing the Dwights succeeds on the strength of its sweet and earnest portrayal of family dysfunction.

title: Coach Carter
tomato_consensus: Even though it's based on a true story, Coach Carter is pretty formulaic stuff, but it's effective and energetic, thanks to a strong central performance from Samuel L. Jackson.

title: Cobb
tomato_consensus: Tommy Lee Jones's searing performance helps to elevate Cobb above your typical sports biopic; he's so effective, in fact, that some may find the film unpleasant.

title: Cocktail
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: There are no surprises in Cocktail, a shallow, dramatically inert romance that squanders Tom Cruise's talents in what amounts to a naive barkeep's banal fantasy.

title: Coco Before Chanel
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though it doesn't quite capture the complexity of its subject's life, Coco Avant Chanel remains a fascinating, appropriately lovely tribute.

title: Cocoon
tomato_consensus: Though it may be too sentimental for some, Ron Howard's supernatural tale of eternal youth is gentle and heartwarming, touching on poignant issues of age in the process.

title: Code Name: The Cleaner
tomato_consensus: Code Name: The Cleaner is a limp action/comedy flick that alternates between lame, worn-out jokes and cheesy martial arts.

title: Code Unknown: Incomplete Tales of Several Journeys
tomato_consensus: Though challengingly cryptic at times, Code Unknown still manages to resonate.

title: Coffee and Cigarettes
tomato_consensus: Episodes vary in quality, but overall this talky film is quirkily engaging.

title: Cold Creek Manor
tomato_consensus: The plot of Cold Creek Manor is too predictable and contrived to generate suspense.

title: Cold Mountain
tomato_consensus: The well-crafted Cold Mountain has an epic sweep and captures the horror and brutal hardship of war.

title: Cold Souls
tomato_consensus: Straddling existential drama and surrealist comedy, Sophie Barthes debut feature is beautifully shot and full of inventive quandaries.

title: Collateral
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 20 wins & 36 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Driven by director Michael Mann's trademark visuals and a lean, villainous performance from Tom Cruise, Collateral is a stylish and compelling noir thriller.

title: Collateral Damage
tomato_consensus: Despite its timely subject matter, Collateral Damage is an unexceptional and formulaic action thriller.

title: College
tomato_consensus: A pale imitation of the raunchy frat comedies of old, College aims low and misses.

title: College Road Trip
tomato_consensus: Filled with shrill gags and middling slapstick, College Road Trip is woefully short on comic imagination.

title: Cologne
wiki_title: Cologne: From the Diary of Ray and Esther

title: Colombiana
tomato_consensus: Zoe Saldana has the chops but she's taken out by erratic and sloppy filmmaking.

title: Color of a Brisk and Leaping Day
wiki_title: Color of a Brisk and Leaping Day

title: Color Me Kubrick
tomato_consensus: Colour Me Kubrick has a fascinating premise, but provides little insight into Kubrick and the man who impersonated him.

title: Come Back to the 5 & Dime, Jimmy Dean, Jimmy Dean

wiki_title: Comic-Con Episode IV: A Fan's Hope

title: Coming to America

title: Committed
tomato_consensus: Critics say Committed is one of those films that shows promise -- some sort of vision -- of what the movie could have been. The key word is "could." As it is, the script is predictable, the story becomes tedious, and it's simply not funny. Heather Graham shows she can play a central character, but she's not enough to make Committed successful.

title: How Much Loving Does a Normal Couple Need?
Compliance
tomato_consensus: Anchored by smart, sensitive direction and strong performances, Complicance is a ripped-from-the-headlines thriller that's equal parts gripping and disturbing.

title: Compulsion
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Con Air
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Conan the Barbarian
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though Conan may take itself too seriously for some, this adventure film about a former slave seeking vengeance is full of quotable Schwarzenegger lines and gritty action.

title: Conan the Barbarian
tomato_consensus: While its relentless, gory violence is more faithful to the Robert E. Howard books, Conan the Barbarian forsakes three-dimensional characters, dialogue, and acting in favor of unnecessary 3D effects.

title: Confessions of a Summer Camp Councillor
Confessions of a Dangerous Mind
tomato_consensus: Rockwell is spot-on as Barris, and Clooney directs with entertaining style and flair.

title: Confessions of a Shopaholic
tomato_consensus: This middling romantic comedy underutilizes a talented cast and delivers muddled messages on materialism and conspicuous consumption.

title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen
tomato_consensus: Sloppily assembled fluff that won't have much of interest for anyone who isn't a preteen girl.
wiki_title: Confessions of a Teenage Drama Queen

title: Confetti
tomato_consensus: This improvised mockumentary has its funny and even sweet moments, but it's not as witty or sharp as Christopher Guest's offerings.

title: Bizalom
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Confidence
tomato_consensus: While it may not be the best con in town, the movie still manages to entertain with its colorful cast.

title: Confidentially Yours
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 nominations.

tomato_consensus: The two female leads, as well as energitic musical numbers, enliven an otherwise silly reworking of Billy Wilder's Some Like It Hot.

title: Conquest of the Planet of the Apes
wiki_title: Conquest of the Planet of the Apes

title: Conspiracy
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 17 nominations.

title: Constantine
tomato_consensus: Despite solid production values and an intriguing premise, Constantine lacks the focus of another spiritual shoot-em-up, The Matrix.

title: Constellation
tomato_consensus: Though earnestly directed, Constellation lacks dramatic fireworks and eventually falls into TV-movie sentimentality.

title: Contact
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 16 nominations.

title: Contagion
tomato_consensus: Tense, tightly plotted, and bolstered by a stellar cast, Contagion is an exceptionally smart -- and scary -- disaster movie.

title: Contempt
tomato_consensus: This powerful work of essential cinema joins "meta" with "physique," casting Brigite Bardot and director Godard's inspiration Fritz Lang.

title: Contraband
tomato_consensus: It's more entertaining than your average January action thriller, but that isn't enough to excuse Contraband's lack of originality and unnecessarily convoluted plot.

title: Control
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 27 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Control is a work of art, thanks to its evocative black and white cinematography and sensational performances from Sam Riley and Samantha Morton. Even those not familiar with Joy Division can still appreciate the beauty of the film.

title: Control Room
tomato_consensus: A fascinating, enlightening behind-the-scenes look at the Al Jazeera network.

title: Conversations with Other Women
tomato_consensus: Its occasional use of split screen may feel gimmicky at times, but Conversations With Other Women is a bold, inventive drama carried by its two charismatic leads.

title: Conviction
tomato_consensus: Less compelling -- and more manipulative -- than it should be, Conviction benefits from its compelling true story and a pair of solid performances from Swank and Rockwell.

title: Cool Hand Luke
tomato_consensus: Though hampered by Stuart Rosenberg's direction, Cool Hand Luke is held aloft by a stellar script and one of Paul Newman's most indelible performances.

title: Cool Runnings
tomato_consensus: Cool Runnings rises above its formulaic sports-movie themes with charming performances, light humor, and uplifting tone.

title: Cop Out
tomato_consensus: Cop Out is a cliched buddy action/comedy that suffers from stale gags and slack pacing.

title: Copying Beethoven
tomato_consensus: A pretentious historical drama that's ultimately a drag, despite Ed Harris' powerful performance.

title: Coraline
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With its vivid stop-motion animation combined with Neil Gaiman's imaginative story, Coraline is a film that's both visually stunning and wondrously entertaining.

title: Corbett and Courtney Before the Kinetograph
wiki_title: Corbett and Courtney Before the Kinetograph

title: Coriolanus
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 10 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Visceral and visually striking, Ralph Fiennes' Coriolanus proves Shakespeare can still be both electrifying and relevant in a modern context.

title: Corky Romano
tomato_consensus: Corky Romano continues the trend of bad movies featuring SNL members. The jokes are tired and unfunny, and the slapstick feels forced.

title: Corpse Bride
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: As can be expected from a Tim Burton movie, Corpse Bride is whimsically macabre, visually imaginative, and emotionally bittersweet.

title: Cosmopolis
tomato_consensus: Though some may find it cold and didactic, Cosmopolis benefits from David Cronenberg's precise direction, resulting in a psychologically complex adaptation of Don DeLillo's novel.

title: Country
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Country Strong
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The cast gives it their all, and Paltrow handles her songs with aplomb, but Country Strong's cliched, disjointed screenplay hits too many bum notes.

title: Coup de torchon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Couples Retreat
tomato_consensus: Despite a talented cast and some reliably pleasant interplay between Jon Favreau and Vince Vaughn, Couples Retreat leaves viewers stranded in an arid, mirthless comedy.

title: Courage Under Fire
tomato_consensus: An emotional and intriguing tale of a military officer who must review the merits of a fallen officer while confronting his own war demons. Effectively depicts the terrors of war as well as its heartbreaking aftermath.

title: Courageous
tomato_consensus: While the filmmaking is fairly competent, Courageous is overall worthless to anybody who doesn't subscribe to its dogmatic agenda.

title: Cousin cousine
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Cowards Bend the Knee or The Blue Hands
Cowboy Bebop: The Movie
tomato_consensus: This may be strictly for anime junkies, but they'll find much to like about Cowboy Bebop's casual violence and cool dialogue.

title: Cowboys & Aliens
tomato_consensus: Daniel Craig and Harrison Ford are as dependably appealing as ever, but they're let down by director Jon Favreau's inability to smooth Cowboys & Aliens' jarring tonal shifts.

title: Coyote Ugly
tomato_consensus: Well, the women in this film are incredibly attractive and flaunt that fact quite a lot. Unfortunatly, that's all there is to the film. The script is almost as big a joke as the charactors, and everything else follows the same path. If you're looking for a tease then see this flick, otherwise stay as far away as possible.

title: Crank: High Voltage
tomato_consensus: Crank: High Voltage delivers on its promises: a fast-paced, exciting thrill ride that doesn't take itself too seriously.

title: Crank
tomato_consensus: It's a film about a guy injected with Speed... wait, there's no bus. It's a film about a guy who has to kick a bunch of squirmy butt to stay alive... wait, no snakes or planes here. But it is a film about doing lots of drugs and pulling lots of punches, and it entertains accordingly.

title: Crash
tomato_consensus: A raw and unsettling morality piece on modern angst and urban disconnect, Crash examines the dangers of bigotry and xenophobia in the lives of interconnected Angelenos.

title: Crazy, Stupid, Love.
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It never lives up to the first part of its title, but Crazy, Stupid, Love's unabashed sweetness -- and its terrifically talented cast -- more than make up for its flaws.

title: Crazy/Beautiful
tomato_consensus: The story is not new, but the film gets credit for trying to move away from the genre's cliches. Kirsten Dunst and newcomer Jay Hernandez give believable performances.

title: Crazy Heart
tomato_consensus: Thanks to a captivating performance from Jeff Bridges, Crazy Heart transcends its overly familiar origins and finds new meaning in an old story.

title: Crazy in Alabama
tomato_consensus: Melanie Griffith gets kudos for her performance, but the movie just doesn't seem to come together.

title: Creation
tomato_consensus: This Charles Darwin biopic is curiously dispassionate, but Creation contains some of director Jon Amiel's best work, and Paul Bettany's performance is not to be missed.

title: Creepshow
tomato_consensus: It's uneven, as anthologies often are, but Creepshow is colorful, frequently funny, and treats its inspirations with infectious reverence.

title: Crime + Punishment in Suburbia
tomato_consensus: Despite the beautiful visuals, Crime and Punishment is too somber and pretentious. Also, the acting is of mixed quality.

awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 17 nominations.

title: Crimes of the Heart
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 1 nomination.

wiki_title: Crimson Rivers II: Angels of the Apocalypse

tomato_consensus: A family movie without toilet jokes, but there's nothing that haven't seen before.

awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 nomination.

tomato_consensus: Crossing Over is flagrant and heavy-handed about a situation that deserves more deliberate treatment, and joins its characters with coincidences that strain believability.

tomato_consensus: A cliched and silly pop star vanity project, Crossroads is strictly for Britney fans only.

title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe
tomato_consensus: With first-rate special effects and compelling storytelling, this adaptation stays faithful to its source material and will please moviegoers of all ages.
wiki_title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe

title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its leisurely, businesslike pace won't win the franchise many new fans, but Voyage of the Dawn Treader restores some of the Narnia franchise's lost luster with strong performances and impressive special effects.
wiki_title: The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader (2010 film)

title: The Chronicles of Riddick
tomato_consensus: As an action movie, Riddick offers some thrills, but as a sequel to Pitch Black, it's a disappointment.

title: The Chumscrubber
tomato_consensus: This derivative poke at suburbia falls short of delivering a scathing indictment of upper middle-class disconnect.

title: The Cider House Rules
tomato_consensus: The Cider House Rules has wonderful performances, lovely visuals, and an old-fashioned feel.

title: The Cincinnati Kid
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins.

title: The Circle
tomato_consensus: Bleak, yet powerful, The Circle offers a searing indictment of the oppressive conditions experienced by women in Iran.

title: The City of Lost Children
tomato_consensus: Not all of its many intriguing ideas are developed, but The City of Lost Children is an engrossing, disturbing, profoundly memorable experience.

title: The Claim
tomato_consensus: Though it sometimes feels cold and detached, The Claim is evocative, beautifully shot, and full of understated performances.

title: The Clan of the Cave Bear
wiki_title: The Clan of the Cave Bear (film)

title: The Class
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Energetic and bright, this hybrid of documentary style and dramatic plotting looks at the present and future of France through the interactions of a teacher and his students in an inner city high school.

title: The Clearing
tomato_consensus: Though it has an excellent cast, this emotionally detached movie is the kind that one admires more than enjoys.

title: The Client
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Closet
tomato_consensus: A pleasant comedy with a great cast.

title: The Collection
tomato_consensus: The Collection offers more grisly thrills and twisted humor than its predecessor; in other words, fun for genre fans, but unpleasant for anyone else.

title: The Collector
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 6 nominations.

title: The Collector
tomato_consensus: Increasingly tedious displays of gore makes this torture porn home-invasion-horror more programmatic than provocative.

title: The Color Purple
awards: Nominated for 11 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A sentimental tale that reveals great emotional truths in American history.

title: The Color of Money
tomato_consensus: That it's inferior to the original goes without saying, but Paul Newman and Tom Cruise are a joy to watch, and Martin Scorsese's direction is typically superb.

title: The Comebacks
tomato_consensus: Full of groin-centric humor and tired sports clich?s, The Comebacks is poor even by parody movie standards.

title: The Commitments
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 7 nominations.

title: The Company
tomato_consensus: Its deliberately unfocused narrative may frustrate some viewers, but The Company finds Altman gracefully applying his distinctive eye to the world of dance.

title: The Company Men
tomato_consensus: It might be hard for most viewers to identify with The Company Men's well-heeled protagonists, but writer/director John Wells uses their plight to make universally resonant points -- and gets the most out of his excellent cast.

title: The Company You Keep
tomato_consensus: The Company You Keep is a (frustratingly) slow-burning thriller about very contemporary issues.

title: The Company of Wolves
awards: Nominated for 4 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 10 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Condemned
tomato_consensus: The Condemned is a morally ambiguous, exceedingly violent and mostly forgettable action film.

title: The Conformist
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A commentary on fascism and beauty alike, Bernadro Bertolucci's The Conformist is acclaimed for its sumptuous visuals and extravagant, artful cinematography.

title: The Conjuring
tomato_consensus: Well-crafted and gleefully creepy, The Conjuring ratchets up dread through a series of effective old-school scares.

title: The Conspirator
tomato_consensus: The Conspirator is well cast and tells a worthy story, but many viewers will lack the patience for Redford's deliberate, stagebound approach.

title: The Constant Gardener
tomato_consensus: The Constant Gardener is a smart, gripping, and suspenseful thriller with rich performances from the leads.

title: The Contender
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Critics say this political thriller is solidly made, with top-notch performances, screenplay, and direction for about two third of the film. Unfortunately, the ending almost tank the whole movie.

title: The Conversation
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This tense, paranoid thriller presents Francis Ford Coppola at his finest -- and makes some remarkably advanced arguments about technology's role in society that still resonate today.

title: The Cook, the Thief, His Wife & Her Lover
tomato_consensus: This romantic crime drama may not be to everyone's taste, but The Cook, the Thief, His Wife & Her Lover is an audacious, powerful film.
wiki_title: The Cook, the Thief, His Wife & Her Lover

title: The Cookout
tomato_consensus: Good-natured but prepared with an absence of craft, The Cookout is an unappetizing collection of warmed-over jokes.

title: The Cooler
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 21 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A small movie elevated by superb performances.

title: The Corporation
tomato_consensus: The Corporation is a satisfyingly dense, thought-provoking rebuttal to some of capitalism's central arguments.

title: The Corruptor
tomato_consensus: This uninspiring cop thriller doesn't measure up to Chow Yun-Fat's Hong Kong work.

title: The Cotton Club
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.

title: The Counselor
tomato_consensus: The Counselor raises expectations with its talented cast and creative crew -- then subverts them with a wordy and clumsy suspense thriller that's mercilessly short on suspense or thrills.

title: The Count of Monte Cristo
wiki_title: The Count of Monte Cristo (1934 film)

title: The Count of Monte Cristo
tomato_consensus: Though it may not reach for any new artistic heights, The Count of Monte Cristo is an old-fashioned yet enjoyable swashbuckler.
wiki_title: The Count of Monte Cristo (2002 film)

title: The Counterfeiters
tomato_consensus: The Counterfeiters is a gripping account of one prisoner's moral dilemma, superbly portrayed by Karl Markovics.

title: The Country Bears
tomato_consensus: Despite all the celebrities on hand, this spin-off from a theme park attraction still feels tired and hokey.

title: The Court Jester
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.
tomato_consensus: A witty spoof of medieval swashbuckler movies, The Court Jester showcases Danny Kaye at his nimble, tongue-twisting best.

title: The Cove
tomato_consensus: Though decidedly one-sided, The Cove is an impeccably crafted, suspenseful expose of the covert slaughter of dolphins in Japan.

title: The Covenant
tomato_consensus: The Covenant plays out like a teen soap opera, full of pretty faces, wooden acting, laughable dialogue, and little suspense.

title: The Cranes are Flying
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 4 wins.

title: The Crazies
tomato_consensus: Tense, nicely shot, and uncommonly intelligent, The Crazies is a horror remake that, unusually, works.

title: The Crew
tomato_consensus: Though the four actors are good together, the jokes are stale and not funny.

title: El crimen del padre Amaro
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 21 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though melodramatic, El Crimen del Padre Amaro's critique of the Catholic church is a timely one.

title: The Criminal Life of Archibaldo de la Cruz
wiki_title: The Criminal Life of Archibaldo de la Cruz

title: The Crocodile Hunter: Collision Course
tomato_consensus: Aside from the unnecessary plot about a downed US spy satellite, there's not much difference between the movie and the TV show.

title: The Croods
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While it may not be as (ahem) evolved as the best modern animated fare, The Croods will prove solidly entertaining for families seeking a fast-paced, funny cartoon adventure.

title: The Crossing Guard
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 nominations.

title: The Crow: City of Angels
tomato_consensus: The Crow: City of Angels is a sloppy pretender that captures neither the mood nor energy of the original.

title: The Crow: Salvation
tomato_consensus: The Crow: Salvation adds nothing new to the series and is plagued by bad acting and dialogue.

title: The Crow
tomato_consensus: Filled with style and dark, lurid energy, The Crow is an action-packed visual feast that also has a soul in the performance of the late Brandon Lee.

title: The Crucible
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 11 nominations.

title: The Curious Case of Benjamin Button
tomato_consensus: Curious Case of Benjamin Button is an epic fantasy tale with rich storytelling backed by fantastic performances.
wiki_title: The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (film)

title: The Curse of the Cat People
tomato_consensus: Foregoing the horror thrills of its predecessor in favor of childhood fantasy, Curse of the Cat People is a touching and psychologically complex family film couched in a ghost story.
wiki_title: The Curse of the Cat People

title: The Curse of the Jade Scorpion
tomato_consensus: The writing for Scorpion is not as sharp as Woody Allen's previous movies as most of the jokes fall flat.
wiki_title: The Curse of the Jade Scorpion

title: A Dangerous Man: Lawrence After Arabia
wiki_title: A Dangerous Man: Lawrence After Arabia

title: A Dangerous Method
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 17 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A provocative historical fiction about the early days of psychoanalysis, A Dangerous Method is buoyed by terrific performances by Michael Fassbender, Keira Knightley, and Viggo Mortensen.

title: A Dry White Season
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.

title: A Good Day to Die Hard
tomato_consensus: A Good Day to Die Hard is the weakest entry in a storied franchise, and not even Bruce Willis' smirking demeanor can enliven a cliched, uninspired script.
wiki_title: A Good Day to Die Hard

title: Detective Conan: Captured in Her Eyes
Detective Conan: Crossroad in the Ancient Capital
Dragon Wars: D-War
tomato_consensus: Dragon Wars' special effects can't make up for an unfocused script and stale acting.

title: D.E.B.S.
tomato_consensus: Lacking enough material for a full-length movie, D.E.B.S. is short on both plot and laughs.

title: D.I.Y. or Die: How to Survive as an Independent Artist
wiki_title: D.I.Y. or Die: How to Survive as an Independent Artist

title: DOA: Dead or Alive
tomato_consensus: With a ridiculous plot and comical acting, checking one's brain at the door is required before watching DOA: Dead or Alive.

title: Dad
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Daddy's Little Girls
tomato_consensus: Daddy's Little Girls boasts fine performances and a poignant message, but is ultimately let down by amateurish filmmaking.

title: Daddy Day Camp
tomato_consensus: A mirthless, fairly desperate family film, Daddy Day Camp relies too heavily on bodily functions for comedic effect, resulting in plenty of cheap gags but no laughs.

title: Daddy Day Care
tomato_consensus: Daddy Day Care does its job of babysitting the tots. Anyone older will probably be bored.

title: Daens
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Daltry Calhoun
tomato_consensus: Watching grass grow would likely be more entertaining than this dull, slight feature about a sod salesman.

title: Damage
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Damn Yankees!
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Damsels in Distress
tomato_consensus: Damsels in Distress can sometimes feel mannered and outlandish, but it's redeemed by director Whit Stillman's oddball cleverness and Greta Gerwig's dryly funny performance.

title: Dan in Real Life
tomato_consensus: The fine performances elevate Dan in Real Life beyond its sentimental plot.

title: Dance Flick
tomato_consensus: Dance Flick scores a few laughs thanks to the Wayans brothers' exuberance, but it's ultimately a scattershot collection of gags without much direction.

title: Dancer in the Dark

awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 28 wins & 34 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Dancer in Dark can be grim, dull, and difficult to watch, but even so, it has a powerful and moving performance from Bjork and is something quite new and visionary.

title: Dances with Wolves
tomato_consensus: A grand, sweeping epic with inarguably noble intentions and arresting cinematography, but one whose center, arguably, is not as weighty as it should be.

wiki_title: Dangerous Living: Coming Out in the Developing World

wiki_title: Danny, the Champion of the World (film)

awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Darby O'Gill and the Little People
wiki_title: Darby O'Gill and the Little People

title: Daredevil
tomato_consensus: Passable if derivative as entertainment, Ben Affleck fits the role but the film is not up to par with recent superhero films.

title: Dark Blue
tomato_consensus: Kurt Russell gives a good performance. Too bad there's nothing here that you haven't seen before.

title: Dark Blue World
country: Czech Republic, UK, Germany, Denmark, Italy, France
tomato_consensus: While it's better than Pearl Harbor, Dark Blue World still spends too much time on a trite love triangle.

title: Dark Days
tomato_consensus: Marc Singer's documentary about a group of homeless people living beneath the streets of New York City is haunting and uplifting in equal measure.

title: Dark Eyes
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 14 nominations.

title: Dark Shadows
tomato_consensus: The visuals are top notch but Tim Burton never finds a consistent rhythm, mixing campy jokes and gothic spookiness with less success than other Johnny Depp collaborations.

title: Dark Skies
tomato_consensus: Dark Skies writer director Scott Stewart has a solid cast, an interesting premise, and some admirable ambitions, but he can't figure out what to do with any of them, and the result is a dull, muddled effort that will bore all but the most devoted horror buffs.

title: Dark Star
tomato_consensus: A loopy 2001 satire, Dark Star may not be the most consistent sci-fi comedy, but its portrayal of human eccentricity is a welcome addition to the genre.

title: Dark Water
tomato_consensus: All the atmospherics in Dark Water can't make up for the lack of genuine scares.

title: Darkman II: The Return of Durant
wiki_title: Darkman II: The Return of Durant

title: Darkness
tomato_consensus: Yet another predictable variation on the hoary old haunted-house movie, Darkness is an illogical, portentous mess.

title: Darkness Falls
tomato_consensus: A derivative movie where the scares are few and things don't make much sense.

title: Darling Lili
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Darwin's Nightmare
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: This eye-opening documentary brings some of the shocking effects of globalization to light.

title: Date Movie
tomato_consensus: In an attempt to parody rom-com cliches, Date Movie ultimately makes a mockery of itself, with juvenile toilet humor and empty pop culture references.

title: Date Night
tomato_consensus: An uneasy blend of action and comedy, Date Night doesn't quite live up to the talents of its two leads, but Steve Carell and Tina Fey still manage to shine through most of the movie's flaws.

title: Dave
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Ivan Reitman's refreshingly earnest political comedy benefits from an understated, charming script and a breezy performance by Kevin Kline.

title: Block Party
tomato_consensus: Dave Chappelle's Block Party is a raucous return to the spotlight for the comic. Buoyed by Chappelle's witty, infectious humor and outstanding performances from some of the more socially conscious artists in hip-hop like Mos Def, Kayne West, the Roots, and (will wonders never cease?) the reunited Fugees, this documentary/concert film is a joyous experience. With an appealing mix like that, who doesn't want to attend this Party?

title: David and Lisa
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Davy Crockett: King of the Wild Frontier
wiki_title: Davy Crockett, King of the Wild Frontier

title: Dawn of the Dead
tomato_consensus: A kinetic, violent and surprisingly worthy remake of George Romero's horror classic that pays homage to the original while working on its own terms.

title: Day Watch
tomato_consensus: Day Watch is frequently cheesy but it offers enough twists, surprises, and inventive action sequences to maintain viewer interest.

title: Daybreakers
tomato_consensus: Though it arrives during an unfortunate glut of vampire movies, Daybreakers offers enough dark sci-fi thrills -- and enough of a unique twist on the genre -- to satisfy filmgoers.

title: Daylight
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Days of Thunder
tomato_consensus: Days of Thunder has Tom Cruise and plenty of flash going for it, but they aren't enough to compensate for the stock plot, two-dimensional characters, and poorly written dialogue.

title: Dazed and Confused
tomato_consensus: Featuring an excellent ensemble cast, a precise feel for the 1970s, and a killer soundtrack, Dazed and Confused is a funny, affectionate, and clear-eyed look at high school life.

title: De-Lovely
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Musical numbers save movie from cliches.

title: Dead Again
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Dead Alive
tomato_consensus: The delightfully gonzo tale of a lovestruck teen and his zombified mother, Dead Alive is extremely gory and exceedingly good fun, thanks to Peter Jackson's affection for the tastelessly sublime.

title: Dead Man's Shoes
tomato_consensus: Though enhanced by cramped, gritty camerawork, this unsettling look at violence and revenge lacks the provocative edge needed to give it a substantial kick.

title: Dead Man Down
tomato_consensus: While the fine cast keeps Dead Man Down watchable throughout, the film is weighted down by absurd plot twists and a slack pace.

title: Dead Man Walking
tomato_consensus: A powerful, thought-provoking film that covers different angles of its topic without resorting to preaching, Dead Man Walking will cause the viewer to reflect regardless of their political viewpoint.

title: Dead Poets Society
tomato_consensus: Affecting performances from the young cast and a genuinely inspirational turn from Robin Williams grant Peter Weir's prep school drama top honors.

title: Dead Silence
tomato_consensus: More tasteful than recent slasher flicks, but Dead Silence is undone by boring characters, bland dialogue, and an unnecessary and obvious twist ending.

title: Dead Snow
tomato_consensus: Though it doesn't cover new ground, Dead Snow is an entertaining mix of camp, scares, and blood and guts.

title: Dead of Night
tomato_consensus: With four accomplished directors contributing, Dead of Night is a classic horror anthology that remains highly influential.

title: Dear America: Letters Home from Vietnam
awards: Won 2 Primetime Emmys. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.
wiki_title: Dear America: Letters Home from Vietnam

title: Dear Frankie
tomato_consensus: Dear Frankie is a small, good-hearted film with fine performances.

title: Dear John
tomato_consensus: Built from many of the same ingredients as other Nicholas Sparks tearjerkers, Dear John suffers from its cliched framework, as well as Lasse Hallstrom's curiously detached directing.

wiki_title: Death, Deceit and Destiny Aboard the Orient Express

title: Death in Gaza
awards: Won 3 Primetime Emmys. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Death Race

title: Death Race 2000
tomato_consensus: Death Race 2000 is a fun, campy classic, drawing genuine thrills from its mindless ultra-violence.

title: Death Sentence
tomato_consensus: A nonsensical plot and an absurd amount of violence make this revenge pic gratuitous and overwrought.

title: Death Wish V: The Face of Death
wiki_title: Death Wish V: The Face of Death

title: Death at a Funeral
tomato_consensus: It's amusing and it assembles a talented cast, but Neil LaBute's surprisingly faithful remake of the 2007 Frank Oz dramedy ultimately falls short of the original.

title: Death in Venice
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Death of a President
tomato_consensus: In this unconvincing fictional documentary, the tense 30 minutes that lead into the title event is outweighed by the boring, melodramatic hour preceding it.

title: Death to Smoochy
tomato_consensus: The talent involved can't save a script that has nowhere to go with its promising premise.

title: Deathstalker and the Warriors from Hell
wiki_title: Deathstalker and the Warriors from Hell

title: Deception
tomato_consensus: Deception is a middling, predictable potboiler with mediocre dialogue and ludicrous plot twists.

title: Decision Before Dawn
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Deck the Halls
tomato_consensus: Relying on flat humor and a preposterous plot, Deck the Halls is an unnecessarily mean-spirited holiday movie that does little to put viewers in a holiday mood.

title: Deconstructing Harry
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Dedication
tomato_consensus: Mandy Moore and Billy Crudup's lack of chemistry in Dedication makes it hard to maintain interest in this confused love story.

title: Deep Blue Sea
tomato_consensus: Aside from a few thrills, Deep Blue Sea is unoriginal and unintelligent.

title: Deep Red
tomato_consensus: The kinetic camerawork and brutal over-the-top gore that made Dario Argento famous is on full display, but the addition of a compelling, complex story makes Deep Red a masterpiece.

title: Deep Sea
tomato_consensus: Viewers will welcome being whisked away to this magical world of exotic sea life.

title: Reigo, the Deep-Sea Monster vs. the Battleship Yamato

awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Professionally made but artistically uninspired, Ed Zwick's story of Jews surviving WWII in the Belarus forest lacks the emotional punch of the actual history.

title: Definitely, Maybe
tomato_consensus: With a clever script and charismatic leads, Definitely, Maybe is a refreshing entry into the romantic comedy genre.

title: Delgo
tomato_consensus: Delgo features a blend of plot elements from earlier (and superior) fantasy films, with weaker animation and dull characters.

title: Pink Floyd: Delicate Sound of Thunder

awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 13 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Director Jean-Pierre Jeunet deftly combines horror, sci-fi, and humor in Delicatessen, a morbid comedy set in a visually ravishing futuristic dystopia.

title: Deliver Us from Eva
tomato_consensus: Though Union and LL Cool J are appealing romantic leads, Deliver Us From Eva is too predictable and contrived.

title: Deliver Us from Evil
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Deliver Us From Evil is a superb documentary and a searing look at an institution protecting its leaders at the expense of its followers. A profoundly disturbing chronicle of a wolf in sheep's clothing, the film builds a clear-eyed case against pedophile priest Oliver O'Grady, and the Catholic bureaucracy that protected him. The recollections of O'Grady's victims are nothing short of shocking and heartbreaking.

title: Deliverance
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Delta Farce
tomato_consensus: Too afraid to be a real satire of the Iraq War, Delta Farce instead devolves into a reprehensible, unfunny mix of slapstick, gay panic, and flatulence jokes.

title: Demolition Man
tomato_consensus: A better-than-average sci-fi shoot-em-up with a satirical undercurrent, Demolition Man is bolstered by strong performances by Sylvester Stallone, Wesley Snipes, and Sandra Bullock.

title: Tales from the Crypt: Demon Knight
Demonlover
tomato_consensus: A stylish but convoluted mess without any sympathetic characters.

title: Dennis the Menace
tomato_consensus: Walter Matthau does a nice job as Mr. Wilson, but Dennis the Menace follows the Home Alone formula far too closely.

title: Departures
tomato_consensus: If slow and predictable, Departures is a quiet, life affirming story.

title: Derailed
tomato_consensus: Derailed is one of those familiar and pulpy cautionary tales that depend largely on implausible coincidences and preposterous twists.

title: Derailed
tomato_consensus: With miscast stars, a ludicrous plot and an obvious twist, Derailed embodies its name all too aptly.

title: Desperately Seeking Susan

title: Despicable Me

tomato_consensus: Melodramatic and weighted down with silly dialogue, Deuces Wild is a forgettable, overheated thriller that leaves no cliche unturned.

title: Dial M for Murder

title: Diamond Men
tomato_consensus: Robert Forster's tour-de-force performance, along with Daniel M. Cohen's sensitive direction and subtly shaded screenplay, brings rare heft to this mentor/prot?g? buddy film.

tomato_consensus: Diamonds are Forever is a largely derivative affair, but it's still pretty entertaining nonetheless, thanks to great stunts, witty dialogue, and the presence of Sean Connery.

title: Diary of a Country Priest
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 7 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Diary of a Mad Black Woman
