wiki_title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days (film)

title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules
tomato_consensus: Moderately witty and acceptably acted, Diary of a Wimpy Kid 2 isn't much worse than the first installment.
wiki_title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules (film)

title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid
tomato_consensus: Unlike its bestselling source material, Diary of a Wimpy Kid fails to place a likable protagonist at the center of its middle-school humor -- and its underlying message is drowned out as a result.

title: Diary of the Dead
tomato_consensus: As Diary of the Dead proves, time hasn't subdued George A. Romero's affection for mixing politics with gore, nor has it given him cinematic grace or subtlety.

title: Dick
tomato_consensus: A clever, funny slice of alternate history, Dick farcically re-imagines the Watergate era and largely succeeds, thanks to quirky, winning performances from Michelle Williams, Kirsten Dunst and Will Ferrell.

title: Dickie Roberts: Former Child Star
tomato_consensus: A so-so David Spade comedy with a few laughs.

title: Did You Hear About the Morgans?
tomato_consensus: It gets a certain amount of mileage out of the inherent likability of its stars, but with an unfunny script and a lack of onscreen chemistry, Did You Hear About the Morgans? falls flat.
wiki_title: Did You Hear About the Morgans?

title: Die, Mommie, Die!
tomato_consensus: This stagy production has enough funny moments to work.

title: Die Another Day
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 28 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its action may be bit too over-the-top for some, but Die Another Day is lavishly crafted and succeeds in evoking classic Bond themes from the franchise's earlier installments.

title: Die Hard
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its many imitators (and sequels) have never come close to matching the taut thrills of the definitive holiday action classic.

title: Dieu est grand, je suis toute petite
tomato_consensus: Silly and superficial, with annoying characters.
wiki_title: Dieu est grand, je suis toute petite

title: Digimon: The Movie
tomato_consensus: Digimon is better than Pokemon, but it's still a predictable movie with mediocre animation.

title: Diner
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Dinner Rush
tomato_consensus: With the aid of a witty script and a well-acted ensemble, Dinner Rush is a tasty dish.

title: Dinosaur
tomato_consensus: While Dinosaur's plot is generic and dull, its stunning computer animation and detailed backgrounds are enough to make it worth a look.

title: Dirty Love
tomato_consensus: The laugh-free Dirty Love is a comedy dead zone -- it's aggressively crude and shoddily constructed.

title: Dirty Pretty Things
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An illuminating and nuanced film about the exploitation of illegal immigrants.

title: Dirty Rotten Scoundrels
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.
tomato_consensus: A buoyant, clever update of the conman flick Bedtime Story, with plenty of comedic jousting resulting from a winning chemistry between Michael Caine and Steve Martin.

title: Disaster Movie
tomato_consensus: Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst Movie yet.

title: The Kid
tomato_consensus: Critics find The Kid to be too sweet and the movie's message to be annoyingly simplistic.

title: Distant
tomato_consensus: Hauntingly beautiful, Distant communicates volumes with its almost pervasive silence.

title: District 9
country: USA, New Zealand, Canada, South Africa
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 52 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Technically brilliant and emotionally wrenching, District 9 has action, imagination, and all the elements of a thoroughly entertaining science-fiction classic.

title: District B13
tomato_consensus: A nonstop thrill ride, District B13's dizzying action sequences more than make up for any expository flaws.

title: Disturbia
tomato_consensus: Aside from its clich?d resolution, Disturbia is a tense, subtle thriller with a noteworthy performance from Shia LaBeouf.

title: Diva
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 9 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Beineix combines unique cinematography, an intelligent script, and a brilliant soundtrack to make Diva a stylishly memorable film.

title: Divided We Fall
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 15 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Divided We Fall takes a complex look at World War II, skillfully balancing humor and gravity.

title: Yadon ilaheyya
tomato_consensus: Suleiman utilizes absurdist humor to craft a provocative, original film.

title: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood
tomato_consensus: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood is more melodramatic than emotionally truthful, and uneven in its mixture of time periods, actresses, laughter and tears.
wiki_title: Divine Secrets of the Ya-Ya Sisterhood (film)

title: Django Unchained
tomato_consensus: Bold, bloody, and stylistically daring, Django Unchained is another incendiary masterpiece from Quentin Tarantino.

title: Do the Right Thing
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Doc Savage: The Man of Bronze
Doctor Zhivago
tomato_consensus: It may not be the best of David Lean's epics, but Dr. Zhivago is still brilliantly photographed and sweepingly romantic.

title: Doctor in the House
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 nominations.

title: Dodgeball: A True Underdog Story
tomato_consensus: Proudly profane and splendidly silly, Dodgeball is a worthy spiritual successor to the goofball comedies of the 1980s.

title: Dogma
tomato_consensus: Provocative and audacious, Dogma is an uneven but thoughtful religious satire that's both respectful and irreverent.

title: Dogtooth
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It'll be too disturbing -- and meandering -- for some, but Dogtooth is as disturbing and startlingly original as modern filmmaking gets.

title: Dogtown and Z-Boys
tomato_consensus: Dogtown and Z-Boys is a colorful, exhilarating look at the skateboarding subculture.

title: Dogville
country: Denmark, Sweden, UK, France, Germany, Netherlands, Norway, Finland, Italy
tomato_consensus: A challenging piece of experimental filmmaking.

title: Dolphin Tale
tomato_consensus: Wisely dialing down the schmaltz, Dolphin Tale is earnest, sweet, and well-told, a rare family film that both kids and parents can enjoy.

title: Domestic Disturbance
tomato_consensus: Well-made but extremely predictable, Domestic Disturbance is an average thriller that may work better on TV.

title: Dominick and Eugene
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Dominion: Prequel to the Exorcist
tomato_consensus: While director Schrader's attempt at a literate, internal exposition on evil temptations and human sin is admirable, this prequel suffers from hit-and-miss psychological tension, poor visual effects, and weak writing -- an overambitious failure of a horror movie.

title: Don't Be Afraid of the Dark
tomato_consensus: While it's pleasantly atmospheric and initially quite scary, Don't Be Afraid of the Dark ultimately fails to deliver the skin-crawling chills of the original.
wiki_title: Don't Be Afraid of the Dark (2011 film)

title: Don't Be a Menace to South Central While Drinking Your Juice in the Hood
wiki_title: Don't Be a Menace to South Central While Drinking Your Juice in the Hood

title: Don't Come Knocking
tomato_consensus: The cinematography conjures beautifully evocative landscapes, but aside from that, the film is meandering and pointless.

title: Don't Look Now
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Don't Look Now patiently builds suspense with haunting imagery and a chilling score -- causing viewers to feel Donald Sutherland and Julie Christie's grief deep within.

title: Don't Move
tomato_consensus: Sergio Castellitto's latest film has a heavy dose of melodrama and is populated with unlikable characters.

title: Don't Raise the Bridge, Lower the River
wiki_title: Don't Raise the Bridge, Lower the River

title: Don't Say a Word
tomato_consensus: Don't Say A Word is slick and competently made, but the movie is routine and stretches believability with many eye rolling moments.

title: Don't Tell Mom the Babysitter's Dead
wiki_title: Don't Tell Mom the Babysitter's Dead

title: Don Giovanni
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Don Juan DeMarco
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.
wiki_title: Dona Flor and Her Two Husbands

title: Donkey Punch
tomato_consensus: Donkey Punch begins as a promising thriller, but loses credibility while adhering too closely to genre conventions.

title: Donnie Brasco
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A stark, nuanced portrait of life in organized crime, bolstered by strong performances from Al Pacino and Johnny Depp.

title: Donnie Darko
tomato_consensus: Richard Kelly's debut feature Donnie Darko is a daring, original vision, packed with jarring ideas and intelligence and featuring a remarkable performance from Jake Gyllenhaal as the troubled title character.

title: Doom
tomato_consensus: Sure to please fans of the video game, but lacking in plot and originality to please other moviegoers.

title: Doomsday
tomato_consensus: Doomsday is a pale imitation of previous futuristic thrillers, minus the cohesive narrative and charismatic leads.

title: Journey to the Far Side of the Sun
Dorf and the First Games of Mount Olympus
wiki_title: Dorf and the First Games of Mount Olympus

title: Dorian Gray
tomato_consensus: Despite a lavish and polished production, Dorian Gray is tame and uninspired with a lifeless performance by Ben Barnes in the title role.

title: Dot the I
tomato_consensus: dot the i starts out as a standard love triangle, but last minute revelations turn the movie into a gimmick.

title: Double Dragon
tomato_consensus: Double Dragon's clever use of special effects cannot mask the film's overly simplistic storyline and cheesy dialogue.

title: Double Indemnity
tomato_consensus: A dark, tautly constructed adaptation of James M. Cain's novel -- penned by Billy Wilder and Raymond Chandler -- Double Indemnity continues to set the standard for the best in Hollywood film noir.

title: Double Jeopardy
tomato_consensus: A talented cast fails to save this unremarkable thriller.

title: Double Take
tomato_consensus: Despite a good performance by Orlando Jones, the movie is ruined by a ridiculous, messy plot and fails to generate laughs.

title: Doubt
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 44 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Doubt succeeds on the strength of its top-notch cast, who successfully guide the film through the occasional narrative lull.

title: Down and Out in Beverly Hills
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An enjoyable farce that relocates Jean Renoir's Boudu Saved From Drowning to '80s California, offering fine comedic performances from Nick Nolte, Richard Dreyfuss and Bette Midler.
wiki_title: Down and Out in Beverly Hills

title: Down in the Valley
tomato_consensus: The premise of Old West clashing with modern suburbia is fresh and initially intriguing, but the second act degenerates into a clumsy jumble of events which strain credibility.

title: Down to Earth
tomato_consensus: A toned down Chris Rock fails to bring a limp script to life as the movie moves from one gag to the next.

title: Down to You
tomato_consensus: Down to You is ruined by a bland, by-the-numbers plot and an awful script.

title: Down to the Sea in Ships
wiki_title: Down to the Sea in Ships (1922 film)

title: Downfall
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 17 nominations.

awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

wiki_title: Dr. Dolittle: Tail to the Chief

title: Dr. Dolittle 2
tomato_consensus: Although there are laughs to be had in Dr. Dolittle 2, its preoccupation with toilet humor and Murphy's restrained performance makes this a missed opportunity.

title: Dr. Goldfoot and the Girl Bombs
wiki_title: Dr. Goldfoot and the Girl Bombs

wiki_title: Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde (1920 film)

title: Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde
tomato_consensus: A classic. The definitive version of the Robert Louis Stevenson novella from 1931, with innovative special effects, atmospheric cinematography and deranged overacting.

wiki_title: Dr. Jekyll y el Hombre Lobo

title: Dr. No
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Featuring plenty of the humor, action, and escapist thrills the series would become known for, Dr. No kicks off the Bond franchise in style.

title: Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Stanley Kubrick's brilliant Cold War satire remains as funny and razor-sharp today as it was in 1964.

title: Dr. T and the Women
tomato_consensus: In terms of quality, Dr. T and the Women is one of Altman's good-but-not-great films. In typical Altman style, it features some great ensemble acting, including a wonderful performance by Richard Gere.

title: Dracula: Pages from a Virgin's Diary
tomato_consensus: Guy Maddin's film is a richly sensuous and dreamy interpretation of Dracula that reinvigorates the genre.
wiki_title: Dracula: Pages from a Virgin's Diary

title: Dracula
tomato_consensus: Bela Lugosi's timeless portrayal of Dracula in this creepy and atmospheric 1931 film has set the standard for major vampiric roles since.

title: Horror of Dracula
tomato_consensus: Trading gore for grandeur, Horror of Dracula marks an impressive turn for inveterate Christopher Lee as the titular vampire, and a typical Hammer mood that makes aristocracy quite sexy.

title: Dracula Has Risen from the Grave
wiki_title: Dracula Has Risen from the Grave

title: Drag Me to Hell
tomato_consensus: Sam Raimi returns to top form with Drag Me to Hell, a frightening, hilarious, delightfully campy thrill ride.

title: Dragnet
tomato_consensus: While it's sporadically funny and certainly well-cast, Dragnet is too clumsy and inconsistent to honor its classic source material.

title: Dragonball: Evolution
tomato_consensus: Executed with little panache or invention, Dragonball Evolution lacks the magic that made the books upon which it was based a cult sensation.

title: Dragonfly
tomato_consensus: Sappy, dull, and muddled, Dragonfly is too melancholic and cliched to generate much suspense.

title: DragonHeart
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Dragonslayer
tomato_consensus: An atypically dark Disney adventure, Dragonslayer puts a realistic spin -- and some impressive special effects -- on a familiar tale.

title: Drawing Restraint 9
tomato_consensus: Some of the images are striking, if confusing, but the film is unbearably slow and tedious.

title: Dream House
tomato_consensus: Dream House is punishingly slow, stuffy, and way too obvious to be scary.

title: Dreamcatcher
tomato_consensus: An incoherent and overly long creature feature.

title: Dreamer: Inspired by a True Story
tomato_consensus: Though formulaic, this horse story's saving grace is its strong performances.

title: Dreamgirls
tomato_consensus: Dreamgirls' simple characters and plot hardly detract from the movie's real feats: the electrifying performances and the dazzling musical numbers.

title: Dreams
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Dreamscape
tomato_consensus: Dreamscape mixes several genres -- horror, sci-fi, action -- and always maintains a sense of adventure and humor.

title: Dredd
tomato_consensus: Fueled by bombastic violence and impressive special effects, rooted in self-satire and deadpan humor, Dredd 3D is a rare example of a remake that actually works.

title: Dressed to Kill
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.

title: Drillbit Taylor
tomato_consensus: Owen Wilson's charms can't save Drillbit Taylor, an unfunny, overly familiar bullied-teen comedy.

title: Drinking Buddies
tomato_consensus: Smart, funny, and powered by fine performances from Olivia Wilde and Jake Johnson, Drinking Buddies offers a bittersweet slice of observational comedy.

title: Drive
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 43 wins & 80 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With its hyper-stylized blend of violence, music, and striking imagery, Drive represents a fully realized vision of arthouse action.

title: Drive Angry
tomato_consensus: It may deliver the over-the-top action pieces, but Drive Angry prefers to work safely within grindhouse formula than do something truly unique.

title: Driven
tomato_consensus: Underdeveloped characters, silly plot dynamics, and obvious CG effects.

title: Driving Lessons
tomato_consensus: Though it has charm, Driving Lessons is a middling offering in the genre where the youngster coming of age meets a quirky senior who teaches valuable lessons about life.

title: Driving Miss Daisy
tomato_consensus: Warm and smartly paced, and boasting impeccable performances from Morgan Freeman and Jessica Tandy.

title: Drowning Mona
tomato_consensus: Despite Danny De Vito's top billing, Drowning Mona drowns itself in humor that never rises about sitcom level. Contributing to the Mona's problems is that the characters are never really interesting, and there is a noticeable lack of energy in the character roles

title: Drumline
tomato_consensus: Essentially a sports movie with drums, the energetic Drumline somehow manages to make the familiar seem fresh.

title: The Legend of Drunken Master
tomato_consensus: Jackie Chan sends up some amazing and entertaining fight sequences in The Legend of Drunken Master.

title: DuckTales the Movie: Treasure of the Lost Lamp
wiki_title: DuckTales the Movie: Treasure of the Lost Lamp

title: Dude, Where's My Car?
tomato_consensus: The movie isn't funny, the plot is too thin, and the production values feel more like a TV sitcom than a movie.

title: Due Date
tomato_consensus: Shamelessly derivative and only sporadically funny, Due Date doesn't live up to the possibilities suggested by its talented director and marvelously mismatched stars.

title: Duets
tomato_consensus: Duets suffers from sloppy direction and stretches credibility. Also, the characters are uninteresting and it's hard to care about what happens to them.

title: Duma
tomato_consensus: This is an old-fashioned, richly textured family film that will appeal to children and adults alike.

title: Dumb and Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd
tomato_consensus: This lame prequel induces more groans than laughs. Rent the original instead.
wiki_title: Dumb & Dumberer: When Harry Met Lloyd

title: Dumb & Dumber
tomato_consensus: A relentlessly stupid comedy elevated by its main actors: Jim Carrey goes bonkers and Jeff Daniels carries himself admirably in an against-type performance.

title: Dumbo
tomato_consensus: Dumbo packs plenty of story into its brief runtime, along with all the warm animation and wonderful music you'd expect from a Disney classic.

title: Dummy
tomato_consensus: Dummy is a sweet family comedy that succeeds due to charming performances, even if the final product feels slightly undercooked.

title: Dune
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

wiki_title: Dungeons & Dragons: The Book of Vile Darkness

wiki_title: Dungeons & Dragons: Wrath of the Dragon God

title: Dungeons & Dragons
tomato_consensus: Critics say this movie has a cheap look and is badly directed. Despite the presence of talented actors, the performances are really bad, and additionally, some people are offended at Marlon Wayans' character, calling it a racist throwback to black stereotypes.

title: Duplex
tomato_consensus: It was funnier when it was called Throw Momma From the Train.

title: Duplicity
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Duplicity is well-crafted, smart, and often funny, but it's mostly more cerebral than visceral and features far too many plot twists.

title: Dylan Dog: Dead of Night
tomato_consensus: An uninspired, feebly-acted horror/comedy that produces little scares and laughs.

title: Deja Vu
tomato_consensus: Tony Scott tries to combine action, science fiction, romance, and explosions into one movie, but the time travel conceit might be too preposterous and the action falls apart under scrutiny.

title: How the Grinch Stole Christmas
tomato_consensus: Jim Carrey shines as the Grinch. Unfortunately, it's not enough to save this movie. You'd be better off watching the TV cartoon.

title: Il divo: La spettacolare vita di Giulio Andreotti
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 19 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While the web of corruption in this Italian political thriller can be hard for a non-native to follow, the visuals and the intrigue are compelling and thrilling in equal measure.

title: Detective Conan: Jolly Roger in the Deep Azure
wiki_title: Jolly Roger in the Deep Azure

title: Le divorce
tomato_consensus: A mixed bag of uneven tones that feels flat.

title: The Decline of the American Empire
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Les dames du Bois de Boulogne
wiki_title: Les Dames du Bois de Boulogne

title: Diabolique
tomato_consensus: Cruel, dark, but undeniably effective, Diabolique is a suspense thriller as effective as Hitchcock's best work and with a brilliant twist ending.

title: Live Free or Die Hard
tomato_consensus: Live Free or Die Hard may be preposterous, but it's an efficient, action-packed summer popcorn flick with thrilling stunts and a commanding performance by Bruce Willis. Fans of the previous Die Hard films will not be disappointed.

title: Detective Conan: Magician of the Silver Sky

Detective Conan: Strategy Above the Depths
The Da Vinci Code
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: What makes Dan Brown's novel a best seller is evidently not present in this dull and bloated movie adaptation of The Da Vinci Code.

title: The Damned
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 6 nominations.

title: The Damned United
tomato_consensus: Better than your average football pic, Damned United is carried by another star turn from Michael Sheen as Brian Clough.

title: The Dancer Upstairs
tomato_consensus: Javier Bardem is compelling in the lead role as a police detective in search of a violent, mysterious politcal radical, and as a director, John Malkovich proves adept at crafting a suspenseful mood.

title: The Dangerous Lives of Altar Boys
wiki_title: The Dangerous Lives of Altar Boys

title: The Darjeeling Limited
tomato_consensus: With the requisite combination of humor, sorrow and outstanding visuals, The Darjeeling Limited will satisfy Wes Anderson fans.

title: The Dark Crystal
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Dark Crystal's narrative never quite lives up to the movie's visual splendor, but it remains an admirably inventive and uniquely intense entry in the Jim Henson canon.

title: The Dark Knight
tomato_consensus: Dark, complex and unforgettable, The Dark Knight succeeds not just as an entertaining comic book film, but as a richly thrilling crime saga.

title: The Dark Knight Rises
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 32 wins & 61 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Dark Knight Rises is an ambitious, thoughtful, and potent action film that concludes Christopher Nolan's franchise in spectacular fashion.

title: The Day After Tomorrow
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A ludicrous popcorn flick filled with clunky dialogues, but spectacular visuals save it from being a total disaster.

title: The Day I Became a Woman
tomato_consensus: Meshkini has made an excellent contribution to Iranian cinema with this poetic, emotionally poignant film.

title: The Day of the Dolphin
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: The Day of the Jackal
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 10 nominations.

awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.

tomato_consensus: Socially minded yet entertaining, The Day the Earth Stood Still imparts its moral of peace and understanding without didacticism.

title: The Day the Earth Stood Still
tomato_consensus: Heavy on special effects, but without a coherent story at its base, The Day the Earth Stood Still is subpar re-imagining of the 1951 science-fiction classic.
wiki_title: The Day the Earth Stood Still (2008 film)

title: The Dead
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 6 nominations.

title: The Dead Zone
tomato_consensus: The Dead Zone combines taut direction from David Cronenberg and and a rich performance from Christopher Walken to create arguably the best Stephen King adaptation.

title: The Death of Mr. Lazarescu
tomato_consensus: Shot in naturalistic style, this is a powerful indictment of absurdity and indifference in the face of human suffering.

title: The Debt
tomato_consensus: Its time-shifting narrative creates distracting casting problems, but ultimately, The Debt is a smart, well-acted entry in a genre that could use more like it.

title: The Deep Blue Sea
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: The Deep Blue Sea
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Featuring an outstanding performance by Rachel Weisz, The Deep Blue Sea is a visually stunning, melancholy tale of subsumed passion.

title: The Deep End
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A well-acted film noir with arresting visuals.

title: The Deep End of the Ocean
wiki_title: The Deep End of the Ocean (film)

title: The Deer Hunter
tomato_consensus: Its greatness is blunted by its length and one-sided point of view, but the film's weaknesses are overpowered by Michael Cimino's sympathetic direction and a series of heartbreaking performances from Robert De Niro, Meryl Streep, and Christopher Walken.

title: The Departed
tomato_consensus: Featuring outstanding work from an excellent cast that includes Jack Nicholson, Leonardo DiCaprio, and Matt Damon, The Departed is a thoroughly engrossing gangster drama with the gritty authenticity and soupy morality that has infused director Martin Scorsese's past triumphs.

title: The Descendants
tomato_consensus: Funny, moving, and beautifully acted, The Descendants captures the unpredictable messiness of life with eloquence and uncommon grace.

title: The Descent
tomato_consensus: Deft direction and strong performances from its all-female cast guide The Descent, a riveting, claustrophobic horror film. In this low-budget import from Scotland, director Neil Marshall has masterfully created a spelunking nightmare, which doubles as a compelling meditation on morality, vengeance, and the depths to which we might go for survival.

title: The Desert Fox: The Story of Rommel
wiki_title: The Desert Fox: The Story of Rommel

title: The Devil's Advocate
tomato_consensus: Though it is ultimately somewhat undone by its own lofty ambitions, The Devil's Advocate is a mostly effective blend of supernatural thrills and character exploration.

title: The Devil's Backbone
tomato_consensus: Creepily atmospheric and haunting, The Devil's Backbone is both a potent ghost story and an intelligent political allegory.

title: The Devil's Rejects
tomato_consensus: Zombie has improved as a filmmaker since "House of 1000 Corpses" and will please fans of the genre, but beware -- the horror is nasty, relentless, and sadistic.

title: The Devil Inside
tomato_consensus: The Devil Inside is a cheap, choppy unscary mess, featuring one of the worst endings in recent memory.

title: The Devil Is a Woman
wiki_title: The Devil Is a Woman (1935 film)

title: The Devil Wears Prada
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 28 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A rare film that surpasses the quality of its source novel, this Devil is a witty expose of New York's fashion scene, with Meryl Streep in top form and Anne Hathaway more than holding her own.

title: The Devil and Daniel Johnston
tomato_consensus: Whether you think this mentally ill cult musician is worthy of being called a "genius," this document of his life is crafted with sincere respect and is fascinating to watch.

title: The Diary of Anne Frank
wiki_title: The Diary of Anne Frank (1959 film)

title: The Dictator
tomato_consensus: Wildly uneven but consistently provocative, The Dictator is a decent entry in the poli-slapstick comedy genre.

title: The Dilemma
tomato_consensus: It boasts a likable cast and an interesting premise, but The Dilemma can't decide what to do with them; the result is an uneven blend of cheesy slapstick and surprisingly dark comedy.

title: The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie
wiki_title: The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie

title: The Dish
tomato_consensus: A feel good movie without an abundance of mush.

title: The Divided Heart
awards: Won 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Diving Bell and the Butterfly
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 56 wins & 41 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Breathtaking visuals and dynamic performances make The Diving Bell and the Butterfly a powerful biopic.
wiki_title: The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (film)

title: The Door in the Floor
tomato_consensus: Though uneven in tone, this is one of the better adaptations of John Irving's novels, with Jeff Bridges giving one of his best performances.

title: The Double Life of Veronique
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 6 nominations.

title: The Dreamers
tomato_consensus: Though lushly atmospheric, The Dreamers doesn't engage or provoke as much as it should.

title: The Dreamlife of Angels
tomato_consensus: Showcasing excellent lead performances, The Dreamlife of Angels is an intelligent, absorbing character study of two women.

title: The Dresser
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 12 nominations.

title: The Duchess
tomato_consensus: While The Duchess treads the now-familiar terrain of the corset-ripper, the costumes look great and Keira Knightley's performance is stellar in this subtly feminist, period drama.

title: The Duellists
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Rich, stylized visuals work with effective performances in Ridley Scott's take on Joseph Conrad's Napoleonic story, resulting in an impressive feature film debut for the director.

title: The Dukes of Hazzard
tomato_consensus: A dumb, goofy, and vacuous adaptation of a TV show where plot is simply an excuse to string together the car chases.

title: Detective Conan: The Last Wizard of the Century
wiki_title: The Last Wizard of the Century

title: Detective Conan: The Phantom of Baker Street
Detective Conan: The Private Eyes' Requiem
Detective Conan: The Time Bombed Skyscraper
The Tunnel
tomato_consensus: The Tunnel is both a tension-filled thriller and a riveting history lesson.

title: An Education
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 25 wins & 55 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though the latter part of the film may not appeal to all, An Education is a charming coming-of-age tale powered by the strength of relative newcomer Carey Mulligan's standout performance.

title: The Einstein of Sex: Life and Work of Dr. M. Hirschfeld
E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial
tomato_consensus: Playing as both an exciting sci-fi adventure and a remarkable portrait of childhood, Steven Spielberg's touching tale of a homesick alien remains a piece of movie magic for young and old.

title: Edtv
tomato_consensus: If it's not as ambitious as The Truman Show in satirizing the voyeuristic nature of television, EdTV is an amiable, witty comedy with fine performances from Matthew McConaughey and Woody Harrelson.

title: Eagle Eye
tomato_consensus: Eagle Eye is a preposterously plotted thriller that borrows heavily from other superior films.

title: Eagle vs Shark
tomato_consensus: Though there are frequent moments of wit and mordant humor, Eagle vs Shark needs more to distinguish itself from other precious, Napoleon Dynamite-ish comedies.

title: Earth
tomato_consensus: With its spectacular and extensive footage, Earth is both informative and entertaining.

title: Earth Days
tomato_consensus: This engaging and well-organized eco-doc maps the successes and failures of the American environmental movement, thanks to sharp interviews and remarkable archive footage.

title: Earth Girls Are Easy
tomato_consensus: Earth Girls Are Easy is messy, silly, and not particularly bright -- qualities it comes by honestly and deliberately.

title: East Is East
awards: Nominated for 4 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 15 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Eastern Promises
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 27 wins & 43 nominations.
tomato_consensus: David Cronenberg triumphs again, showcasing the Viggo Mortensen's onscreen prowess in a daring performance. Bearing the trademarks of psychological drama and gritty violence, Eastern Promises is a very compelling crime story.

title: Easy A
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It owes a huge debt to older (and better) teen comedies, but Easy A proves a smart, witty showcase for its irresistibly charming star, Emma Stone.

title: Easy Rider
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Eat Drink Man Woman
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A richly layered look at the complex interactions between a widowed chef and his daughters, Ang Lee's generational comedy Eat Drink Man Woman offers filmgoers a tasty cinematic treat.

title: Eat Pray Love
tomato_consensus: The scenery is nice to look at, and Julia Roberts is as luminous as ever, but without the spiritual and emotional weight of the book that inspired it, Eat Pray Love is too shallow to resonate.

title: Eating Out
tomato_consensus: The cast recites lines of forced wit that aren't funny, and the clunky plot has too many contrivances.

title: Ed Wood
tomato_consensus: Tim Burton and Johnny Depp team up to fete the life and work of cult hero Ed Wood, with typically strange and wonderful results.

title: Eddie and the Cruisers II: Eddie Lives!
wiki_title: Eddie and the Cruisers II: Eddie Lives!

title: Edge of Darkness
tomato_consensus: For better and for worse, Edge of Darkness offers vintage Mel Gibson, working within the familiar framework of a bloody revenge thriller.

title: Edmond
tomato_consensus: Despite an electrifying performance by William H. Macy, David Mamet's one-act morality play translates poorly into a film that is overburdened by dialogue.

title: Educating Rita
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Edward Scissorhands
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The first collaboration between Johnny Depp and Tim Burton, Edward Scissorhands is a magical modern fairy tale with gothic overtones and a sweet center.

title: Eight Below
tomato_consensus: Featuring a stellar cast of marooned mutts, who deftly display emotion, tenderness, loyalty and resolve, Eight Below is a heartwarming and exhilarating adventure film.

title: Eight Legged Freaks
tomato_consensus: This homage to the B-movies of the '50s has a promising first half, but runs out of ideas in the second.

title: Eight Thousand Li of Cloud and Moon
wiki_title: Eight Thousand Li of Cloud and Moon

title: Ek Aur Ek Gyarah: By Hook or by Crook
Election
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 22 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Election successfully combines dark humor and intelligent writing in this very witty and enjoyable film.

title: Triad Election
tomato_consensus: Taking its cues from the Godfather series, Triad Election understands how a giddy mix of thrills and gunplay can make for compelling cinema.

title: Electra
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Electra Glide in Blue
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 nomination.

title: Electric Dreams
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Elegy
tomato_consensus: An intelligent, adult, and provocative Philip Roth adaptation that features classy performances, Elegy is never quite the sum of its parts.

title: Elektra
tomato_consensus: This comic book movie is an inert muddle that takes itself much too seriously.

title: Elephant
tomato_consensus: The movie's spare and unconventional style will divide viewers.

title: Elf
tomato_consensus: A movie full of Yuletide cheer, Elf is a spirited, good-natured family comedy, and it benefits greatly from Will Ferrell's funny and charming performance as one of Santa's biggest helpers.

title: Elite Squad
tomato_consensus: Brutal, action heavy, Brazilian cop film with a pointless voiceover. Lacks flair, overdoes the violence and is never quite sure where its morals lie.

title: Elite Squad: The Enemy Within
tomato_consensus: Elite Squad: The Enemy Within is a bleak, violent descent into the Brazilian underbelly, ripping into the favelas with unstoppable and kinetic force.

title: Elizabeth
tomato_consensus: No mere historical drama, Elizabeth is a rich, suspenseful journey into the heart of British Royal politics, and features a typically outstanding performance from Cate Blanchett.

title: Elizabethtown
tomato_consensus: This story of a floundering shoe designer who returns home for a family tragedy gets lost in undeveloped plot lines and lackluster performances.

title: Ella Enchanted
tomato_consensus: Hathaway is a charming heroine, but the simple storyline gets overwhelmed by silly gimmickry.

title: Elling
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Quirky without being overly cutesy, Elling is a gentle, warm comedy.

title: Elsa & Fred
tomato_consensus: Boosted by charming performances by the octogenarian leads, Elsa and Fred overcomes its schmaltzy premise to make for a satisfying romantic tale.

title: Elvis: That's the Way It Is
wiki_title: Elvis: That's the Way it Is

title: Elysium
tomato_consensus: After the heady sci-fi thrills of District 9, Elysium is a bit of a comedown for director Neill Blomkamp, but on its own terms, it delivers just often enough to satisfy.

title: Empire
tomato_consensus: In terms of the gangster genre, Empire's story is yet another tired retread.

title: Empire Records
tomato_consensus: Despite a terrific soundtrack and a strong early performance from Renee Zellweger, Empire Records is mostly a silly and predictable teen dramedy.

title: Empire of the Sun
awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Employee of the Month
tomato_consensus: Employee of the Month features mediocre performances, few laughs, and a lack of satiric bite.

title: Enchanted
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A smart re-imagining of fairy tale tropes that's sure to delight children and adults, Enchanted features witty dialogue, sharp animation, and a star turn by Amy Adams.

title: Enchanted April
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Mike Newell's adaptation of Elizabeth von Arnim's moves at a more generous pace than the 1935 version, allowing excellent performances from Miranda Richardson and Joan Plowright to flourish.

title: Encounters at the End of the World
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Encounters at the End of the World offers a poignant study of the human psyche amid haunting landscapes.
wiki_title: Encounters at the End of the World

title: End of Days
tomato_consensus: An overblown thriller with formulaic action scenes and poor acting.

title: End of Watch
tomato_consensus: End of Watch has the energy, devotion to characters, and charismatic performances to overcome the familiar pitfalls of its genre and handheld format.

title: End of the Spear
tomato_consensus: Shoddy filmmaking and a lack of character development derail what could be a potentially compelling tale.

title: Endless Love
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 9 nominations.

title: Enduring Love
tomato_consensus: While it strains credibility and isn't ultimately as profound as it might first appear, Enduring Love is still an intriguing thriller fueled by strong performances from Rhys Ifans and Daniel Craig.

title: Enemies: A Love Story
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Enemy at the Gates
tomato_consensus: Atmospheric and thrilling, Enemy at the Gates gets the look and feel of war right. However, the love story seems out of place.

title: Enemy of the State
tomato_consensus: An entertaining, topical thriller that finds director Tony Scott on solid form and Will Smith confirming his action headliner status.

title: Enigma
tomato_consensus: The well-crafted, twist-filled Enigma is a thinking person's spy thriller.

title: Enough
tomato_consensus: Enough exploits the serious issue of spousal abuse to make an illogical, unintelligent thriller.

title: Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
wiki_title: Enron: The Smartest Guys in the Room

title: Entrapment
tomato_consensus: A poorly developed plot weighs down any potential chemistry between the movie's leads.

title: Entre Nous
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Envy
tomato_consensus: Jack Black and Ben Stiller fail to wring laughs from a script that's essentially one extended poop joke.

title: Epic Movie
tomato_consensus: A crude comedy with nothing new or insightful to say about the subjects it satirizes.

title: Equilibrium
tomato_consensus: Equilibrium is a reheated mishmash of other sci-fi movies.

title: Equus
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Erased
tomato_consensus: Derivative to a fault, Erased squanders some nifty potential and its talented cast in a bland retelling of a story action fans have seen too many times before.

title: Eraser
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Eraserhead
tomato_consensus: David Lynch's surreal Eraserhead uses detailed visuals and a creepy score to create a bizarre and disturbing look into a man's fear of parenthood.

title: Erin Brockovich
tomato_consensus: Taking full advantage of Julia Roberts's considerable talent and appeal, Erin Brockovich overcomes a few character and plot issues to deliver a smart, thoughtful, and funny legal drama.

title: Eros
country: Hong Kong, USA, Italy, France, Luxembourg, UK

title: Escape Plan
tomato_consensus: As much fun as it is to see Sylvester Stallone and Arnold Schwarzenegger team up onscreen, Escape Plan fails to offer much more than a pale imitation of 1980s popcorn thrills.

title: Escape from New York
tomato_consensus: Featuring an atmospherically grimy futuristic metropolis, Escape from New York is a strange, entertaining jumble of thrilling action and oddball weirdness.

title: Escape from the Planet of the Apes
tomato_consensus: One of the better Planet of the Apes sequels, Escape is more character-driven than the previous films, and more touching as a result.
wiki_title: Escape from the Planet of the Apes

title: Lemon Popsicle
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 nomination.

title: Est - Ouest
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind
tomato_consensus: Propelled by Charlie Kaufman's smart, imaginative script and Michel Gondry's equally daring directorial touch, Eternal Sunshine is a twisty yet heartfelt look at relationships and heartache.
wiki_title: Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind

title: Eureka
tomato_consensus: With its subtitles and a running time nearing four hours, Eureka certainly places demands upon its viewers. For those with the patience, however, this visually lovely film builds to an emotionally resonant vision of transcendence.

title: Europa
country: Spain, Denmark, Sweden, France, Germany, Switzerland

title: Europa Europa
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Europa Report
tomato_consensus: Claustrophobic and stylish, Europa Report is a slow-burning thriller that puts the science back into science fiction.

title: Evan Almighty
tomato_consensus: Big on special effects but short on laughs, Evan Almighty underutilizes a star-studded cast that includes Steve Carell and Morgan Freeman.

title: Evelyn
tomato_consensus: Though predictable and sometimes overly sentimental, Evelyn still manages to be heartwarming.

title: Evening
tomato_consensus: Beautifully filmed, but decidedly dull, Evening is a collossal waste of a talented cast.

title: Ever After: A Cinderella Story
tomato_consensus: Ever After is a sweet, frothy twist on the ancient fable, led by a solid turn from star Barrymore.

title: Everlasting Moments
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 11 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Elegant and intimate, Everlasting Moments moves at the deliberate and gentle pace of a classical European period drama.

title: Every Little Step
tomato_consensus: Fascinating and insightful, Every Little Step is a thoroughly engrossing behind the scenes look at Broadway performers.

title: Everybody's Fine
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A calm, charismatic performance from Robert De Niro nearly saves the movie, but ultimately, Everybody's Fine has the look and feel of a stereotypical Christmas dramedy.

title: Everybody's Famous!
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though some critics consider Everybody Famous too lightweight to have deserved a slot among the Academy Awards foreign film nominations, this whacky satire of the cult of celebrity makes for loopy, cheerful fun.

title: Everyone's Hero
tomato_consensus: Everyone's Hero is such a predictable and bland tale that it'll appeal mostly to little kids; others seeking something in Pixar's league are looking in the wrong ballpark.

title: Everyone Says I Love You
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 13 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A likable, infectious musical, Woody Allen's Everyone Says I Love You is sometimes uneven but always toe-tapping and fun.

title: Everything's Gone Green
tomato_consensus: Set in beautifully photographed Vancouver, Everything's Gone Green is a winsome coming-of-age tale, thanks to a deft script by Douglas Coupland.

title: Everything Is Illuminated
tomato_consensus: Although it excises much from its famously dense source material, Everything is Illuminated is a quirky, ambitious debut film from Liev Schreiber.

title: Everything Must Go
tomato_consensus: It may not improve on the Raymond Carver short story that inspired it, but Everything Must Go resists cliche and boasts a pair of magnetic performances from the perfectly cast Ferrell and Wallace.

title: Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex * But Were Afraid to Ask
wiki_title: Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask)

title: Evil
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 9 nominations.

title: Evil Dead II
tomato_consensus: Evil Dead 2's increased special effects and slapstick-gore makes it as good -- if not better -- than the original.

title: Evolution
tomato_consensus: Director Reitman tries to remake Ghostbusters, but his efforts are largely unsuccessful because the movie has too many comedic misfires.

title: Exam
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Excalibur
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: John Boorman's operatic, opulent take on the legend of King Arthur is visually remarkable, and features strong performances from an all-star lineup of British thespians.

title: Executive Suite
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Exit Through the Gift Shop
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An amusing, engrossing look at underground art, Exit Through the Gift Shop entertains as it deflates the myths and hype surrounding its subjects.

title: Exit Wounds
tomato_consensus: It probably goes without saying that Exit Wounds is loaded with plotholes and bad dialogue. Critics also note that Seagal has aged rather badly.

title: Exorcist: The Beginning
tomato_consensus: A mediocre, gory horror film, nowhere near the quality of the 1973 original.

title: Expelled: No Intelligence Allowed
tomato_consensus: Full of patronizing, poorly structured arguments, Expelled is a cynical political stunt in the guise of a documentary.

title: Experiments in the Revival of Organisms
wiki_title: Experiments in the Revival of Organisms

title: Extract
tomato_consensus: Extract has some very funny moments and several fine performances, but the film feels slighter and more uneven than Mike Judge's previous work.

title: Extraordinary Measures
tomato_consensus: Despite a timely topic and a pair of heavyweight leads, Extraordinary Measures never feels like much more than a made-for-TV tearjerker.

title: Extreme Ops
tomato_consensus: The various stunts in Extreme Ops don't compensate for the inane storyline and bad dialogue.

title: Extremely Loud & Incredibly Close
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Extremely Loud & Incredibly Close has a story worth telling, but it deserves better than the treacly and pretentious treatment director Stephen Daldry gives it.

title: Eyes Wide Shut
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kubrick's intense study of the human psyche yields an impressive cinematic work.

title: Eyes Without a Face
tomato_consensus: A horrific tale of guilt and obsession, Eyes Without a Face is just as chilling and poetic today as it was in 1959.

title: L'enfant
tomato_consensus: The Dardennes continue to excel at presenting works of rigorous naturalism, with detached observations of authentic characters that nevertheless resonate with complex moral issues.

title: Les Enfants Terribles
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.

title: Star Wars: Episode V - The Empire Strikes Back
tomato_consensus: Dark, sinister, but ultimately even more involving than A New Hope, The Empire Strikes Back defies viewer expectations and takes the series to heightened emotional levels.
wiki_title: Star Wars Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back

title: The Eagle
tomato_consensus: The Eagle has a pleasantly traditional action-adventure appeal, but it's drowned out by Kevin Macdonald's stolid direction and Channing Tatum's uninspired work in the central role.

title: The Earrings of Madame de...
tomato_consensus: Oph?ls' graceful camerawork and visual portrayal of luxury and loss make Earrings a powerful French drama.

title: The East
tomato_consensus: Tense, thoughtful, and deftly paced, The East is a political thriller that never loses sight of the human element.

title: The Echo of Thunder
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 2 nominations.

title: The Eclipse
tomato_consensus: An intriguingly unusual ghost story, Conor McPherson's Eclipse blends supernatural suspense with romance to create a satisfying, character-driven whole.

title: The Edge of Heaven
tomato_consensus: Evocative and complex, this story of struggling immigrants in Germany will stay with you after you leave the theater.

title: The Edge of Love
tomato_consensus: Despite effective performances from Knightley and Miller, The Edge of Love lacks a coherent narrative.

title: The Education of Charlie Banks
tomato_consensus: Unevenness and earnestness mire this otherwise sweet, surprising coming of age drama.

title: The Edukators
tomato_consensus: The Edukators engagingly plays out the clash between youthful idealism and older pragmaticism.

title: The Eighth Day
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Elephant Man
awards: Nominated for 8 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: David Lynch's relatively straight second feature finds an admirable synthesis of compassion and restraint in treating its subject, and features outstanding performances by John Hurt and Anthony Hopkins.

title: The Emerald Forest
awards: Nominated for 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 nomination.

title: The Emigrants
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Emperor's Club
tomato_consensus: Though Kline is excellent in his portrayal of Hundert, the movie is too dull and sentimental to distinguish itself from other titles in its genre.

title: The Emperor's New Groove
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Emperor's New Groove isn't the most ambitious animated film, but its brisk pace, fresh characters, and big laughs make for a great time for the whole family.

title: Neon Genesis Evangelion: The End of Evangelion

wiki_title: The End of the Affair (1999 film)

title: The English Patient
tomato_consensus: Though it suffers from excessive length and ambition, director Minghella's adaptation of the Michael Ondaatje novel is complex, powerful, and moving.

title: The Englishman Who Went Up a Hill But Came Down a Mountain
wiki_title: The Englishman Who Went Up a Hill But Came Down a Mountain

title: The Entertainer
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Equation of Love and Death
wiki_title: The Equation of Love and Death

title: The Escapist
tomato_consensus: A tense, smart prison break movie, The Escapist is a sharp debut from director Rupert Wyatt.

title: The Evening Star
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Evil Dead
tomato_consensus: This classic low budget horror film combines just the right amount of gore and black humor, giving The Evil Dead an equal amount of thrills and laughs.

title: The Ex
tomato_consensus: The Ex suffers from inept direction and characters that are either unsympathetic or plain unpleasant to watch.

title: The Exorcist
tomato_consensus: The Exorcist rides its supernatural theme to magical effect, with remarkable special effects and an eerie atmosphere, resulting in one of the scariest films of all time.

title: The Expendables
tomato_consensus: It makes good on the old-school action it promises, but given all the talent on display, The Expendables should hit harder.

title: The Expendables 2
tomato_consensus: Taut, violent, and suitably self-deprecating, The Expendables 2 gives classic action fans everything they can reasonably expect from a star-studded shoot-'em-up -- for better and for worse.

title: The Express
tomato_consensus: This inspirational sports biopic set in the the civil rights era is interesting even for non-football fans, and features a great performance by Dennis Quaid as tough-but-fair football coach.

title: The Eye
tomato_consensus: Conventional ghost tale with a few genuine scares.

title: The Eye
tomato_consensus: Featuring wooden performances and minimal scares, The Eye is another tedious remake of an Asian horror film.

title: A Few Good Men
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 15 nominations.

title: A Fish Called Wanda
tomato_consensus: Smartly written, smoothly directed, and solidly cast, A Fish Called Wanda offers a classic example of a brainy comedy with widespread appeal.

title: Fistful of Dollars
tomato_consensus: With Akira Kurosawa's Yojimbo as his template, Sergio Leone's A Fistful of Dollars helped define a new era for the Western and usher in its most iconic star, Clint Eastwood.

title: A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum
wiki_title: A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum (film)

title: Face/Off
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: John Travolta and Nicolas Cage play cat-and-mouse (and literally play each other) against a beautifully stylized backdrop of typically elegant, over-the-top John Woo violence.

title: Faces
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Facing the Giants
tomato_consensus: The tropes of both football and evangelical movies are gracelessly on parade in this banal, insipid drama.

title: Factory Girl
tomato_consensus: Despite a dedicated performance by Sienna Miller, Factory Girl delves only superficially into her character, and ultimately fails to tell a coherent story.

title: Factotum
tomato_consensus: Matt Dillon's performance is the highlight of this somewhat slow but fascinating portrayal of Charles Bukowski's alter-ego.

title: Fahrenheit 451
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Fahrenheit 451 is an intriguing film that suffuses Truffaut's trademark wit and black humor with the intelligence and morality of Ray Bradbury's novel.

title: Fahrenheit 9/11
tomato_consensus: Extremely one-sided in its indictment of the Bush administration, but worth watching for the humor and the debates it'll stir.

title: Failure to Launch
tomato_consensus: The few comic gags sprinkled throughout the movie fail to spice up this formulaic rom-com.

title: Fair Game
tomato_consensus: It struggles with the balance between fact-based biopic and taut political thriller, but Fair Game brims with righteous anger -- and benefits from superb performances by Naomi Watts and Sean Penn.

title: Fallen
tomato_consensus: Has an interesting premise. Unfortunately, it's just a recycling of old materials, and not all that thrilling.

title: Fame
tomato_consensus: Fame is ultimately undone by its choppy editing, its incomplete characterizations, and its apparent desire to appeal to the High School Musical generation.

title: Family Plot
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Fanboys
tomato_consensus: This undercooked, sporadically funny road movie is a sop to Star Wars fanatics, but the uninitiated will find little to enjoy.

title: Fantasia
tomato_consensus: A landmark in animation (and a huge influence on the medium of music video), Disney's Fantasia is a relentlessly inventive blend of the classics with phantasmagorical images.

title: Fantasia/2000
tomato_consensus: It provides an entertaining experience for adults and children alike.

title: Fantastic 4: Rise of the Silver Surfer
tomato_consensus: While an improvement on its predecessor, Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer is nevertheless a juvenile, simplistic picture that has little benefit beyond its special effects.
wiki_title: Fantastic Four: Rise of the Silver Surfer

title: Fantastic Four
tomato_consensus: Fantastic Four is a goofy, mediocre entry in the superhero genre.

title: Fantastic Mr. Fox
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 30 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Fantastic Mr. Fox is a delightfully funny feast for the eyes with multi-generational appeal -- and it shows Wes Anderson has a knack for animation.

title: Fantastic Planet
tomato_consensus: Fantastic Planet is an animated epic that is by turns surreal and lovely, fantastic and graceful.

title: Fantastic Voyage
tomato_consensus: The special effects may be a bit dated today, but Fantastic Voyage still holds up well as an imaginative journey into the human body.

title: Far from Heaven
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 93 wins & 37 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An exquisitely designed and performed melodrama, Far From Heaven earns its viewers' tears with sincerity and intelligence.

title: Far from the Madding Crowd
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.
wiki_title: Far from the Madding Crowd (1967 film)

title: Faraway, So Close!
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Farewell My Concubine
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Chen Kaing's epic is grand in scope and presentation, and, bolstered by solid performances, the result is a film both horrifying and enthralling.

title: Fargo
tomato_consensus: Violent, quirky, and darkly funny, Fargo delivers an original crime story and a wonderful performance by McDormand.

title: Farinelli
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Fast and the Furious
tomato_consensus: Sleek and shiny on the surface, The Fast and the Furious recalls those cheesy teenage exploitation flicks of the 1950s.

title: Fast & Furious 6
tomato_consensus: With high-octane humor and terrific action scenes, Fast & Furious 6 builds upon the winning blockbuster formula that made Fast 5 a critical and commercial success.

title: Fast Five
tomato_consensus: Sleek, loud, and over the top, Fast Five proudly embraces its brainless action thrills and injects new life into the franchise.

title: Fast Food Nation
tomato_consensus: Despite some fine performances and memorable scenes, Fast Food Nation is more effective as Eric Schlosser's eye-opening non-fiction book than as Richard Linklater's fictionalized, mostly punchless movie.

title: Fast Times at Ridgemont High
tomato_consensus: While Fast Times at Ridgemont High features Sean Penn's legendary performance, the film endures because it accurately captured the small details of school, work, and teenage life.

title: Faster
tomato_consensus: It's good to see Dwayne Johnson back in full-throttle action mode, but Faster doesn't deliver enough of the high-octane thrills promised by its title.

title: Fat Albert
tomato_consensus: A bland but good-natured adaptation of the cartoon show.

title: Fat Girl
tomato_consensus: The controversial Fat Girl is an unflinchingly harsh but powerful look at female adolescence.

title: Fatal Attraction
awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A potboiler in the finest sense, Fatal Attraction is a sultry, juicy thriller that's hard to look away from once it gets going.

title: Fatal Fury: Legend of the Hungry Wolf
wiki_title: Fatal Fury: Legend of the Hungry Wolf

title: Fateless
tomato_consensus: Beautifully photographed and majestically scored, Fateless is a haunting account of one boy's experiences during the Holocaust and his journey to pick up the pieces in the war's aftermath.

title: Father of the Bride Part II
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
wiki_title: Father of the Bride Part II

title: Fay Grim
tomato_consensus: Fay Grim is too concerned with its own farcical premise to present a coherent, involving story.

title: Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas
tomato_consensus: Visually creative, but also aimless, repetitve, and devoid of character development.
wiki_title: Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas (film)

title: Fear and Trembling
tomato_consensus: This tale of culture clash is by turns downbeat and hilarious.

title: Feardotcom
tomato_consensus: As frustrating as a 404 error, Fear Dot Com is a stylish, incoherent, and often nasty mess with few scares.

title: Fearless
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This underrated gem from director Peter Weir features an outstanding performance from Jeff Bridges as a man dealing with profound grief.

title: Feast
tomato_consensus: Director Gulager makes the most of what he's given; the resulting Feast offers up some surprisingly tasty -- if far from nourishing -- morsels.

title: Feast of Love
tomato_consensus: Though beautifully photographed, Feast of Love offers little beyond a trite, melodramatic character drama.

title: Femme Fatale
tomato_consensus: The thriller Femme Fatale is overheated, nonsensical, and silly.

title: Ferris Bueller's Day Off
tomato_consensus: Matthew Broderick charms in Ferris Bueller's Day Off, a light and irrepressibly fun movie about being young and having fun.

title: Festival Express
tomato_consensus: Festival Express is a spellbinding documentary that nostalgically chronicles five days in the summer of 1970, when a train full of now- legendary rock perfomers jammed its way across Canada.

title: Festival in Cannes
tomato_consensus: One of Jaglom's better films, Festival in Cannes is an enjoyable insider's take on the movie industry.

title: Fever Pitch
tomato_consensus: While not a home run, Fever Pitch has enough charm and on-screen chemistry between the two leads to make it a solid hit.

title: Fido
tomato_consensus: Making the most of its thin premise, Fido is an occasionally touching satire that provides big laughs and enough blood and guts to please gorehounds.

title: Field of Dreams
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Field of Dreams is sentimental, but in the best way; it's a mix of fairy tale, baseball, and family togetherness.

title: Fight Club
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Solid acting, amazing direction, and elaborate production design make Fight Club a wild ride.

title: Fighting
tomato_consensus: Though Fighting has a likable lead performer, and the fight scenes are impressive, the paper-thin plot ultimately unravels.

title: Final Destination 2
tomato_consensus: This sequel is little more than an excuse to stage elaborate, gory scenes of characters getting killed off.

title: Final Destination
tomato_consensus: Despite a panel of X-Files' alums at the helm and a promising premise, flighty performances and poor execution keep Final Destination from ever taking off.

title: Final Destination 2
tomato_consensus: This sequel is little more than an excuse to stage elaborate, gory scenes of characters getting killed off.

title: Final Destination 3
tomato_consensus: Final Destination 3 is more of the same: gory and pointless, with nowhere new to go.

title: Final Destination 5
tomato_consensus: It's still only for the gore-thirsty faithful, but Final Destination 5 represents a surprising return to form for the franchise.

title: Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within
tomato_consensus: The movie raises the bar for computer animated movies, but the story is dull and emotionally removed.

title: Find Me Guilty
tomato_consensus: Find Me Guilty's excessive length and heavy-handed narrative keep it from reaching its full potential, but Vin Diesel's performance is well worth watching.

title: Finding Forrester
tomato_consensus: Despite the predictability of its plot and its similarity to Good Will Hunting, Finding Forrester has an honest, solid feel to it and good rapport between Connery and Brown.

title: Finding Neverland
tomato_consensus: It won't pass muster for those looking for historical accuracy, but Finding Neverland is a warm, heartfelt drama with a charm all its own -- and Johnny Depp gives a graceful performance as Peter Pan creator J.M. Barrie.

title: Finian's Rainbow
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.

title: Fired Up!
tomato_consensus: Though not as raunchy or juvenile as the average teen comedy, Fired Up is also not as funny.

title: Fireflies in the Garden
tomato_consensus: Despite boasting a stellar cast, Fireflies in the Garden is just tedious, dull and predictable melodrama. Instantly forgettable.

title: Firehouse Dog
tomato_consensus: Firehouse Dog's cute premise is ruined with endless fart and poop jokes, and an overlong run time.

title: Firewall
tomato_consensus: Harrison Ford's rote performance brings little to this uninspired techno-heist film whose formulaic plot is befuddled with tedious and improbable twists.

title: First Blood
tomato_consensus: A much darker, more sensitive film than the sequels it spawned, First Blood is a thrilling survival adventure, and the role of haunted Vietnam vet John Rambo takes full advantage of Sylvester Stallone's acting skills.

title: First Daughter
tomato_consensus: First Daughter is a bland and charmless fairy tale that fails to rise above the formula.

title: First Descent
tomato_consensus: This snowboarding doc scores with its dazzling array of snowboarding stunts and beautiful scenery, but loses points with shameless product placement and an overlong runtime.

title: First Men in the Moon
wiki_title: First Men in the Moon (1964 film)

title: First Monday in October
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 nomination.

title: Fish Tank
tomato_consensus: Cannes Jury Prize-winner Fish Tank is gritty British realism at its very best, with flawless performances from newcomer Kate Jarvis, and Michael Fassbender.

wiki_title: Fist of the North Star (1995 film)

title: Fitzcarraldo
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Killers
tomato_consensus: Dull, formulaic, and chemistry-free, Killers is an action/comedy that's largely bereft of thrills or laughs.

title: Flags of Our Fathers
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Flags of Our Fathers is both a fascinating look at heroism, both earned and manufactured, and a well-filmed salute to the men who fought at the battle of Iwo Jima.

title: Flash Gordon
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 win & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Campy charm and a knowing sense of humor help to overcome a silly plot involving a spacefaring ex-football player, his adoring bevy of groupies, and a supervillain named Ming the Merciless.

title: Flash of Genius
tomato_consensus: The touching underdog story of a single guy against a massive corporation, Flash of Genius is a well-paced and well-written tale with a standout performance by star Greg Kinnear.

title: Flashbacks of a Fool
tomato_consensus: Despite Daniel Craig's earnest efforts, Flashbacks of a Fool suffers from an ambitious but underdeveloped script.

title: Flawless
tomato_consensus: Michael Caine's excellent performance makes Flawless something more than an average heist movie.

title: Flesh Gordon Meets the Cosmic Cheerleaders
wiki_title: Flesh Gordon Meets the Cosmic Cheerleaders

title: Flicka
tomato_consensus: The rebellious protagonist will rally girls and children, but adults may find Flicka saddled with thin characters, over-the-top dialogue, and a plot that wanders into the countryside and never comes back.

title: Flight
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 11 wins & 31 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Robert Zemeckis makes a triumphant return to live-action cinema with Flight, a thoughtful and provocative character study propelled by a compelling performance from Denzel Washington.

title: Flight 93
awards: Won 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 2 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Flight of the Navigator
tomato_consensus: Bolstered by impressive special effects and a charming performance from its young star, Flight of the Navigator holds up as a solidly entertaining bit of family-friendly sci-fi.

title: Flight of the Phoenix
tomato_consensus: What this update lacks in tension, it makes up for with generic action.

title: Flightplan
tomato_consensus: The actors are all on key here, but as the movie progress, tension deflates as the far-fetched plot kicks in.

title: Flipped
tomato_consensus: While not without its nostalgic charms, Rob Reiner's sometimes awkward adaptation of Wendelin Van Draanen's childhood novel doesn't reach the heights of the director's earlier work like Stand By Me.

title: Flirting
tomato_consensus: A terrific follow-up to The Year My Voice Broke, Flirting is a teen movie worth watching, thanks to emotionally engaging performances and an endearing script.

title: Flirting with Disaster
tomato_consensus: Darkly funny, solidly cast, and surprisingly thoughtful, Flirting with Disaster proved David O. Russell's Spanking the Monkey was no fluke.

title: Floating Weeds
tomato_consensus: Floating Weeds boasts the visual beauty and deep tenderness of director Yasujiro Ozu's most memorable films -- and it's one of the few the master shot in color.

title: Flower Drum Song
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Flushed Away
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Clever and appealing for both children and adults, Flushed Away marks a successful entry into digital animated features for Aardman Animations.

title: Fly Away Home
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Fly Me to the Moon 3D
tomato_consensus: Flatly animated and indifferently scripted, Fly Me To the Moon offers little for audiences not comprised of very young children.

title: Flyboys
tomato_consensus: A poorly scripted history-rewriting exercise with mediocre acting and unconvincing CGI battle scenes.

title: Focus
tomato_consensus: Though full of good intentions, Focus somehow feels dated, and pounds away its points with a heavy hand.

title: Following
tomato_consensus: Super brief but efficient, Following represents director Christopher Nolan's burgeoning talent in tight filmmaking and hard-edge noir.

title: Food, Inc.
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An eye-opening expose of the modern food industry, Food, Inc. is both fascinating and terrifying, and essential viewing for any health-conscious citizen.

title: Fool's Gold
tomato_consensus: With little chemistry among the performers, humorless gags, and a predictable storyline, Fool's Gold fails on every level.

title: Footloose
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: There's not much dancing, but what's there is great. The rest of the time, Footloose is a nice hunk of trashy teenage cheese.

title: Footloose
tomato_consensus: While it hews closely to the 1984 original, Craig Brewer infuses his Footloose remake with toe-tapping energy and manages to keep the story fresh for a new generation.

title: Footnote
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 6 nominations.

awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 13 nominations.
wiki_title: For Love or Country: The Arturo Sandoval Story

title: For Your Consideration
tomato_consensus: As the object of satire gets bigger the jokes become thinner, and Christopher Guest isn't as droll or insightful here than when he was lampooning smaller subjects.

tomato_consensus: Brisk, funny, and sweetly raunchy, For a Good Time, Call... adds to the recent string of R-rated female comedies while serving as an overdue coming out party for the charming Ari Graynor.

wiki_title: Forbidden Love: The Unashamed Stories of Lesbian Lives

title: Forbidden Planet

wiki_title: Forklift Driver Klaus – The First Day on the Job

tomato_consensus: Filled with profanities, Formula 51 is a stylized and incoherent mess that doesn't add up to much.

tomato_consensus: Despite a strong cast, this sour holiday comedy suffers from a hackneyed script.

awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.
