title: The Fabulous Baker Boys
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 17 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its story is nothing special, but The Fabulous Baker Boys glows beneath luminous performances from its perfectly cast stars.

title: The Fall
tomato_consensus: More visually elaborate than the fragmented story can sometimes support, The Fall walks the line between labor of love and filmmaker self-indulgence.

title: The Fall of the House of Usher
wiki_title: The Fall of the House of Usher (1928 American film)

title: The Fall of the Roman Empire
wiki_title: The Fall of the Roman Empire (film)

title: The Fallen Idol
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Family Man
tomato_consensus: Despite good performances by Cage and especially by Leoni, The Family Man is too predictable and derivative to add anything new to the Christmas genre. Also, it sinks under its sentimentality.

title: The Family Stone
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This family holiday dramedy features fine performances but awkward shifts of tone.

title: The Family That Preys
tomato_consensus: Tyler Perry's The Family that Preys treads the filmmaker's established terrain of family loyalty and moral uprightness, though the occasionally predictable plot slides forward, aided by an excess of soapy melodrama.

title: The Farmer Takes a Wife
wiki_title: The Farmer Takes a Wife (1953 film)

title: The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift
tomato_consensus: Eye-popping driving sequences coupled with a limp story and flat performances make this Drift an adequate follow-up to the previous Fast and Furious installments. Strictly for the racing crowd and fans of the first two films.
wiki_title: The Fast and the Furious: Tokyo Drift

title: The Fast and the Furious
wiki_title: The Fast and the Furious (1955 film)

title: The Fast and the Furious
tomato_consensus: Sleek and shiny on the surface, The Fast and the Furious recalls those cheesy teenage exploitation flicks of the 1950s.
wiki_title: The Fast and the Furious (2001 film)

title: The Fearless Vampire Killers
tomato_consensus: This uneven but amiable 1967 vampire picture is part horror spoof, part central European epic, and 100 percent Roman Polanski, whose signature sensibility colors every frame.

title: The Fighter
tomato_consensus: Led by a trio of captivating performances from Mark Wahlberg, Christian Bale, and Amy Adams, The Fighter is a solidly entertaining, albeit predictable, entry in the boxing drama genre.

title: The Fighting Temptations
tomato_consensus: The music is the only saving grace in this predictable and eager-to-please comedy.

title: The Final Destination
tomato_consensus: With little of the ingenuity of previous installments, The Final Destination is predictable, disposable horror fare.

title: The Fine Art of Love: Mine Ha-Ha
wiki_title: The Fine Art of Love: Mine Ha-Ha

title: The Firm
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The First $20 Million Is Always the Hardest
wiki_title: The First $20 Million Is Always the Hardest

title: The First Men in the Moon
wiki_title: The First Men in the Moon (1919 film)

title: The First Wives Club
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Fisher King
tomato_consensus: An odd but affecting mixture of drama, comedy and fantasy, The Fisher King manages to balance moving performances from Robin Williams and Jeff Bridges with director Terry Gilliam's typically askew universe.

title: The Five-Year Engagement
tomato_consensus: While certainly overlong, The Five-Year Engagement benefits from the easy chemistry of its leads and a funny, romantic script with surprising depth and intelligence.

title: The Flag: A Story Inspired by the Tradition of Betsy Ross
wiki_title: The Flag: A Story Inspired by the Tradition of Betsy Ross

title: The Flight of the Phoenix
wiki_title: The Flight of the Phoenix (1965 film)

title: The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas
tomato_consensus: The prequel to the first full-length feature set in Bedrock, Viva Rock Vegas is a surprising improvement over The Flintstones. Aimed towards an audience of adults and children alike, critics feel Viva will appeal to a broad range of viewers.
wiki_title: The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas

title: The Flowers of War
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 10 nominations.

title: The Fly
tomato_consensus: Deliciouly funny to some and eerily presicient to others, The Fly walks a fine line between shlocky fun and unnerving nature parable.

title: The Fly
tomato_consensus: David Cronenberg combines his trademark affinity for gore and horror with strongly developed characters, making The Fly a surprisingly affecting tragedy.

title: The Fog
tomato_consensus: The Fog is a so-so remake of a so-so movie, lacking scares, suspense or originality.

title: The Fog of War: Eleven Lessons from the Life of Robert S. McNamara
wiki_title: The Fog of War: Eleven Lessons from the Life of Robert S. McNamara

title: The Forbidden Kingdom
tomato_consensus: This hotly-anticipated pairing of martial arts legends Jackie Chan and Jet Li features dazzling fight scenes but is weighed down by too much filler.

title: The Forgotten
tomato_consensus: The premise grows too ridiculous to take seriously.

title: The Forsaken
tomato_consensus: It's all been done before, and done better.

title: The Fountain
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Fountain -- a movie about metaphysics, universal patterns, Biblical symbolism, and boundless love spread across one thousand years -- is visually rich but suffers from its own unfocused ambitions.

title: The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse
wiki_title: The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse (film)

title: The Fox and the Hound
tomato_consensus: The Fox and the Hound is a likeable, charming, unassuming effort that manages to transcend its thin, predictable plot.

title: The French Connection
tomato_consensus: Realistic, fast-paced and uncommonly smart, The French Connection is bolstered by stellar performances by Gene Hackman and Roy Scheider, not to mention William Friedkin's thrilling production.

title: The French Lieutenant's Woman
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 13 nominations.

title: The Front
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: The Front Page
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Fugitive
tomato_consensus: Exhilarating and intense, this high-impact chase thriller is a model of taut and efficient formula filmmaking, and it features Harrison Ford at his frantic best.

title: The Future
tomato_consensus: A dark and whimsical exploration of human existence that challenges viewers as much as it rewards them.

title: A Glimpse Inside the Mind of Charles Swan III
wiki_title: A Glimpse Inside the Mind of Charles Swan III

title: A Good Old Fashioned Orgy
tomato_consensus: Its titillating title promises ribald laughs, but the lazily written, indifferently acted, and only sporadically funny A Good Old Fashioned Orgy fails to consummate.

title: A Good Woman
tomato_consensus: This adaptation of Wilde's Lady Windermere's Fan lacks bite due to liberties taken with the source material, coupled with uneven performances.

title: A Good Year
tomato_consensus: A Good Year is a fine example of a top-notch director and actor out of their elements, in a sappy romantic comedy lacking in charm and humor.

title: A Grand Day Out
wiki_title: A Grand Day Out with Wallace and Gromit

title: A Guide for the Married Man
wiki_title: A Guide for the Married Man

title: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints
tomato_consensus: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints is a lively, powerful coming-of-age tale with winning performances and sharp direction from first-timer Dito Montiel.
wiki_title: A Guide to Recognizing Your Saints (film)

title: A Guy Thing
tomato_consensus: Wasting the talent of its leads, this predictable romantic comedy relies on cheap laughs.

title: Elizabeth: The Golden Age
tomato_consensus: This sequel is full of lavish costumes and elaborate sets, but lacks the heart and creativity of the original Elizabeth

title: G.I. Joe: Retaliation
tomato_consensus: Though arguably superior to its predecessor, G.I. Joe: Retaliation is overwhelmed by its nonstop action and too nonsensical and vapid to leave a lasting impression.

title: G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra
tomato_consensus: While fans of the Hasbro toy franchise may revel in a bit of nostalgia, G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra is largely a cartoonish, over-the-top action fest propelled by silly writing, inconsistent visual effects, and merely passable performances.
wiki_title: G.I. Joe: The Rise of Cobra

title: Gabrielle
tomato_consensus: Patrice Ch?reau's exquisite rendering of Joseph Conrad's The Return brings underlying passions to surface in a long-suffering marriage.

title: Galaxy Quest
tomato_consensus: Intelligent and humorous satire with an excellent cast -- no previous Trekkie knowledge needed to enjoy this one.

title: Gallipoli
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 11 wins & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Peter Weir's devastating anti-war film features a low-key but emotionally wrenching performance from Mel Gibson as a young soldier fighting in one of World War I's most deadly and horrifying battles.

title: Gambit
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: Goodbye Bruce Lee: His Last Game of Death
Gamer
tomato_consensus: With all of the hyperkinetic action and none of the flair of Mark Neveldine and Brian Taylor's earlier work, Gamer has little replay value.

title: Gandhi
tomato_consensus: Director Richard Attenborough is typically sympathetic and sure-handed, but it's Ben Kingsley's magnetic performance that acts as the linchpin for this sprawling, lengthy biopic.

title: Gangs of New York
awards: Nominated for 10 Oscars. Another 44 wins & 63 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though flawed, the sprawling, messy Gangs of New York is redeemed by impressive production design and Day-Lewis's electrifying performance.

title: Gangster No. 1
tomato_consensus: Gangster No. 1 is brutally violent, yet also compelling.

title: Gangster Squad
tomato_consensus: Though it's stylish and features a talented cast, Gangster Squad suffers from lackluster writing, underdeveloped characters, and an excessive amount of violence.

title: Garden State
tomato_consensus: Delivering a quirky spin on familiar twentysomething tropes -- with a cannily-placed soundtrack -- Garden State has enough charm to mark a winning debut for first-time director Zach Braff.

title: Garfield 2
tomato_consensus: Strictly for (very) little kids, A Tale of Two Kitties features skilled voice actors but a plot that holds little interest.
wiki_title: Garfield: A Tale of Two Kitties

title: Garfield
tomato_consensus: When the novelty of the CGI Garfield wears off, what's left is a simplistic kiddie movie.

title: Gas! -Or- It Became Necessary to Destroy the World in Order to Save It.
Gattaca
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Intelligent and scientifically provocative, Gattaca is an absorbing sci fi drama that poses important interesting ethical questions about the nature of science.

title: General Idi Amin Dada
wiki_title: General Idi Amin Dada: A Self Portrait

title: General Della Rovere
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Genevieve
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Gentleman's Agreement
tomato_consensus: It occasionally fails to live up to its subject matter -- and is perhaps an 'important' film more than a 'great' one -- but the performances from Gregory Peck and Dorothy McGuire are superb.

title: Gentlemen Broncos
tomato_consensus: Unselfconsciously juvenile and overwhelmingly quirky, Gentlemen Broncos offers a lot of potty humor but isn't terribly funny.

title: Gentlemen Prefer Blondes
tomato_consensus: Anchored by Marilyn Monroe and Jane Russell's sparkling magnetism, Gentlemen Prefer Blondes is a delightfully entertaining 1950s musical.

title: George Wallace
awards: Won 2 Golden Globes. Another 15 wins & 20 nominations.

title: George of the Jungle
tomato_consensus: George of the Jungle is faithful to its source material -- which, unfortunately, makes it a less-than-compelling feature film.

title: Georgia
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Georgia Rule
tomato_consensus: Comedic and dramatic in all the wrong places, Georgia Rule is a confused dramedy that wastes the talents of its fine cast.

title: Georgy Girl
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 13 nominations.

title: Gerry
tomato_consensus: The type of uncompromising film that divides filmgoers over whether it is profound or pretentious.

title: Gervaise
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Get Carter
tomato_consensus: A remake that doesn't approach the standard of the original, Get Carter will likely leave viewers confused and unsatisfied. Also, reviews are mixed concerning Stallone's acting.

title: Get Him to the Greek
tomato_consensus: Thanks to a suitably raunchy script and a pair of winning performances from Jonah Hill and Russell Brand, Get Him to the Greek is one of the year's funniest comedies.

title: Get Low
tomato_consensus: Subtle to a fault, this perfectly cast ensemble drama is lifted by typically sharp performances from Robert Duvall and Bill Murray.

title: Get Over It
tomato_consensus: As with most teen movies, Get Over It is entirely predictable, and there's not enough plot to sustain the length of the movie. However, it is not without its charms.

title: Get Real
tomato_consensus: An authentic portrayal of homosexuality in high school, Get Real is an engaging dramedy that doesn't sermonize its audience nor trivialize its characters.

title: Get Rich or Die Tryin'
tomato_consensus: While it may be based upon 50 Cent's own life experiences, Get Rich Or Die Tryin' is too similar to many other rags-to-riches stories to resonate.
wiki_title: Get Rich or Die Tryin' (2005 film)

title: Get Shorty
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 7 wins & 11 nominations.

title: Get Smart
tomato_consensus: Get Smart rides Steve Carell's considerable charm for a few laughs, but in the end is a rather ordinary Summer comedy.

title: Getaway
tomato_consensus: Monotonously fast-paced to the point of exhaustion, Getaway offers a reminder of the dangers in attempting to speed past coherent editing, character development, sensible dialogue, and an interesting plot.

title: Getting Even with Dad
tomato_consensus: Overly formulaic and tonally inconsistent, Getting Even with Dad tries for a sentimental conclusion it doesn't earn and winds up a slapsticky cash grab aimed at fans of Home Alone.

title: Ghost Dad
tomato_consensus: A startlingly misconceived effort from director Sidney Poitier and star Bill Cosby, Ghost Dad is a listless, glacially-paced comedy that's alternately schmaltzy and incomprehensible.

title: Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai
tomato_consensus: An innovative blend of samurai and gangster lifestyles.
wiki_title: Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai

title: Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance
tomato_consensus: With a weak script, uneven CG work, and a Nic Cage performance so predictably loony it's no longer amusing, Ghost Rider: Spirit of Vengeance aims to be trashy fun but ends up as plain trash.

title: Ghost Rider
tomato_consensus: Ghost Rider is a sour mix of morose, glum histrionics amidst jokey puns and hammy dialogue.

title: Ghost Ship
tomato_consensus: With a plot as creaky as the boat, Ghost Ship fails to deliver the scares.

title: Ghost Town
tomato_consensus: Ricky Gervais' consistently sharp performance and beautifully dry execution transform this otherwise mainstream comedy into an endearing, funny, and altogether snappy romantic comedy. With ghosts.

title: Ghost World
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 35 wins & 35 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With acerbic wit, Terry Zwigoff fashions Daniel Clowes' graphic novel into an intelligent, comedic trip through deadpan teen angst.

title: Ghost in the Shell
tomato_consensus: A stunning feat of modern animation, Ghost in the Shell offers a thoughtful, complex treat for anime fans, as well as a perfect introduction for viewers new to the genre.

title: Ghost in the Shell 2: Innocence
tomato_consensus: The animation is lovely, but the plot is complex to the point of inscrutability, leaving Ghost in the Shell 2: Innocence both original and numbing.

title: Ghostbusters
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An infectiously fun blend of special effects and comedy, with Bill Murray's hilarious deadpan performance leading a cast of great comic turns.

title: Ghostbusters II
tomato_consensus: Thanks to the cast, Ghostbusters 2 is reasonably amusing, but it lacks the charm, wit, and energy of its predecessor.

title: Ghosts of Girlfriends Past
tomato_consensus: A retread of A Christmas Carol, featuring Matthew McConaughey in a retread of his Dazed and Confused role, Ghosts of Girlfriends Past lacks originality, humor, and any semblance of charm.

title: Ghosts of Mars
tomato_consensus: John Carpenter's Ghosts of Mars is not one of Carpenter's better movies, filled as it is with bad dialogue, bad acting, confusing flashbacks, and scenes that are more campy than scary.

title: Ghosts of Mississippi
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Ghosts of the Abyss
tomato_consensus: The underwater footage is both beautiful and awe-inspiring.

title: Gigantic (A Tale of Two Johns)
tomato_consensus: A clever, absorbing documentary about They Might Be Giants, a musical duo whose brainy, idiosyncratic brand of pop has earned them decades of cult success.

title: Gigantic
tomato_consensus: This overly quirky, incessantly whimsical indie is too self-conscious for its own good.

title: Gigi
tomato_consensus: It may not be one of Minnelli's best, but the charming and flawlessly acted Gigi still offers enough visual and musical treats to satisfy.

title: Ginger Snaps
tomato_consensus: The strong female cast and biting satire of teenage life makes Ginger Snaps far more memorable than your average werewolf movie -- or teen flick.

title: Ginger and Fred
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 13 wins & 15 nominations.

title: Girl, Interrupted
tomato_consensus: Critics praise Angelina Jolie's intense performance, but overall they say the movie suffers from flatness of storyline, inability to bring the true spirit of the book to screen, and a diminuative performance by Ryder.

title: Girl Most Likely
tomato_consensus: Largely witless and disappointingly dull, Girl Most Likely strands the gifted Kristen Wiig in a blandly hollow foray into scattershot sitcom territory.

title: The Girl on the Bridge
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 15 nominations.

title: Girl with a Pearl Earring
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 35 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Visually arresting, but the story could be told with a bit more energy.

title: Girlfight
tomato_consensus: Michelle Rodriguez gives a compelling performance, despite lack of a boxing background; Karyn Kusama packs a punch with this directorial debut.

title: Girlfriends
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Girls! Girls! Girls!
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins.

title: Girls Just Want to Have Fun
wiki_title: Girls Just Want to Have Fun (film)

title: Gladiator
tomato_consensus: Ridley Scott and an excellent cast successfully convey the intensity of Roman gladitorial combat as well as the political intrigue brewing beneath.

title: Glengarry Glen Ross
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This adaptation of David Mamet's play is every bit as compelling and witty as its source material, thanks in large part to a clever script and a bevy of powerhouse actors.

title: Glitter
tomato_consensus: Glitter is a hodgepodge of movie cliches and bad acting that's sure to generate unintentional laughs. Unfortunately, the movie is not bad enough to be good.

title: Gloomy Sunday
tomato_consensus: Gloomy Sunday is beautiful, well-acted, and every bit as downcast as its title.

title: Gloria
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Glory
tomato_consensus: Bolstered by exceptional cinematography, powerful storytelling, and an Oscar-winning performance by Denzel Washington, Glory remains one of the finest Civil War movies ever made.

title: Gnomeo & Juliet
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While it has moments of inspiration, Gnomeo and Juliet is often too self-referential for its own good.

title: Go
tomato_consensus: With its sharp dialogue and raucous visuals, Go entertains at an exhilarating pace.

title: Goal! The Dream Begins
tomato_consensus: Impressive sports action sequences are the highlight, as the run-of the-mill story invokes every known sports movie cliche.

title: God Bless America
tomato_consensus: A darkly comic polemic on modern culture, God Bless America is uneven and somewhat this but the ideas behind this revenge fulfillment journey has primal appeal.

title: God Grew Tired of Us
tomato_consensus: Not just a powerful telling of the journey of exiled Sudanese boys, God Grew Tired of Us is also a poignant account of the determination of the human spirit.

title: God Sleeps in Rwanda
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Gods and Generals
tomato_consensus: Filled with two-dimensional characters and pompous self-righteousness, Gods and Generals is a long, tedious sit. Some may also take offense at the pro-Confederate slant.

title: Gods and Monsters
tomato_consensus: Gods and Monsters is a spellbinding, confusing piece of semi-fiction, featuring fine performances; McKellen leads the way, but Redgrave and Fraser don't lag far behind.

title: Godspell: A Musical Based on the Gospel According to St. Matthew
Godzilla, Mothra and King Ghidorah: Giant Monsters All-Out Attack
wiki_title: Godzilla, Mothra and King Ghidorah: Giant Monsters All-Out Attack

title: Godzilla
tomato_consensus: More than straight monster-movie fare, Gojira offers potent, sobering postwar commentary.

title: Going My Way
tomato_consensus: Bing Crosby and Barry Fitzgerald are eminently likable, and film is pleasantly sentimental, but it suffers from a surplus of sweetness.

title: Going Upriver: The Long War of John Kerry
tomato_consensus: Interesting and revealing footage of both Kerry and the Vietnam era in general.

title: Going the Distance
tomato_consensus: It's timelier and a little more honest than most romantic comedies, but Drew Barrymore and Justin Long's screen chemistry doesn't make up for Going the Distance's overall flatness.

title: GoldenEye
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The first and best Pierce Brosnan Bond film, GoldenEye brings the series into a more modern context, and the result is a 007 entry that's high-tech, action-packed, and urbane.

title: Goldfinger
tomato_consensus: Goldfinger is where James Bond as we know him comes into focus - it features one of 007's most famous lines ("A martini. Shaken, not stirred") and a wide range of gadgets that would become the series' trademark.

title: Gomorrah
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 23 wins & 22 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Portraying organised crime with an unflinching realism, this gritty and searing Italian crime masterpiece pulls no punches.

title: Gone Baby Gone
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 23 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Ben Affleck proves his directing credentials in this gripping dramatic thriller, drawing strong performances from the excellent cast and bringing working-class Boston to the screen.

title: Gone Fishin'
tomato_consensus: Sloppy, formulaic, and unfunny, Gone Fishin' marks a painful low point in the careers of its two talented leads.

title: Gone in Sixty Seconds
tomato_consensus: Even though Oscar-bearers Nicolas Cage, Angelina Jolie, and Robert Duval came aboard for this project, the quality of Gone in 60 Seconds is disappointingly low. The plot line is nonsensical, and even the promised car-chase scenes are boring.

title: Gone with the Wind
tomato_consensus: Filmed and presented on a scale not seen in modern productions, Gone with the Wind is, if not the definitive Hollywood film, then certainly near the top of the list.

title: Good Boy!
tomato_consensus: Good Boy! should appeal to kids. Adults, however, might consider it a dog.

title: Good Bye Lenin!
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 32 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Funny and poignant social critique of German reunification.

title: Good Deeds
tomato_consensus: Tyler Perry's craftmanship as a director continues to improve, but his stories are still the same ol' hoary, pretentious melodramas.

title: Good Dick
tomato_consensus: Marianna Palka's quirky indie debut centred on two dysfunctional loners is hit and miss, but has enough originality to see it through.

title: Good Hair
tomato_consensus: Funny, informative, and occasionally sad, Good Hair is a provocative look at the complex relationship between African Americans and their hair.

title: Good Luck Chuck
tomato_consensus: A shortage of laughs and an undercurrent of mean-spiritedness undermine Good Luck Chuck, squandering a decent premise on gross-out humor and shopworn slapstick.

title: Good Morning, Vietnam
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Good Neighbor Sam
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.

title: Good Night, and Good Luck.
awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 43 wins & 65 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A passionate and concise cinematic civics lesson, Good Night, And Good Luck has plenty to say about today's political and cultural climate, and its enseble cast is stellar.

title: Good Will Hunting
tomato_consensus: It follows a predictable narrative arc, but Good Will Hunting adds enough quirks to the journey -- and is loaded with enough powerful performances -- that it remains an entertaining, emotionally rich drama.

title: Goodbye, Columbus
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Goodbye, Mr. Chips
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Goodbye Lover
tomato_consensus: Half-baked plot twists disorient rather than build drama.

title: Goodfellas
tomato_consensus: Hard-hitting and stylish, GoodFellas is a gangster classic -- and arguably the high point of Martin Scorsese's career.

title: Goon
tomato_consensus: Goon is a crude slapstick comedy with well-formed characters and a surprising amount of heart.

title: Gorillas in the Mist
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 4 nominations.
wiki_title: Gorillas in the Mist: The Story of Dian Fossey

title: Gorky Park
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Gosford Park
tomato_consensus: A mixture of Upstairs, Downstairs, Clue, and perceptive social commentary, Gosford Park ranks among director Altman's best.

title: Gossip
tomato_consensus: Gossip drags on far beyond its entertainment value.

title: Gothika
tomato_consensus: Berry's acting talents can't save Gothika from its preposterous plot and bad dialogue.

title: Goya's Ghosts
tomato_consensus: Ornate costumes and a talented cast can't make up for Ghosts' glacial pace and confused plot.

title: Gozu
tomato_consensus: Miike continues his run of compellingly bizarre flicks.

title: Grace
tomato_consensus: Though not entirely effective as a conventional horror flick, Grace is still a graphic, disturbing, and artful exploration of twisted maternal instinct.

title: Grace Is Gone
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A refreshing departure from the current crop of Iraq war dramas, Grace is Gone is a heartfelt, finely acted portrayal of grief and healing.

title: Gran Torino
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 20 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though a minor entry in Eastwood's body of work, Gran Torino is nevertheless a humorous, touching, and intriguing old-school parable.

title: Grand Canyon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk
wiki_title: Grand Canyon Adventure: River at Risk

title: Grand Hotel
tomato_consensus: Perhaps less a true film than a series of star-studded vignettes, Grand Hotel still remains an entertaining look back at a bygone Hollywood era.

title: La Grande Illusion
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Grandma's Boy
tomato_consensus: A gross-out comedy that's more gross than comedic, Grandma's Boy is lazy and unrewarding.

title: Grass: A Nation's Battle for Life
Grave of the Fireflies
tomato_consensus: An achingly sad anti-war film, Grave of the Fireflies is one of Studio Ghibli's most profoundly beautiful, haunting works.

title: Gravity
tomato_consensus: Alfonso Cuar?n's Gravity is an eerie, tense sci-fi thriller that's masterfully directed and visually stunning.

title: Gray Matters
tomato_consensus: Gray Matters tries emulating Hollywood screwball classics, but the rapid fire dialogue and witticisms comes off only as a contrived gimmick.

title: Grease
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Grease is a pleasing, energetic musical with infectiously catchy songs and an ode to young love that never gets old.

title: Great Expectations
tomato_consensus: Great Expectations is all surface tension: beautiful people shot in beautiful locations without any depth or emotion.

title: Great Expectations
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Not the best version of the oft-filmed Dickens classic but far from the worst, Mike Newell's Great Expectations breathes just enough life into the source material to justify yet another adaptation.

title: Green Card
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Green Lantern
tomato_consensus: Noisy, overproduced, and thinly written, Green Lantern squanders an impressive budget and decades of comics mythology.

title: Green Street Hooligans
tomato_consensus: When it comes to the subculture of soccer thugs, Green Street Hooligans lacks sufficient insight, and instead comes off as a Fight Club knock-off.

title: Green Zone
tomato_consensus: Matt Damon and Paul Greengrass return to the propulsive action and visceral editing of the Bourne films -- but a cliched script and stock characters keep those methods from being as effective this time around.

title: Greenberg
tomato_consensus: Greenberg's title character is harder to like than most, but Ben Stiller's nuanced performance and a darkly funny script help take the misanthropic edge off.

title: Greenfingers
tomato_consensus: Greenfingers follows the British feel-good formula of underdogs somehow beating the odds, adding nothing new to this already saturated genre.

title: Gregory's Girl
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: Gremlins
tomato_consensus: Whether you choose to see it as a statement on consumer culture or simply a special effects-heavy popcorn flick, Gremlins is a minor classic.

title: Greystoke: The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 11 nominations.
wiki_title: Greystoke - The Legend of Tarzan, Lord of the Apes

title: Gridiron Gang
tomato_consensus: The role of probation officer Sean Porter fits Dwayne "The Rock" Johnson like a glove; however, the execution is so cliched, the youths' stories (based on real events), fail to inspire.

title: Grind
tomato_consensus: Mediocre skateboard stunts are padded by a half-baked plot and one-dimensional characters.

title: Grindhouse
tomato_consensus: Grindhouse delivers exhilarating exploitation fare with wit and panache, improving upon its source material with feral intelligence.

title: Grizzly Man
tomato_consensus: Whatever opinion you come to have of the obsessive Treadwell, Herzog has once again found a fascinating subject.

title: Groove
tomato_consensus: Though high on energy and great techno tunes, Groove's characters and plotlines are too cliched to be engaging.

title: Groundhog Day
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Smart, sweet, and inventive, Groundhog Day highlights Murray's dramatic gifts while still leaving plenty of room for laughs.

title: Grown Ups
tomato_consensus: Grown Ups' cast of comedy vets is amiable, but they're let down by flat direction and the scattershot, lowbrow humor of a stunted script.

title: Grown Ups 2
tomato_consensus: While it's almost certainly the movie event of the year for filmgoers passionate about deer urine humor, Grown Ups 2 will bore, annoy, and disgust audiences of nearly every other persuasion.

title: Grudge Match
tomato_consensus: Grudge Match is sporadically funny but meandering, and its strong cast largely mired in a plot that's overrun with clich?s.

title: Che: Part Two
tomato_consensus: The second part of Soderbergh's biopic is a dark, hypnotic and sometimes frustrating portrait of a warrior in decline, with a terrific central performance from Del Toro.

title: Guess Who
tomato_consensus: Despite the chemistry of its stars, Guess Who, a loose remake of Guess Who's Coming to Dinner, lacks the political relevance of the original.

title: Gulliver's Travels
tomato_consensus: Though Jack Black is back doing what he does best, Gulliver's Travels largely fails to do any justice to its source material, relying instead on juvenile humor and special effects.

title: Gumshoe
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 win.

title: Gun Shy
tomato_consensus: A dark comedy of the low brow nature -- filled with fart and gay jokes. Even Liam Neeson and Sandra Bullock cannot save this failure.

title: Gunfight at the O.K. Corral
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Primeval
tomato_consensus: Primeval is a low-quality horror film, which due to the inane political messages does not even qualify as campy fun.

title: Guyana Tragedy: The Story of Jim Jones
wiki_title: Guyana Tragedy: The Story of Jim Jones

title: Guys and Dolls
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Gypsy
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Gypsy 83
tomato_consensus: This coming-of-age story of alienated youth is too familiar.

title: Le grand voyage
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 wins & 2 nominations.

title: The Game
tomato_consensus: The ending could use a little work but this is otherwise another sterling example of David Fincher's iron grip on atmosphere and storytelling.

title: The Game Plan
tomato_consensus: Despite The Rock's abundant charisma, The Game Plan is just another run-of-the-mill Disney comedy.

title: The Game of Their Lives
tomato_consensus: An enthusiastic but ultimately uninspired soccer film.
wiki_title: The Game of Their Lives (2005 film)

title: The Gang That Couldn't Shoot Straight
wiki_title: The Gang That Couldn't Shoot Straight

title: The General's Daughter
tomato_consensus: Contrived performances and over-the-top sequences offer little real drama.

title: The General
tomato_consensus: Brilliantly filmed and fueled with classic physical comedy, The General captures Buster Keaton at his timeless best.

title: The Getaway
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.

title: The Ghost
tomato_consensus: While it may lack the revelatory punch of Polanski's finest films, Ghost Writer benefits from stylish direction, a tense screenplay, and a strong central performance from Ewan McGregor.

title: The Gift
tomato_consensus: With a reported budget of around 10 million, The Gift is obviously a labor of love for those involved. Unfortunately, the A-list cast can't prevent the movie from becoming a by-the-numbers whodunit with an ending that's all but unsatisfactory.

title: The Girl in the Park
tomato_consensus: Sigourney Weaver delivers a towering performance in this poignant meditation on unresolved grief.

title: The Girl Next Door
tomato_consensus: The movie borrows heavily from Risky Business, though Hirsch and Cuthbert are appealing leads.

title: The Girl Who Kicked the Hornets' Nest
tomato_consensus: Slow and mostly devoid of the stellar chemistry between its two leads, The Girl Who Kicked The Hornet's Nest is a disappointingly uneven conclusion to the Millennium trilogy.
wiki_title: The Girl Who Kicked the Hornets' Nest (film)

title: The Girl Who Knew Too Much
wiki_title: The Girl Who Knew Too Much (1969 film)

title: The Girl Who Leapt Through Time
tomato_consensus: An imaginative and thoughtfully engaging anime film with a highly effective visual design. This coming-of-age comedy drama has mad inventiveness to spare.
wiki_title: The Girl Who Leapt Through Time (2006 film)

title: The Girl Who Played with Fire
tomato_consensus: Noomi Rapace and Michael Nyqvist remain extraordinarily well-suited to their roles, but the second installment in Stieg Larsson's Millennium Trilogy doesn't pack quite as much punch as the first.
wiki_title: The Girl Who Played with Fire (film)

title: The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 12 wins & 22 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its graphic violence and sprawling length will prove too much for some viewers to take, but Noomi Rapace's gripping performance makes The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo an unforgettable viewing experience.
wiki_title: The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2009 film)

title: The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo
tomato_consensus: Brutal yet captivating, The Girl With the Dragon Tattoo is the result of David Fincher working at his lurid best with total role commitment from star Rooney Mara.
wiki_title: The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (2011 film)

title: The Girlfriend Experience
tomato_consensus: Steven Soderbergh's latest lo-fi production is strikingly crafted but emotionally vague.

title: The Glass House
tomato_consensus: Due to obvious plot twists and foreshadowing, The Glass House fails to thrill. By the end, it degenerates into ludicrousness.

title: The Go-Between
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 10 nominations.

title: The Goalie's Anxiety at the Penalty Kick
wiki_title: The Goalkeeper's Fear of the Penalty

title: The Godfather
tomato_consensus: One of Hollywood's greatest critical and commercial successes, The Godfather gets everything right; not only did the movie transcend expectations, it established new benchmarks for American cinema.

title: The Godfather: Part II
tomato_consensus: Drawing on strong performances by Al Pacino and Robert De Niro, Francis Ford Coppola's continuation of Mario Puzo's Mafia saga set new standards for sequels that have yet to be matched or broken.

title: The Godfather: Part III
awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 13 nominations.

title: The Gold Rush
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Golden Bowl
tomato_consensus: Coming from the Merchant-Ivory team, The Golden Bowl is visually stunning, but the filmmakers have difficulty in transporting the characterizations of the Henry James novel to the screen.

title: The Golden Compass
tomato_consensus: Without the bite or the controversy of the source material, The Golden Compass is reduced to impressive visuals overcompensating for lax storytelling.

title: The Golem
wiki_title: The Golem: How He Came Into the World

title: The Good, the Bad, the Weird
tomato_consensus: Whilst never taking itself too seriously, this riotous and rollicking Sergio Leone-inspired Korean Western is serious fun.
wiki_title: The Good, the Bad, the Weird

title: The Good, the Bad and the Ugly
tomato_consensus: Arguably the greatest of the spaghetti westerns, this epic features a compelling story, memorable performances, breathtaking landscapes, and a haunting score.
wiki_title: The Good, the Bad and the Ugly

title: The Good German
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though Steven Soderbergh succeeds in emulating the glossy look of 1940s noirs, The Good German ultimately ends up as a self-conscious exercise in style that forgets to develop compelling characters.

title: The Good Shepherd
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This fictitious CIA origin film is an overlong, tedious effort that leaves viewers with more questions than answers.

title: The Good Thief
tomato_consensus: Bolstered by Nolte's strong performance, The Good Thief brims with seductive style.

title: The Goods: Live Hard, Sell Hard
tomato_consensus: Despite the talent in front of and behind the camera, The Goods: Live Hard, Sell Hard largely misfires, proving a squandered opportunity for all involved.
wiki_title: The Goods: Live Hard, Sell Hard

title: The Goonies
tomato_consensus: An energetic, sometimes noisy mix of Speilbergian sentiment and funhouse tricks that will appeal to kids and nostalgic adults alike.

title: The Gospel
tomato_consensus: While it features outstanding musical numbers, The Gospel reduces a series of worthy themes -- faith, family, forgiveness -- to soapy, banal clich?s.

title: Sopralluoghi in Palestina per il vangelo secondo Matteo
wiki_title: The Gospel According to St. Matthew (film)

title: The Visual Bible: The Gospel of John
The Graduate
tomato_consensus: The music, the performances, the precision in capturing the post-college malaise -- The Graduate's coming-of-age story is indeed one for the ages.

title: The Grandmaster
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 26 wins & 29 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though its storytelling is a tad muddled, Wong Kar Wai's The Grandmaster still exhibits the auteur's stylistic flourishes in gorgeous cinematography and explosive action set pieces.

title: The Grapes of Wrath
tomato_consensus: A potent drama that is as socially important today as when it was made, The Grapes of Wrath is affecting, moving, and deservedly considered an American classic.

title: The Grass Is Greener
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 nominations.

title: The Great Buck Howard
tomato_consensus: By turns fluffy and biting, this show biz comedy is given girth by comic heavyweight John Malkovich and made all the more charming by Emily Blunt.

title: The Great Dictator
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Great Escape
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The Great Gatsby
tomato_consensus: While certainly ambitious -- and every bit as visually dazzling as one might expect -- Baz Luhrmann's The Great Gatsby emphasizes visual splendor at the expense of its source material's vibrant heart.

title: The Great Man
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 nominations.

title: The Great Mouse Detective
tomato_consensus: The Great Mouse Detective may not rank with Disney's classics, but it's an amiable, entertaining picture with some stylishly dark visuals.

title: The Great Muppet Caper
tomato_consensus: The Great Muppet Caper is overplotted and uneven, but the appealing presence of Kermit, Miss Piggy and the gang ensure that this heist flick is always breezily watchable.

title: The Great New Wonderful
tomato_consensus: Set in post-9/11 New York, this largely evocative dramedy interweaves the stories of five disconnected individuals who share an unspoken emotional malaise that shadows their attempts at returning to normal life.

title: The Great Raid
tomato_consensus: Though the climax of the film -- the actual raid -- is exciting, the rest of it is bogged down in too many subplots and runs on for too long.

title: The Great Santini
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 2 nominations.

wiki_title: The Great St Trinian's Train Robbery

title: The Great White Hope
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: The Great Ziegfeld
tomato_consensus: This biopic is undeniably stylish, but loses points for excessive length, an overreliance on clich?s, and historical inaccuracies.

title: The Greatest
tomato_consensus: It's burdened by a predictable, overly melodramatic story, but The Greatest benefits from strong performances by its talented cast.

title: The Greatest Game Ever Played
tomato_consensus: Despite all the underdog sports movie conventions, the likable cast and lush production values make The Greatest Game Ever Played a solid and uplifting tale.

title: The Greatest Show on Earth
tomato_consensus: The Greatest Show on Earth is melodramatic, short on plot, excessively lengthy and bogged down with clich?s, but not without a certain innocent charm.

title: The Green Hornet
tomato_consensus: It's sporadically entertaining, but The Green Hornet never approaches the surreal heights suggested by a Michel Gondry/Seth Rogen collaboration.

title: The Green Mile
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though The Green Mile is long, critics say it's an absorbing, emotionally powerful experience.

title: The Grey
tomato_consensus: The Grey is an exciting tale of survival, populated with fleshed-out characters and a surprising philosophical agenda.

title: The Grey Zone
tomato_consensus: A grim and devastating tale of the Holocaust.

title: The Grifters
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 7 nominations.

title: The Groomsmen
tomato_consensus: Director and star Burns returns to his home turf -- dialogue-driven examinations of the relationships between men and women -- with uneven results.

title: The Grudge
tomato_consensus: There's some creepy imagery to be found, but not much in the way of logic or truly jarring scares.

title: The Grudge 2
tomato_consensus: A diminished sequel that makes even less sense than The Grudge 1.

title: The Guard
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A violent, crackerjack comedy with a strong Irish flavor and an emminently likable Brendan Gleeson in the main role.

title: The Guardian
tomato_consensus: The Coast Guard gets its chance for a heroic movie tribute, but The Guardian does it no justice, borrowing cliche after cliche from other (and better) military branch movies.

title: The Guilt Trip
tomato_consensus: Tyler Perry and Matthew Fox do their best, but they're trampled by Rob Cohen's frustrating direction and a tasteless, lazily written screenplay.

title: The Guru
tomato_consensus: A sweetly silly but wafer-thin romantic comedy.

title: A Hard Day's Night
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A Hard Day's Night, despite its age, is still a delight to watch and has proven itself to be a rock-and-roll movie classic.

title: A History of Violence
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 35 wins & 34 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A History of Violence raises compelling and thoughtful questions about the nature of violence, while representing a return to form for director David Cronenberg in one of his more uncharacteristic pieces.

title: A Home at the End of the World
wiki_title: A Home at the End of the World (film)

title: The War of the Worlds
wiki_title: H.G. Wells' The War of the Worlds (2005 film)

title: The Shape of Things to Come
wiki_title: H. G. Wells' The Shape of Things to Come

title: Hag in a Black Leather Jacket
wiki_title: Hag in a Black Leather Jacket

title: Hairspray
tomato_consensus: Hairspray is perhaps John Waters' most accessible film, and as such, it's a gently subversive slice of retro hilarity.

title: Hairspray
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 13 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Hairspray is an energetic, wholly entertaining musical romp; a fun Summer movie with plenty of heart. Its contagious songs will make you want to get up and start dancing.

title: Half Nelson
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 30 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Half Nelson features powerful performances from Ryan Gosling and Shareeka Epps. It's a wise, unsentimental portrait of lonely people at the crossroads.

title: Half Past Dead
tomato_consensus: Seagal is now too bulky to make a convincing action hero, and Half Past Dead is too silly and incoherent to deliver any visceral kicks.

title: Dian zhi gong fu gan chian chan
wiki_title: Half a Loaf of Kung Fu

title: Hall Pass
tomato_consensus: Some filmgoers may be surprised by the Farrellys' defense of traditional domestic values in Hall Pass -- unfortunately, they'll probably also be dismayed by the absence of laughs.

title: Hallam Foe
tomato_consensus: Carefully balanced between the dark and the dreamy, Mister Foe is a charged coming-of-age story with whimsy and bite.

title: Halloween: Resurrection
tomato_consensus: The only thing this tired slasher flick may resurrect is nostalgia for when the genre was still fresh and scary.

title: Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers
wiki_title: Halloween: The Curse of Michael Myers

title: Halloween
tomato_consensus: Scary, suspenseful, and viscerally thrilling, Halloween set the standard for modern horror films.

title: Halloween
tomato_consensus: Rob Zombie doesn't bring many new ideas to the table in Halloween, making it another bloody disappointment for fans of the franchise.

title: Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers
wiki_title: Halloween 4: The Return of Michael Myers

title: Halloween 5
wiki_title: Halloween 5: The Revenge of Michael Myers

title: Halloween H20: 20 Years Later
tomato_consensus: Halloween: H2O is the best of the many sequels, yet still pales in comparison to the original Halloween.

title: Halloween III: Season of the Witch
wiki_title: Halloween III: Season of the Witch

title: Halloween II
tomato_consensus: Zombie shows flashes of vision in the follow-up to his Halloween reboot, but they're smothered by mountains of gore and hackneyed, brutal violence.

title: Hamlet
tomato_consensus: A well-executed labor of love from star and director Laurence Olivier, Hamlet not only proved that Shakespeare could be successfully adapted to the big screen, it paved the way for further cinematic interpretations.

title: Hamlet
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Hamlet
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It may lack some of the depth and complexity of the play, but Mel Gibson and Franco Zeffirelli make a surprisingly successful team.

title: Hamlet
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kenneth Branagh's sprawling, finely textured adaptation of Shakespeare's masterpiece lives up to its source material, using strong performances and a sharp cinematic focus to create a powerfully resonant film that wastes none of its 246 minutes.

title: Hamlet
tomato_consensus: Stiff performances fail to produce any tension onscreen.

title: Hamlet 2
tomato_consensus: The script's biting premise and Steve Coogan's endearing, off-the-handle performance make Hamlet 2 an hysterical -- if slightly painful -- ride.

title: Hancock
tomato_consensus: Though it begins with promise, Hancock suffers from a flimsy narrative and poor execution.

title: Hanging Up
tomato_consensus: Though the screenplay and the novel it's based on were both written by the same person, critics say Hanging Up is an unsuccessful adaptation. The acting is praised as solid, but is ultimately unable to save the film.

title: Hanna
tomato_consensus: Fantastic acting and crisply choreographed action sequences propel this unique, cool take on the revenge thriller.

title: Hannah Montana: The Movie
tomato_consensus: While youthful Miley fans won't complain, Hannah Montana the Movie is little more than a formulaic Disney Channel episode stretched thin.

title: Hannah Montana & Miley Cyrus: Best of Both Worlds Concert
tomato_consensus: This high-energy concert film should please Cyrus' rabid pre-teen fan base -- and may come as a pleasant surprise for parents.
wiki_title: Hannah Montana & Miley Cyrus: Best of Both Worlds Concert (film)

title: Hannah and Her Sisters
tomato_consensus: Smart, tender, and funny in equal measure, Hannah and Her Sisters is one of Woody Allen's finest films.

title: Hannibal
tomato_consensus: While superbly acted and stylishly filmed, Hannibal lacks the character interaction between the two leads which made the first movie so engrossing.

title: Hannibal Rising
tomato_consensus: Hannibal Rising reduces the horror icon to a collection of dime-store psychological traits.

title: Hansel & Gretel: Witch Hunters
tomato_consensus: Alternately bloody and silly, Hansel and Gretel: Witch Hunters fails as both a fantasy adventure and as a parody of same.

title: Hanussen
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.

title: ...And They Lived Happily Ever After
tomato_consensus: Though this French film features good acting, it lacks the wit and charm one would expect to see.

title: Happily N'Ever After
tomato_consensus: Happily N'Ever After has none of the moxy, edge, or postmodern wit of the other fairy-tales-gone-haywire CG movie it so blatantly rips off.

title: Happiness
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 13 wins & 12 nominations.

title: Happy, Texas
tomato_consensus: A smart, light-hearted romantic comedy, Happy, Texas uses its well-written script and exceptional cast to prove there's still life left in the fish-out-of-water caper genre.

title: Happy Accidents
tomato_consensus: Happy Accidents has enough quirkiness and charm to rise above the more formulaic entries in the romantic comedy genre.

title: Happy Endings
tomato_consensus: Despite strong individual performances, the overlong, disjointed plot of Happy Endings self-indulgently rambles.

title: Happy Feet
tomato_consensus: Visually dazzling, with a thoughtful storyline and catchy musical numbers, Happy Feet marks a successful animated debut from the makers of Babe.

title: Happy Feet Two
tomato_consensus: The animation is as eye-popping as ever, but Happy Feet Two's narrative is too noisily incoherent to recapture the Oscar-winning charm of its predecessor.

title: Happy Gilmore
tomato_consensus: Those who enjoy Adam Sandler's schtick will find plenty to love in this gleefully juvenile take on professional golf; those who don't, however, will find it unfunny and forgettable.

title: Happy Times
tomato_consensus: One of Zhang's smaller films, Happy Times is nevertheless moving and bittersweet.

title: Hard Candy
tomato_consensus: Disturbing, controversial, but entirely engrossing, Hard Candy is well written with strong lead performances, especially that of newcomer Ellen Page. A movie that stays with the viewer long after leaving the theater.

title: Hard Rain
country: USA, UK, Denmark, France, Japan, New Zealand, Germany

title: Harlem Nights
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man
wiki_title: Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man

title: Harold & Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay
tomato_consensus: It may not equal its predecessor, but Harold and Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay is still good for some laughs -- and food for thought.
wiki_title: Harold & Kumar Escape from Guantanamo Bay

title: Harold & Kumar Go to White Castle
tomato_consensus: The likable leads and subversion of racial stereotypes elevate Harold and Kumar above the typical stoner comedy.
wiki_title: Harold & Kumar Go to White Castle

title: Harold and Maude
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Hal Ashby's comedy is too dark and twisted for some, and occasionally oversteps its bounds, but there's no denying the film's warm humor and big heart.

title: Harrison's Flowers
tomato_consensus: Though it presents the war in shockingly gritty, realistic terms, Harrison's Flowers uses such scenes as background for a trite love story.

title: Harry Brown
tomato_consensus: Its lurid violence may put off some viewers, but Harry Brown is a vigilante thriller that carries an emotional as well as a physical punch, thanks to a gripping performance from Michael Caine in the title role.

title: Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets
awards: Nominated for 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 10 wins & 31 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though perhaps more enchanting for younger audiences, Chamber of Secrets is nevertheless both darker and livelier than its predecessor, expanding and improving upon the first film's universe.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (film)

title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 1
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 39 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It can't help but feel like the prelude it is, but Deathly Hallows: Part I is a beautifully filmed, emotionally satisfying penultimate installment for the Harry Potter series.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 1

title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part 2
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 33 wins & 49 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Thrilling, powerfully acted, and visually dazzling, Deathly Hallows Part II brings the Harry Potter franchise to a satisfying -- and suitably magical -- conclusion.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 2

title: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 34 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The main characters are maturing, and the filmmakers are likewise improving on their craft; vibrant special effects and assured performances add up to what is the most complex yet of the Harry Potter films.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)

title: Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 25 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Dark, thrilling, and occasionally quite funny, Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince is also visually stunning and emotionally satisfying.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)

title: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 13 wins & 32 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It's not easy to take the longest Harry Potter book and streamline it into the shortest HP movie, but director David Yates does a bang up job of it, creating an Order of the Phoenix that's entertaining and action-packed.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)

title: Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 50 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Being so faithful to the book is both the movie's strength and weakness. The movie unfolds exactly as written in the book, so there is little room for surprises or discoveries. For Potter fans, what more can you ask for?
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)

title: Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 35 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Under the assured direction of Alfonso Cuaron, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban triumphantly strikes a delicate balance between technical wizardry and complex storytelling.
wiki_title: Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)

title: Harsh Times
tomato_consensus: Despite a dedicated performance by Christian Bale, Harsh Times suffers from a heavy-handed and overly bleak plot.

title: Hart's War
tomato_consensus: Well-made and solidly acted, Hart's War is modestly compelling. However, the movie suffers from having too many subplots.

title: Harvard Man
tomato_consensus: Harvard Man is a pretentious, incoherent mess.

title: Hatchet
tomato_consensus: The over-the-top gore, campy acting, and dim cinematography may be part of Hatchet's self-described old-school ethos, but irony alone can't sustain a horror film.

title: Hatchet II
tomato_consensus: Funnier and more gleefully gory than most slasher sequels, Hatchet II aims for so-bad-it's-good territory, but can't quite hack it.

title: Hated: GG Allin & the Murder Junkies
wiki_title: Hated: GG Allin and the Murder Junkies

title: High Tension
tomato_consensus: There is indeed a good amount of tension in this French slasher, but the dubbing is bad and the end twist unbelievable.

title: Haven
tomato_consensus: The plot's gratuitously nonlinear structure only ends up confusing viewers of this island thriller.

title: Hawaii
awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Haywire
tomato_consensus: MMA star and first-time actress Gina Carano displays ample action-movie chops in Haywire, a fast-paced thriller with a top-notch cast and outstanding direction from Steven Soderbergh.

title: He's Just Not That Into You

title: An Inconvenient Truth
tomato_consensus: While global warming is a hotly-debated subject, what everyone on both sides can agree upon is that, if real, it's a very bad thing. Since losing the 2000 presidential election to George W. Bush, former Vice President Al Gore has busied himself by being an outspoken figure against this potential environmental disaster. As much about the man as about greenhouse gases, this candid, powerful and informative documentary illuminates some of the myths surrounding both of its subjects equally well.
