tomato_consensus: Typical David Lynch fare: fans of the director will find Inland Empire seductive and deep. All others will consider the heady surrealism impenetrable and pointless.

title: Innerspace
tomato_consensus: A manic, overstuffed blend of sci-fi, comedy, and romance, Innerspace nonetheless charms, thanks to Martin Short's fine performance and the insistent zaniness of the plot.

title: Inside Daisy Clover
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Inside Deep Throat
tomato_consensus: A documentary on the film that brought smut mainstream, Inside Deep Throat is gaining praise as an entertaining look at a pop culture milestone. However, some critics say the film could have gone a little deeper into the people involved.

title: Rory O'Shea Was Here
tomato_consensus: The dramatic aspects of Rory O'Shea Was Here veer into mawkish, formulaic sentiment, which undercuts the characters' individuality.

title: Inside Job
tomato_consensus: Disheartening but essential viewing, Charles Ferguson's documentary explores the 2008 Global Financial Crisis with exemplary rigor.

title: Inside Llewyn Davis
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 32 wins & 71 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Smart, funny, and profoundly melancholy, Inside Llewyn Davis finds the Coen brothers in fine form.

title: Inside Man
tomato_consensus: Spike Lee's energetic and clever bank-heist thriller touches on questions of race and class without taking away from the tension and fun of the cat-and-mouse games between a hostage negotiator (Denzel Washington), a bank robber (Clive Owen), and a high-powered fixer (Jodie Foster). Inside Man puts a spin on the Dog Day Afternoon scenario, with a group of sharp bank robbers who stay one step ahead of the police; it's a smart genre film that is not only rewarding on its own terms, but manages to subvert its pulpy trappings with wit and skill.

title: Insidious
tomato_consensus: Aside from a shaky final act, Insidious is a very scary and very fun haunted house thrill ride.

title: Insomnia
tomato_consensus: Driven by Pacino's performance, Insomnia is a smart and riveting psychological drama.

title: Inspector Gadget
tomato_consensus: Despite an abundance of eyecandy, the film doesn't amount to much.

title: Instinct
tomato_consensus: A convoluted and predictable plot overshadows the performances.

title: Intact
tomato_consensus: The plot gimmick is original, bolstered by stylishly intriguing setpieces.

title: Interiors
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Intermission
tomato_consensus: An edgy and energetic ensemble story.

title: Interview
tomato_consensus: Captivating performances from Steve Buscemi and Sienna Miller make a seemingly simple premise gripping and entertaining.

title: Interview with the Vampire: The Vampire Chronicles
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite lacking some of the book's subtler shadings, and suffering from some clumsy casting, Interview with a Vampire benefits from Neil Jordan's atmospheric direction and a surfeit of gothic thrills.
wiki_title: Interview with the Vampire: The Vampire Chronicles

title: Intimacy
tomato_consensus: Acted out with both physical and psychological nakedness by its two leads, Intimacy is an unflinchingly honest look at alienation.

title: Intimate Strangers
tomato_consensus: Intimate Strangers is Hitchcockian noir with a Gallic twist: Rather than simply imitating the genre's form, director/screenwriter Patrice Leconte delves into the underlying psychological drama.

title: Into Great Silence
tomato_consensus: A meditative, deliberately paced doc capable of absorbing patient viewers into a whole different world.

title: Into the Arms of Strangers: Stories of the Kindertransport
tomato_consensus: Although it appears to be nothing more than a "talking heads" documentary you may see on TV, Into the Arms of Strangers, nonetheless, tells a heart-wrenching story.
wiki_title: Into the Arms of Strangers: Stories of the Kindertransport

title: Into the Blue
tomato_consensus: Even the endless shots of bronzed beach babes and buffed dudes can't keep this soggy scuba flick's plot from drowning.

title: Into the Wild
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 17 wins & 44 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With his sturdy cast and confident direction, Sean Penn has turned a complex work of non-fiction like Into the Wild into an accessible and poignant character study.

title: Intolerable Cruelty
tomato_consensus: Though more mainstream than other Coen films, there are still funny oddball touches, and Clooney and Zeta-Jones sizzle like old-time movie stars.

title: Intolerance: Love's Struggle Throughout the Ages
tomato_consensus: A pioneering classic and one of the most influential films ever made, D.W. Griffith's Intolerance stands as the crowning jewel in an incredible filmography.

title: InuYasha the Movie: The Castle Beyond the Looking Glass
wiki_title: Inuyasha the Movie: The Castle Beyond the Looking Glass

title: Invasion of the Body Snatchers
tomato_consensus: One of the best political allegories of the 1950s, Invasion of the Body Snatchers is an efficient, chilling blend of sci-fi and horror.
wiki_title: Invasion of the Body Snatchers (1956 film)

title: Invasion of the Body Snatchers
tomato_consensus: Employing gritty camerawork and evocative sound effects, Invasion of the Body Snatchers is a powerful remake that expands upon themes and ideas only lightly explored in the original.
wiki_title: Invasion of the Body Snatchers (1978 film)

title: Investigation of a Citizen Above Suspicion
wiki_title: Investigation of a Citizen Above Suspicion

title: Invictus
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 21 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Delivered with typically stately precision from director Clint Eastwood, Invictus may not be rousing enough for some viewers, but Matt Damon and Morgan Freeman inhabit their real-life characters with admirable conviction.

title: Invincible
tomato_consensus: Sluggish and flawed, this is a minor work in Herzog's career.

title: Invincible
tomato_consensus: As simple and authentic as the gritty South Philly invirons in which it's set in, Invincible sends a uplifting and heartfelt message packed with an athletic enthusiasm that shouldn't be missed.

title: Ip Man
tomato_consensus: At once beholden to the established conventions of the genre and delightfully subversive of them, Ip Man is one of the most exciting -- and refreshingly character-driven -- martial arts films in years.

title: Ip Man 2: Legend of the Grandmaster
Irina Palm
tomato_consensus: A strong performance from Faithfull anchors this perverse and lethargic -- but ultimately thought-provoking -- Garbarski drama.

title: Iris
tomato_consensus: A solidly constructed drama, Iris is greatly elevated by the strength of its four lead performances.

title: Iron Man
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 43 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Director Jon Favreau and star Robert Downey make this smart, high impact superhero movie one that even non-comics fans can enjoy.

title: Iron Man 2
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It isn't quite the breath of fresh air that Iron Man was, but this sequel comes close with solid performances and an action-packed plot.

title: Iron Man 3
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 35 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With the help of its charismatic lead, some impressive action sequences, and even a few surprises, Iron Man 3 is a witty, entertaining adventure and a strong addition to the Marvel canon.

title: Iron Monkey
tomato_consensus: Iron Monkey may not have the poetic lyricism of Crouching Tiger, it makes up for it in fun and energy.

title: Ironweed
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Irreconcilable Differences
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 nomination.

title: Irreversible
tomato_consensus: Though well-filmed, Irreversible feels gratuitous in its extreme violence.

title: Is Paris Burning?
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Isadora
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Isn't She Great
tomato_consensus: Bland material produces entirely forgettable comic performances.

title: It! The Terror from Beyond Space
wiki_title: It! The Terror from Beyond Space

title: It's All About Love
country: Italy, France, Canada, Spain, USA, Japan, Sweden, UK, Denmark, Germany, Netherlands

title: It's All Gone Pete Tong
tomato_consensus: Part raucous mockumentary, part drama-filled biopic, It's All Gone Pete Tong amuses and warms hearts with its touching, comic, and candid look at a musician faced with a career-ending handicap.

title: It's Complicated
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite fine work by an appealing cast, It's Complicated is predictable romantic comedy fare, going for broad laughs instead of subtlety and nuance.

title: It's Kind of a Funny Story
tomato_consensus: It's amiable, and it does a surprisingly good job of sidestepping psych ward comedy cliches, but given its talented cast and directors, It's Kind of a Funny Story should be more than just mildly entertaining.
wiki_title: It's Kind of a Funny Story (film)

title: It's a Disaster
tomato_consensus: A clever black comedy, It's a Disaster is sometimes uneven but the sharp writing and stellar ensemble cast keeps the film on track.

title: It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World
tomato_consensus: It's long, frantic, and stuffed to the gills with comic actors and set pieces -- and that's exactly its charm.
wiki_title: It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World

title: It's a Wonderful Life
tomato_consensus: The holiday classic to define all holiday classics, It's a Wonderful Life is one of a handful of films worth an annual viewing.

title: It Came from Beneath the Sea
wiki_title: It Came from Beneath the Sea

title: It Came from Outer Space
tomato_consensus: It Came From Outer Space is a pulpy-but-effective psychological sci-fi picture, with a provocative message about xenophobia.

title: It Happened Here
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win.

title: It Happened One Night
tomato_consensus: Capturing its stars and director at their finest, It Happened One Night remains unsurpassed by the countless romantic comedies it has inspired.

title: It Happened at the World's Fair
wiki_title: It Happened at the World's Fair

title: It Might Get Loud
tomato_consensus: An affectionate tribute to rock's most distinctive instrument, It Might Get Loud is insightful and musically satisfying.

title: It Runs in the Family
tomato_consensus: Despite its gimmick casting, the movie ultimately goes nowhere.
wiki_title: It Runs in the Family (2003 film)

title: Italian for Beginners
tomato_consensus: Unlike many romantic comedies, the charming Italian for Beginners feels natural and genuinely heart-warming.

title: Ivan Vasilievich: Back to the Future
wiki_title: Ivan Vasilievich: Back to the Future

title: Raiders of the Lost Ark
tomato_consensus: Featuring bravura set pieces, sly humor, and white-knuckle action, Raiders of the Lost Ark is one of the most consummately entertaining adventure pictures of all time.

title: The Ice Storm
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Director Ang Lee revisits the ennui-laden decadence of 1970s suburban America with deft humor and gripping pathos.

title: The Iceman
tomato_consensus: While it deserved stronger direction and a more fully realized script, Michael Shannon's riveting performance in the title role is more than enough to make The Iceman recommended viewing.

title: The Ides of March
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 21 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While not exactly exposing revelatory truths, The Ides of March is supremely well-acted drama that moves at a measured, confident clip.

title: The Idiots
country: Spain, Denmark, Sweden, France, Netherlands, Italy

title: The iDOLM@STER Movie: Kagayaki no Mukougawa e
wiki_title: The Idolmaster Movie: Kagayaki no Mukogawa e!

title: The Illusionist
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Illusionist is an engrossing, well-crafted story of mystery, magic and intrigue that is certain to enchant, if not hypnotize, audiences.

title: The Illusionist
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An engrossing love letter to fans of adult animation, The Illusionist offers a fine antidote to garish mainstream fare.

title: The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Terry Gilliam remains as indulgent as ever, but The Imaginarium of Doctor Parnassus represents a return to the intoxicatingly imaginative, darkly beautiful power of his earlier work, with fine performances to match all the visual spectacle.

title: The Importance of Being Earnest
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
wiki_title: The Importance of Being Earnest (1952 film)

title: The Importance of Being Earnest
tomato_consensus: Oliver Parker's adaptation of Oscar Wilde's classic play is breezy entertainment, helped by an impressive cast, but it also suffers from some peculiar directorial choices that ultimately dampen the film's impact.
wiki_title: The Importance of Being Earnest (2002 film)

title: The Impossible
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 23 wins & 40 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The screenplay isn't quite as powerful as the direction or the acting, but with such an astonishing real-life story at its center, The Impossible is never less than compelling.

title: The Imposter
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 10 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite its true-crime trappings, The Imposter is an utterly gripping and sometimes heartbreaking documentary thriller cleverly told with narrative flair.

title: The In-Laws
tomato_consensus: Bigger and slicker than the original, but not necessarily better.

title: The In Crowd
tomato_consensus: A dull, soapy potboiler that lacks the energy to qualify as a guilty pleasure, The In Crowd is undone by slow pacing, poor acting, and a stunning lack of originality.

title: The Inbetweeners Movie
tomato_consensus: It arguably plays most strongly to fans of the BBC series, but even viewers who have never seen The Inbetweeners on TV may find themselves won over by the film's surprisingly tender ribaldry.

title: The Incredible Burt Wonderstone
tomato_consensus: The Incredible Burt Wonderstone serves up some goofy laughs, but given its outrageous conceit, it's surprisingly safe and predictable.

title: The Incredible Hulk
tomato_consensus: The Incredible Hulk provides the action and excitement to please comic book fans and re-ignite this fledgling franchise.

title: The Incredibly True Adventure of Two Girls in Love
wiki_title: The Incredibly True Adventures of Two Girls in Love

title: The Informant!
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A charismatic turn by star Matt Damon and a consistently ironic tone boost this quietly funny satire about a corporate whistle-blower.

title: The Informers
tomato_consensus: As miserable and insipid as its protagonists, The Informers fails to provide anything to think about after the sheen of fake blond is gone.

title: The Inn of the Sixth Happiness
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 5 nominations.
wiki_title: The Inn of the Sixth Happiness

title: The Innkeepers
tomato_consensus: It doesn't break any rules of the genre, but The Innkeepers serves as additional proof that Ti West is a young director that discriminating horror fans can trust.

title: The Innocents
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Creepily atmospheric, The Innocents is a stylishly crafted, chilling British ghost tale with Deborah Kerr at her finest.

title: The Insider
awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 27 wins & 34 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Intelligent, compelling, and packed with strong performances, The Insider is a potent corporate thriller.

title: The International
tomato_consensus: The International boasts some electric action sequences and picturesque locales, but is undone by its preposterous plot.

title: The Internship
tomato_consensus: The Internship weighs down Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson's comic charisma with a formulaic script and padded running time that leans heavily on its stars' easygoing interplay.

title: The Interpreter
tomato_consensus: A polished and intelligent thriller, though marred by plot implausibilities.

title: The Intouchables
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 25 wins & 31 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It handles its potentially prickly subject matter with kid gloves, but Intouchables gets by thanks to its strong cast and some remarkably sensitive direction.

title: The Invasion
tomato_consensus: The Invasion is slickly made, but it lacks psychological insight and thrills.

title: The Invention of Lying
tomato_consensus: It doesn't quite follow through on its promise, and relies too heavily on shopworn romantic comedy tropes, but The Invention of Lying is uncommonly sly and funny.

title: The Invisible
tomato_consensus: Dull and confusing execution makes this ghost story utterly forgettable and unintentionally funny.

title: The Invisible Circus
tomato_consensus: Despite Jordana Brewster's strong performance, The Invisible Circus lacks the necessary dramatic tension to be interesting. Also, the cultural and political contexts of the period are barely explored.

title: The Invisible Man
tomato_consensus: James Whale's classic The Invisible Man features still-sharp special effects, loads of tension, a goofy sense of humor, and a memorable debut from Claude Rains.

title: The Invisible War
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Invisible War is a vital and frank expose on sexual assault in the U.S. military, shot by master filmmaker Kirby Dick (This Film is Not Yet Rated).

title: The Ipcress File
awards: Won 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The Iron Giant
tomato_consensus: Engaging, endearing, affecting and charmingly retro, The Iron Giant tackles touchy subjects and complex relationships with a steady hand and beautiful animation direction from Brad Bird.

title: The Iron Lady
tomato_consensus: Meryl Streep's performance as The Iron Lady is reliably perfect, but it's mired in bland, self-important storytelling.

title: The Island
tomato_consensus: A clone of THX 1183, Coma, and Logan's Run, The Island is another loud and bombastic Michael Bay movie where explosions and chases matter more than characters, dialogue, or plot.

title: The Island at the Top of the World
wiki_title: The Island at the Top of the World

title: The Island of Dr. Moreau
wiki_title: The Island of Dr. Moreau (1977 film)

title: The Island of Dr. Moreau
wiki_title: The Island of Dr. Moreau (1996 film)

title: The Isle
tomato_consensus: A compelling and oddly haunting combination of brutal and beautiful imagery.

title: The Italian Job
tomato_consensus: Despite some iffy plot elements, The Italian Job succeeds in delivering an entertaining modern take on the original 1969 heist film, thanks to a charismatic cast.

title: A Kid in King Arthur's Court
wiki_title: A Kid in King Arthur's Court

title: A Kind of Loving
awards: Nominated for 4 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 win.

title: A Knight's Tale
tomato_consensus: Once you get past the anachronism, A Knight's Tale becomes a predictable, if spirited, Rocky on horseback.

title: A View to a Kill
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Absurd even by Bond standards, A View to a Kill is weighted down by campy jokes and a noticeable lack of energy.

title: The Kid
tomato_consensus: Critics find The Kid to be too sweet and the movie's message to be annoyingly simplistic.

title: From Up on Poppy Hill
tomato_consensus: Gentle and nostalgic, From Up on Poppy Hill is one of Studio Ghibli's sweeter efforts -- and if it doesn't push the boundaries of the genre, it remains as engagingly lovely as Ghibli fans have come to expect.

title: J. Edgar
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Leonardo DiCaprio gives a predictably powerhouse performance, but J. Edgar stumbles in all other departments with cheesy makeup, poor lighting, confusing narrative, and humdrum storytelling.

title: JFK
tomato_consensus: As history, Oliver Stone's JFK is dubious, but as filmmaking it's electric, cramming a ton of information and excitement into its three-hour runtime and making great use of its outstanding cast.

title: Jaan-E-Mann: Let's Fall in Love... Again
wiki_title: Jaan-E-Mann: Let's Fall in Love... Again

title: Jack Brooks: Monster Slayer
tomato_consensus: A sincere but sometimes-excessive send up of low-rent horror hokum, Jack Brooks: Monster Slayer features some sharp laughs and features a scene-stealing performance by Robert Englund.

title: Jack Frost
tomato_consensus: Sentimental schmaltz and uninspired storytelling sink this film.

title: Jack Frost 2: Revenge of the Mutant Killer Snowman
wiki_title: Jack Frost 2: Revenge of the Mutant Killer Snowman

title: Jack Reacher
tomato_consensus: Jack Reacher is an above-average crime thriller with a smoothly charismatic performance from Tom Cruise.

title: Jack and Jill
tomato_consensus: Although it features an inexplicably committed performance from Al Pacino, Jack and Jill is impossible to recommend on any level whatsoever.

title: Jack the Giant Slayer
tomato_consensus: It's enthusiastically acted and reasonably fun, but Jack the Giant Slayer is also overwhelmed by digital effects and a bland, impersonal story.

title: Jackass Number Two
tomato_consensus: Better than any sequel to a movie of a television show has a right to be, Jackass: Number Two dares you not to laugh.

title: Jackass: The Movie
tomato_consensus: There's a good chance you'll be laughing hysterically at one stunt, but getting grossed out by the next one in this big screen version of the controversial MTV show.

title: Jackass 3D
tomato_consensus: The Jackass gang might be running out of gross-out stunts, but this installment contains plenty of brilliantly brain-dead comedy -- and the 3-D adds a pungent new dimension.

title: Jackass Presents: Bad Grandpa
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Never quite as funny as it wants to be, Jackass Presents: Bad Grandpa still offers viewers the timeless pleasures of seeing an old man get his privates stuck in a vending machine.

title: Jackie Brown
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Tarantino's third film, fashioned as a comeback vehicle for star Pam Grier, offers typical wit and charm -- and is typically overstuffed.

title: Jacob
country: Czech Republic, France, UK, Italy, Germany, USA, Netherlands

title: Jakob the Liar
tomato_consensus: Any real story is buried by awkward performances and contrived situations.

title: James' Journey to Jerusalem
tomato_consensus: A smart and funny social satire about modern-day Jerusalem.

title: James and the Giant Peach
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The arresting and dynamic visuals, offbeat details and light-as-air storytelling make James and the Giant Peach solid family entertainment.

title: Jamón, Jamón
tomato_consensus: It isn't as provocative or amusing as it pretends to be, but Jam?n Jam?n's cheerfully overheated melodrama is often its own reward.

title: Jane Eyre
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Cary Fukunaga directs a fiery and elegant adaptation of Charlotte Bronte's classic novel, and Mia Wasikowska delivers possibly the best portrayal of the title character ever.

title: Japanese Story
tomato_consensus: An emotional film where Toni Collette gets to show her impressive range.

title: Jarhead
tomato_consensus: This first person account of the first Gulf War scores with its performances and cinematography but lacks an emotional thrust.

title: Jason and the Argonauts
tomato_consensus: Don Chaffey's Jason and the Argonauts is an outlandish, transportive piece of nostalgia whose real star is the masterful stop-motion animation work of Ray Harryhausen.

title: Jawbreaker
tomato_consensus: This throwaway comedy falls victim to its hip sensibilities.

title: Jaws: The Revenge
tomato_consensus: Illogical, tension-free, and filled with cut-rate special effects, Jaws 4 - The Revenge is a sorry chapter in a once-proud franchise.

title: Jaws
tomato_consensus: Compelling, well-crafted storytelling and a judicious sense of terror ensure Steven Spielberg's Jaws has remained a benchmark in the art of delivering modern blockbuster thrills.

title: Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back
tomato_consensus: Fans can expect a good laugh as the cast from Smith's previous films reunite for Jay and Silent Bob's last bow. The loose plotting and crude language may be too much for others though.
wiki_title: Jay and Silent Bob Strike Back

title: Jayne Mansfield's Car
tomato_consensus: Jayne Mansfield's Car assembles an impressive number of talented actors, but the screenplay -- co-written by director and star Billy Bob Thornton -- never gives them much of anything to do.

title: Jean de Florette
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 11 wins & 15 nominations.

title: Jeanne Dielman, 23 Quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles
wiki_title: Jeanne Dielman, 23 quai du Commerce, 1080 Bruxelles

title: Jeepers Creepers
tomato_consensus: Jeepers Creepers has a promising start. Unfortunately, the tension and suspense quickly deflates into genre cliches as movie goes on.

title: Jeepers Creepers II
tomato_consensus: Jeepers Creepers 2 is competently made, but it doesn't have the scares of the original.

title: Jeff, Who Lives at Home
tomato_consensus: Sweet, funny, and flawed, Jeff, Who Lives at Home finds the Duplass brothers moving into the mainstream with their signature quirky charm intact.

title: Jennifer's Body
tomato_consensus: Jennifer's Body features occasionally clever dialogue but the horror/comic premise fails to be either funny or scary enough to satisfy.

title: Jerry Maguire
tomato_consensus: Anchored by dazzling performances from Tom Cruise, Cuba Gooding Jr., and Ren?e Zellweger, as well as Cameron Crowe's tender direction, Jerry Maguire meshes romance and sports with panache.

title: Jesus Camp

title: Jesus Christ Superstar
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 9 nominations.

title: Jesus of Montreal
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 18 wins & 9 nominations.

title: Jet Lag
tomato_consensus: A light and fluffy romantic comedy for fans of Juliette Binoche and Jean Reno.

title: Jimmy Neutron: Boy Genius
tomato_consensus: What Jimmy Neutron lacks in computer animation, it makes up for in charm and cleverness.

title: Jindabyne
tomato_consensus: Jindabyne's disparate themes may not quite cohere, but the film features fine performances from Linney and Byrne.

title: Jiro Dreams of Sushi
tomato_consensus: Beautiful, thoughtful, and engrossing, Jiro Dreams of Sushi should prove satisfying even for filmgoers who don't care for the cuisine.

title: The Land Where the Ganges Flows
wiki_title: Jis Desh Men Ganga Behti Hai

title: Jo Jo Dancer, Your Life Is Calling
wiki_title: Jo Jo Dancer, Your Life Is Calling

title: Joan of Arc
awards: Nominated for 4 Golden Globes. Another 6 wins & 19 nominations.

title: Jobs
tomato_consensus: An ambitious but skin-deep portrait of an influential, complex figure, Jobs often has the feel of an over-sentimentalized made-for-TV biopic.

title: Joe's Bed-Stuy Barbershop: We Cut Heads
wiki_title: Joe's Bed-Stuy Barbershop: We Cut Heads

title: Joe Dirt
tomato_consensus: If you fall within the target audience of Joe Dirt, you may find it funny. Otherwise, the jokes will seem like a tired retread.

title: John Carter
tomato_consensus: While John Carter looks terrific and delivers its share of pulpy thrills, it also suffers from uneven pacing and occasionally incomprehensible plotting and characterization.

title: John Dies at the End
tomato_consensus: Some will find the darkly funny, genre-bending incoherence of John Dies at the End charming; some will feel its zany antics and gore lead to an unsatisfying payoff.

title: John Q
tomato_consensus: Washington's performance rises above the material, but John Q pounds the audience over the head with its message.

title: John Tucker Must Die
tomato_consensus: This derivitive teen comedy tries to go for cute when it could use more bite.

title: Johnny English
tomato_consensus: A tame spy spoof that elicits infrequent chuckles.

title: Johnny English Reborn
tomato_consensus: Arguably a marginal improvement on its mostly-forgotten predecessor, Johnny English Reborn nonetheless remains mired in broad, tired spy spoofing that wastes Rowan Atkinson's once considerable comedic talent.

title: Johnny Got His Gun
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Johnson Family Vacation
tomato_consensus: The poorly crafted Johnson Family Vacation squanders its talented cast in a bland family road comedy that draws unfavorable comparisons to Chevy Chase's Vacation movies.

title: Jonah: A VeggieTales Movie
tomato_consensus: Jonah teaches wholesome messages to children in a funny, bouncy package.

title: Jonah Hex
tomato_consensus: Josh Brolin gives it his best shot, but he can't keep the short, unfocused Jonah Hex from collapsing on the screen.

title: Jonah Who Will Be 25 in the Year 2000
wiki_title: Jonah Who Will Be 25 in the Year 2000

title: Jonas Brothers: The 3D Concert Experience
tomato_consensus: Jonas Brothers: The 3-D Concert Experience should please the brothers' adoring followers, but for non-converts, this concert film is largely flat and unenlightening.

title: Jonathan Livingston Seagull
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Joseph in Egypt
awards: Won 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 1 win & 8 nominations.

title: Joshua
tomato_consensus: Joshua is well-intentioned, but too heavy-handed.

title: Joshua
tomato_consensus: Though Joshua is ultimately too formulaic, its intelligence and suspenseful buildup heighten the overall creep factor.

title: Josie and the Pussycats
tomato_consensus: This live-action update of Josie and the Pussycats offers up bubbly, fluffy fun, but the constant appearance of product placements seems rather hypocritical.

title: Journey 2: The Mysterious Island
tomato_consensus: Aggressively unambitious, Journey 2 might thrill tween viewers, but most others will find it too intense for young audiences and too cartoonishly dull for adults.

title: Journey to the Center of the Earth
tomato_consensus: A silly but fun movie with everything you'd want from a sci-fi blockbuster -- heroic characters, menacing villains, monsters, big sets and special effects.
wiki_title: Journey to the Center of the Earth (1959 film)

title: Journey to the Center of the Earth
tomato_consensus: Modern visuals and an old fasioned storyline make this family adventure/comedy a fast-paced, kitschy ride.
wiki_title: Journey to the Center of the Earth 3-D

title: Journey to the West: Conquering the Demons
tomato_consensus: As sweet, silly, action-packed and ridiculous as director Steven Chow's best work, Journey to the West serves up dazzling action sequences while playing its disparate elements against each other with thrilling abandon.
wiki_title: Journey to the West: Conquering the Demons

title: Joy Ride
tomato_consensus: A well-constructed B-movie thriller, Joy Ride keeps up the necessary level of tension and chills. Critics also liked Zahn's performance as the goofball older brother.

title: Joyful Noise
tomato_consensus: Joyful Noise's musical numbers are solidly entertaining, and it benefits from Queen Latifah and Dolly Parton's sizable chemistry; unfortunately, they aren't enough to make up for the rest of the film.

title: Ju-on: The Grudge 2
tomato_consensus: The film grows more repetitive as it goes on, and as a result, the scares lessen.

title: Ju Dou
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Judge Dredd
tomato_consensus: Judge Dredd wants to be both a legitimate violent action flick and a parody of one, but director Danny Cannon fails to find the necessary balance to make it work.

title: Jules and Jim
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 3 wins.

title: Julie & Julia
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Boosted by Meryl Streep's charismatic performance as Julia Child, Julie and Julia is a light, but fairly entertaining culinary comedy.

title: Juliet of the Spirits
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 11 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Jumper
tomato_consensus: Featuring uninvolving characters and loose narrative, Jumper is an erratic action pic with little coherence and lackluster special effects.

title: Jumping the Broom
tomato_consensus: Its heart is in the right place -- and so is its appealing cast -- but Jumping the Broom is ultimately too cliched and thinly written to recommend.

title: Junebug
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 19 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Aided and abetted by a wonderful cast, director Phil Morrison transforms familiar material into an understated and resonant comedy.

title: Juno
tomato_consensus: One of the brightest, funniest comedies of the year, Juno's smart script and direction are matched by assured performances in a coming of age story with a 21st century twist.

title: Jurassic Park
tomato_consensus: Jurassic Park is a spectacle of special effects and life-like animatronics, with some of Spielberg's best sequences of sustained awe and sheer terror since Jaws.

title: Jurassic Park III
tomato_consensus: The dinos are as cool as ever, but there's too much of a "been there, done that" feel.

title: Just Friends
tomato_consensus: There are moments of mirth in this overly broad comedy, but mostly, Just Friends is just not that funny.

title: Just Go with It
tomato_consensus: Just Go With It may be slightly better than some entries in the recently dire rom-com genre, but that's far from a recommendation.

title: Just Like Heaven
tomato_consensus: Delightfully sweet like a lollipop, Just Like Heaven is a dreamy romantic comedy that may give you a toothache when it attempts to broach difficult end of life issues by throwing a cherry on top.

title: Just My Luck
tomato_consensus: Just My Luck is a screwball rom-com that fails to take advantage of Lindsay Lohan's considerable charm. The film (along with Robert Altman's A Prairie Home Companion) marks the end of Lohan's teen queen phase as she begins playing characters that are older, but not necessarily wiser. Lohan's character is supposedly cursed with bad luck, though the movie confuses misfortune with plain stupidity, leading Lohan into a long series of silly and senseless physical gags.

title: Just Visiting
tomato_consensus: This remake of the French comedy Les Visiteurs ends up being a middling, forgettable effort -- not as good as the original.

title: Justice League: The New Frontier
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 2 nominations.

title: Justin Bieber: Never Say Never
tomato_consensus: As a tour documentary, it's rather uninspired -- but as a 3D glimpse of a building pop culture phenomenon, Never Say Never is undeniably entertaining.

title: Juwanna Mann
tomato_consensus: With its tired premise, Juwanna Mann's jokes fall flat.

title: K-19: The Widowmaker
tomato_consensus: A gripping drama even though the filmmakers have taken liberties with the facts.

title: K-PAX
tomato_consensus: For those who have seen One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest or Starman, K-Pax may not hold anything new. The movie works best as a showcase for Kevin Spacey and Jeff Bridges.

title: Kaena: The Prophecy
tomato_consensus: Though Kaena: The Prophecy is visually inventive, its story is incoherent, derivative, and dull.

title: Kagemusha
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 20 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Kama Sutra: A Tale of Love
wiki_title: Kama Sutra: A Tale of Love

title: Kanal
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Kandahar
tomato_consensus: Eerily timely, Kandahar offers haunting images of a bleak land.

title: Karayuki-san, the Making of a Prostitute
wiki_title: Karayuki-san, the Making of a Prostitute

title: Kate & Leopold
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though Jackman charms, Kate and Leopold is bland and predictable, and the time travel scenario lacks inner logic.

title: Katy Perry: Part of Me
tomato_consensus: Katy Perry: Part of Me succeeds on the strengths of the pop star's genuine likability, inspiring work ethic, and dazzling stage show, even if it plays somewhat like a PR puff piece at times.

title: Kazaam
tomato_consensus: Crafted from a mix of genre clich?s, Kazaam doesn't know what kind of film it wants to be, and Shaq's larger-than-life charisma is stifled by rote filmmaking and an unimaginative story.

title: Keane
tomato_consensus: The scrutinizing camera angles of Keane might at first feel too close for comfort, but this powerful portrait of a man distraught by the abduction of his child plumbs the depths of mental illness and the corners of fleabag hotels in an intimate and touching examination of the seedier side of life.

title: Keeping Mum
tomato_consensus: The stellar cast, including Kristin Scott Thomas and Dame Maggie Smith, is certainly an asset, but this black comedy is too uneven.

title: Keeping the Faith
tomato_consensus: A dramedy featuring an unusual love triangle, Keeping the Faith is a perceptive look at how religion affects us in everyday life.

title: Mountain Patrol
tomato_consensus: In a setting both visually stunning and cruel, this Eastern film evokes the epic spirit of old-fashioned Westerns.

title: Kes
awards: Won 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Kick-Ass
tomato_consensus: Not for the faint of heart, Kick-Ass takes the comic adaptation genre to new levels of visual style, bloody violence, and gleeful profanity.

title: Kick-Ass 2
tomato_consensus: Kick-Ass 2 falls short in its attempt to emulate the original's unique blend of ultra-violence and ironic humor.

title: Kicking & Screaming
tomato_consensus: The script is mediocre and fails to give Ferrell a proper comedic showcase.

title: Kill Bill: Vol. 1
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 16 wins & 49 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kill Bill is nothing more than a highly stylized revenge flick. But what style!

title: Kill Bill: Vol. 2
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 12 wins & 39 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Talkier and less action-packed than Vol. 1, Kill Bill Vol. 2, nevertheless delivers the goods for those expecting a satisfying conclusion to this two-parter.

title: Kill List
tomato_consensus: Kill List is an expertly executed slow-burn crime thriller that thrives on tension before morphing into visceral horror.

title: Killer Elite
tomato_consensus: A rote, utterly disposable Jason Statham vehicle that just happens to have Clive Owen and Robert De Niro in it.

title: Killer Joe
tomato_consensus: Violent, darkly comic, and full of strong performances, Killer Joe proves William Friedkin hasn't lost his touch, even if the plot may be too lurid for some.

title: Killer Klowns from Outer Space
tomato_consensus: Killer Klowns from Outer Space's title promises darkly goofy fun -- and more often than not, the movie delivers.

title: Killer of Sheep
tomato_consensus: By turns funny, sad, and profound, Killer of Sheep offers a sympathetic and humane glimpse into inner-city life.

title: Killers
tomato_consensus: Dull, formulaic, and chemistry-free, Killers is an action/comedy that's largely bereft of thrills or laughs.

title: Killing Me Softly
tomato_consensus: Respected director Chen Kaige's first English-language film is a spectacularly misguided erotic thriller, with ludicrous plot twists and cringe-worthy dialogue.

title: Killing Them Softly
tomato_consensus: Killing Them Softly is a darkly comic, visceral thriller that doubles as a cautionary tale on capitalism, whose message is delivered with sledgehammer force.

title: Kind Hearts and Coronets
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: King's Ransom
tomato_consensus: Filled with crass dialogue, unlikable characters, and overdone slapstick gags, King's Ransom is an utterly inept would-be comedy.

title: King: A Filmed Record... Montgomery to Memphis
wiki_title: King: a Filmed Record...Montgomery To Memphis

title: King Arthur
tomato_consensus: The magic is gone, leaving a dreary, generic action movie.

title: King Kong
tomato_consensus: King Kong explores the soul of a monster -- making audiences scream and cry throughout the film -- in large part due to Kong's breakthrough special effects.

title: King Kong
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: King Kong
tomato_consensus: Featuring state-of-the-art special effects, terrific performances, and a majestic sense of spectacle, Peter Jackson's remake of King Kong is a potent epic that's faithful to the spirit of the 1933 original.

title: King of California
tomato_consensus: A quirky and often touching comedy about a mature teenager and her manic depressive father, King of California is a charming tale of familial relations and treasure hunting.

title: King of Kings
tomato_consensus: With enough narrative depth to anchor the expected spectacle, King of Kings is a true blessing for fans of Biblical epics.

title: King of the Hill
tomato_consensus: A subtle, affecting, character-driven coming-of-age story, King of the Hill is one of Steven Soderbergh's best and most criminally overlooked films.

title: Kingdom Come
tomato_consensus: While it has its moments, Kingdom Come is marred by a script that's low on laughs and uneven in tone.

title: Kingdom of Heaven
tomato_consensus: Although it's an objective and handsomely presented take on the Crusades, Kingdom of Heaven lacks depth.

title: Kingpin
tomato_consensus: Kingpin has its moments, but they're often offset by an eagerness to descend into vulgar mean-spiritedness.

title: Kinky Boots
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kinky Boots relies heavily on the Full Monty formula of Britcoms, while playing it too safe in a desperate attempt not to offend. Ejiofor's performance is its redeeming virtue.

title: Kinsey
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 17 wins & 33 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A biopic of the sex researcher is hailed as adventurous, clever, and subversive, with fine performances by Liam Neeson and Laura Linney.

title: Kirikou and the Sorceress
tomato_consensus: Kirikou and the Sorceress is a beautifully uplifting throwback to a simpler animated era, with refreshingly unique art and a timeless soundtrack.

title: Kiss Kiss Bang Bang
tomato_consensus: Tongue-in-cheek satire blends well with entertaining action and spot-on performances in this dark, eclectic neo-noir homage.

title: Kiss Me Deadly
tomato_consensus: An intriguing, wonderfully subversive blend of art and commerce, Kiss Me Deadly is an influential noir classic.

title: Kiss of Death
tomato_consensus: An outstanding ensemble cast propels Kiss of Death, a noir-ish crime thriller that's slick and big on atmosphere, even if its script may only provide sporadic bursts of tension.

title: Kiss of the Dragon
tomato_consensus: A formulaic actioner that's sure to please action fans. Those looking for plot, believability, or character development will have difficulty finding them.

title: Kiss the Blood Off My Hands
wiki_title: Kiss the Blood Off My Hands

title: Kissing Jessica Stein
tomato_consensus: A trite but refreshing and comical spin on nature of love.

title: Kit Kittredge: An American Girl
tomato_consensus: Refreshingly sweet and sincere, Kit's doll-and-book-inspired do-good mystery may be geared towards the tween girl but will please audiences of all ages.

title: Kitchen Stories
tomato_consensus: By turns touching and funny, this Norwegian import offers quietly absorbing commentary on modern life and friendship.

title: Kites
tomato_consensus: Thoroughly overwrought in true Bollywood fashion, Kites is deeply flawed -- and too effervescently charming to resist.

title: Klimt
tomato_consensus: Klimt is handsomely filmed, but the blurred storyline and substandard performances prove its undoing.

title: Knife in the Water
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Knight and Day
tomato_consensus: It's pure formula, but thanks to its breezy pace and a pair of charming performances from Tom Cruise and Cameron Diaz, Knight and Day offers some agreeably middle-of-the-road summer action.

title: Knowing
tomato_consensus: Knowing has some interesting ideas and a couple good scenes, but it's weighted down by its absurd plot and over-seriousness.

title: Kon-Tiki
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A well-crafted retelling of an epic true story, Kon Tiki is a throwback to old-school adventure filmmaking that's exciting and entertaining in spite of its by-the-book plotting.

title: Kotch
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Kramer vs. Kramer
tomato_consensus: The divorce subject isn't as shocking, but the film is still a thoughtful, well-acted drama that resists the urge to take sides or give easy answers.

title: The Emperor's New Groove 2: Kronk's New Groove
The Wonderful World of Captain Kuhio
Kundun
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Kung Fu Hustle
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 22 wins & 32 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kung Fu Hustle blends special effects, martial arts, and the Looney Toons to hilarious effect.

title: Kung Fu Panda
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Kung Fu Panda has a familiar message, but the pleasing mix of humor, swift martial arts action, and colorful animation makes for winning Summer entertainment.

title: Kung Fu Panda 2
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The storyline arc may seem a tad familiar to fans of the original, but Kung Fu Panda 2 offers enough action, comedy, and visual sparkle to compensate.

title: Kung Pow: Enter the Fist
tomato_consensus: A short sketch's worth of jokes stretched into a full-length feature.

title: Ghost Stories
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Licence to Kill
tomato_consensus: License to Kill is a sharp action picture -- it's darker than many of the other entries, with Timothy Dalton playing Bond with intensity -- but it still has some solid chases and fight scenes.

title: Live and Let Die
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While not one of the highest-rated Bond films, Live and Let Die finds Roger Moore adding his stamp to the series with flashes of style and an improved sense of humor.

title: Love Me If You Dare
tomato_consensus: The romantic leads are too obnoxious and self-centered to generate interest or sympathy.

title: Moonraker
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Featuring one of the series' more ludicrous plots but outfitted with primo gadgets and spectacular sets, Moonraker is both silly and entertaining.

title: Octopussy
tomato_consensus: Despite a couple of electrifying action sequences, Octopussy is a formulaic, anachronistic Bond outing.

title: On Her Majesty's Secret Service
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: George Lazenby's only appearance as 007 is a fine entry in the series, featuring one of the most intriguing Bond girls in Tracy di Vincenzo (Diana Rigg), breathtaking visuals, and some great ski chases.

title: Quantum of Solace
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 4 wins & 22 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Brutal and breathless, Quantum Of Solace delivers tender emotions along with frenetic action. Not as good as franchise reboot Casino Royale, but still an impressive entry to the Bond canon.

title: Skyfall
tomato_consensus: Sam Mendes brings Bond surging back with a smart, sexy, riveting action thriller that qualifies as one of the best 007 films to date.

title: The Jacket
tomato_consensus: The Jacket is a case of creepy style over substance.

title: The Jane Austen Book Club
tomato_consensus: Though at times formulaic and sentimental, Jane Austen Book Club succeeds on the strength of its likable ensemble cast. Even those not familiar with Jane Austen's work may find much to enjoy this lighthearted romance.

title: The Jazz Singer
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The Joneses
tomato_consensus: It doesn't pursue its subversive premise as far as it should, but The Joneses benefits from its timely satire of consumer culture -- as well as a pair of strong performances from David Duchovny and Demi Moore.

title: The Joy Luck Club
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The Jungle Book
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With expressive animation, fun characters, and catchy songs, The Jungle Book endures as a crowd-pleasing Disney classic.

title: The Jungle Book 2
tomato_consensus: This inferior rehash of The Jungle Book should have gone straight to video.

title: The Karate Kid, Part II
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 2 nominations.

title: The Karate Kid
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Utterly predictable and wholly of its time, but warm, sincere, and difficult to resist, due in large part to Pat Morita and Ralph Macchio's relaxed chemistry.

title: The Karate Kid
tomato_consensus: It may not be as powerful as the 1984 edition, but the 2010 Karate Kid delivers a surprisingly satisfying update on the original.

title: The Kid & I
tomato_consensus: Well-intentioned but sappy, The Kid & I is a strange hybrid of comedy and cinema verite.

title: The Kid Stays in the Picture
wiki_title: The Kid Stays in the Picture

title: The Killer Inside Me
tomato_consensus: The Killer Inside Me is stylish and beautifully shot, but Michael Winterbottom's distance from his characters robs this often brutally violent film of crucial emotional context.

title: The Killers
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Though it can't best Robert Siodmak's classic 1946 version, Don Siegel's take on the Ernest Hemingway story stakes out its own violent territory, and offers a terrifically tough turn from Lee Marvin.

title: The Killing of a Chinese Bookie
wiki_title: The Killing of a Chinese Bookie

title: The King's Speech
tomato_consensus: Colin Firth gives a masterful performance in The King's Speech, a predictable but stylishly produced and rousing period drama.

title: The King
tomato_consensus: This disturbing film about the past coming back demanding its due evokes classical tragedy, but is ultimately too heavy-handed.

title: The King of Comedy
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Largely misunderstood upon its release, The King of Comedy today looks eerily prescient, and features a fine performance by Robert DeNiro as a strangely sympathetic psychopath.

title: The King of Kong: A Fistful of Quarters
tomato_consensus: The King of Kong is funny and compelling with more than a few poignant insights into human behavior. Director Seth Gordon presents the dueling King Kong players in all their obsessive complexity and with perfectly al dente observations.
wiki_title: The King of Kong: A Fistful of Quarters

title: The Kingdom
tomato_consensus: While providing several top-notch action scenes, The Kingdom ultimately collapses under the weight of formula and muddled politics.

title: The Kings of Summer
tomato_consensus: Thanks to charming performances and endearingly off-kilter spirit, The Kings of Summer proves to be a slight, sweet entry in the crowded coming-of-age genre.

title: The Kite Runner
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite some fine performances, The Kite Runner is just shy of rendering the magic of the novel on to the big screen.

title: The Kites Flying in the Sky
wiki_title: The Kites Flying in the Sky

title: The Knack... and How to Get It
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 5 wins & 7 nominations.
wiki_title: The Knack...and How to Get It

title: The Krays
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Living Daylights
tomato_consensus: In The Living Daylights, newcomer Timothy Dalton plays James Bond with more debonair seriousness than preceding installments, and the result, is energetic, exciting, and occasionally weighty.

title: The Lost World: Jurassic Park
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 16 nominations.

title: The Man with the Golden Gun
tomato_consensus: A middling Bond film, The Man With the Golden Gun suffers from double entendre-laden dialogue, a noteworthy lack of gadgets, and a villain that overshadows 007.
wiki_title: The Man with the Golden Gun (film)

title: The Next Karate Kid
tomato_consensus: The Next Karate Kid is noteworthy for giving audiences the chance to see a pre-Oscars Hilary Swank, but other than a typically solid performance from Pat Morita, this unnecessary fourth installment in the franchise has very little to offer.

title: The Spy Who Loved Me
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though it hints at the absurdity to come in later installments, The Spy Who Loved Me's sleek style, menacing villains, and sly wit make it the best of the Roger Moore era.

title: Thunderball
tomato_consensus: Lavishly rendered set pieces and Sean Connery's enduring charm make Thunderball a big, fun adventure, even if it doesn't quite measure up to the series' previous heights.

title: Tomorrow Never Dies
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 6 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A competent, if sometimes by-the-numbers entry to the 007 franchise, Tomorrow Never Dies may not boast the most original plot but its action sequences are genuinely thrilling.

title: You Only Live Twice
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: With exotic locales, impressive special effects, and a worthy central villain, You Only Live Twice overcomes a messy and implausible story to deliver another memorable early Bond flick.

title: A League of Their Own
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 6 wins & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Sentimental and light, but still thoroughly charming, A League of Their Own is buoyed by solid performances from a wonderful cast.

title: A Little Princess
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Alfonso Cuar?n adapts Frances Hodgson Burnett's novel with a keen sense of magic realism, vividly recreating the world of childhood as seen through the characters.

title: A Lizard in a Woman's Skin
wiki_title: A Lizard in a Woman's Skin

title: A Love Song for Bobby Long
wiki_title: A Love Song for Bobby Long

title: L.A. Confidential
tomato_consensus: Taut pacing, brilliantly dense writing and Oscar-worthy acting combine to produce a smart, popcorn-friendly thrill ride.

title: L.I.E.
tomato_consensus: L.I.E. is a well-acted and unsettling look at a boy's relationship with a pedophile.

title: La Bamba
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: Luna
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.

title: Labyrinth
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While it's arguably more interesting on a visual level, Labyrinth provides further proof of director Jim Henson's boundless imagination.

title: Lacombe, Lucien
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Ladies and Gentlemen, the Fabulous Stains
wiki_title: Ladies and Gentlemen, The Fabulous Stains

title: Ladies in Lavender
tomato_consensus: A charming, if slight, period drama that quietly showcases fine performances by its two stars.

title: Lady Caroline Lamb
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 nomination.

title: Lady Chatterley
tomato_consensus: Tasteful, poetic, yet sexually forthright, Lady Chatterley skillfully translates its source novel's high-art erotica onto the big screen.

title: Lady Sings the Blues
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Lady and the Tramp
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: A nostalgic charmer, Lady and the Tramp's token sweetness is mighty but the songs and richly colored animation are technically superb and make for a memorable experience.

title: Lady and the Tramp II: Scamp's Adventure
wiki_title: Lady and the Tramp II: Scamp's Adventure

title: Lady in the Water
tomato_consensus: A far-fetched story with little suspense and unconvincing scenarios, Lady In The Water feels contrived, pretentious, and rather silly.

title: Ladyhawke
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Lagaan: Once Upon a Time in India
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 44 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Lagaan is lavish, rousing entertainment in the old-fashioned tradition of Hollywood musicals.

title: Lights in the Dusk
tomato_consensus: From its brilliant cinematography to its compassionate characters, Lights in the Dusk is another successful exercise in deadpan minimalist comedy from Aki Kaurism?ki.

title: Lake Placid
tomato_consensus: Faux horror schtick fails to elicit any laughs or scares.

title: Lakeview Terrace
tomato_consensus: This thriller about a menacing cop wreaking havoc on his neighbors is tense enough but threatens absurdity when it enters into excessive potboiler territory.

title: Lan Yu
tomato_consensus: A well-crafted love story, but it may be too simplistic for some.

title: Land of the Dead
tomato_consensus: George A. Romero's latest entry in his much-vaunted Dead series is not as fresh as his genre-inventing original, Night of the Living Dead. But Land of the Dead does deliver on the gore and zombies-feasting-on-flesh action.

title: Land of the Lost
tomato_consensus: Only loosely based on the original TV series, Land of the Lost is decidedly less kid-friendly and feels more like a series of inconsistent sketches than a cohesive adventure comedy.

title: Lantana
tomato_consensus: Lantana is an intricately plotted character study that quietly shines with authenticity.

title: Lara Croft: Tomb Raider
tomato_consensus: Angelina Jolie is perfect for the role of Lara Croft, but even she can't save the movie from a senseless plot and action sequences with no emotional impact.

title: Lara Croft Tomb Raider: The Cradle of Life
tomato_consensus: Though the sequel is an improvement over the first movie, it's still lacking in thrills.
wiki_title: Lara Croft Tomb Raider: The Cradle of Life

title: Larry Crowne
tomato_consensus: Despite the relaxed, easy chemistry of stars Tom Hanks and Julia Roberts, Larry Crowne is surprisingly bland and conventional.

title: Larry the Cable Guy: Health Inspector
tomato_consensus: An aggressively lowbrow vehicle for its titular star, this gross-out comedy fails to "git-r-done."
wiki_title: Larry the Cable Guy: Health Inspector

title: Lars and the Real Girl
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Lars and the Real Girl could've so easily been a one-joke movie. But the talented cast, a great script, and direction never condescends to its character or the audience.

title: Lassie
tomato_consensus: A beautifully-made retelling of the classic collie tale, one need not be a dog-lover to fall for Lassie.

title: Fitzgerald
awards: Nominated for 2 Primetime Emmys. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Last Chance Harvey
tomato_consensus: Last Chance Harvey is an above-average story that graduates to potent romantic drama based on the chemistry and charm of its top-notch performers.

title: Last Days
tomato_consensus: While the minimalist style is not for all viewers, those who prefer experimentalism will find Last Days hypnotic.

title: Last Holiday

awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Last Vegas
tomato_consensus: The cast of Last Vegas keep things amiably watchable, but the film is mostly a mellower Hangover retread for the older set.

wiki_title: Lavoura Arcaica (To the left of the father)

title: Law Abiding Citizen
tomato_consensus: Unnecessarily violent and unflinchingly absurd, Law Abiding Citizen is plagued by subpar acting and a story that defies reason.

title: Lawless

tomato_consensus: The epic of all epics, Lawrence of Arabia cements director David Lean's status in the filmmaking pantheon with nearly four hours of grand scope, brilliant performances, and beautiful cinematography.

tomato_consensus: A bland and forgettable copy of Adam's Rib.

title: Layer Cake
tomato_consensus: A stylized, electric British crime thriller.

title: Leatherface: Texas Chainsaw Massacre III
wiki_title: Leatherface: The Texas Chainsaw Massacre III

title: Leatherheads
tomato_consensus: Despite a good premise and strong cast, this pro football romcom is half screwball and half fumble.

title: Leaves of Grass

tomato_consensus: Gut-wrenching and emotionally affecting,  Lee Daniels' The Butler overcomes an uneven narrative thanks to strong performances from an all-star cast.

tomato_consensus: Poor production values, slow pacing, and an implausible story makes Left Behind a movie only for the faithful.

wiki_title: Let's All Go To the Lobby

title: Let's Go to Prison
tomato_consensus: Let's Go to Prison is guilty on all counts of cliched setups, base humor, and failure to ellicit laughs.

title: Let's Make Love

title: Lethal Weapon

title: Lethal Weapon 2

wiki_title: Letter from an Unknown Woman (2004 film)

title: Letter to Jane: An Investigation About a Still

title: Life
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Entertaining if not over-the-top humor from a solid comic duo provides plenty of laughs.

title: Life During Wartime
tomato_consensus: With Life During Wartime, Todd Solondz delivers an unexpected semi-sequel to Happiness in typically uncompromising fashion.

title: Life Is Beautiful

title: Life as a House
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Life Is a Long Quiet River
wiki_title: Life is a long quiet river

title: Like Water for Chocolate
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 25 wins & 10 nominations.

awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 12 nominations.
