tomato_consensus: Shallow, sappy, and dull, New Year's Eve assembles a star-studded cast for no discernible purpose.

title: New York, I Love You
tomato_consensus: Like many anthologies, New York, I Love You has problems of consistency, but it isn't without its moments.

title: New York, New York
awards: Nominated for 4 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: New York Doll
tomato_consensus: Arthur Kane is a fascinating subject in what ultimately proves to be a touching, bittersweet documentary.

title: New York Minute
tomato_consensus: Feels more like a calculated product designed to expand the Olsens' brand than an actual movie. Also, it contains ethnic stereotyping and sexual innuendo.

title: New in Town
tomato_consensus: Cliched and short on charm, New In Town is a pat genre exercise that fails to bring the necessary heat to its Minnesota setting.

title: Next
tomato_consensus: Numerous plot holes and poorly motivated characters prevent Next from being the thought-provoking sci-fi flick it could've been.

title: Next Day Air
tomato_consensus: Rife with half-baked jokes and excessive violence, Next Day Air is an uninspired stoner comedy.

title: Next Friday
tomato_consensus: Next Friday lacks the fun of the original Friday. The movie is messy and plotless and relies on unfunny vulgar gags.

title: Next Stop Wonderland
tomato_consensus: Endearing performances create characters you care about.

title: Nicholas Nickleby
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Thanks to a strong cast of experienced actors and director Douglas McGrath's steady hand, Nicholas Nickleby is a worthy and respectful adaptation of the Dickens novel.

title: Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist
tomato_consensus: Nick and Norah's Infinite Playlist combines a pair of charming leads, the classic New York backdrop, and a sweet soundtrack.

title: Night Shift
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.

title: Night Watch
tomato_consensus: This Russian horror/fantasy film pits darkness and light against each other using snazzy CGI visuals to create an extraordinary atmosphere of a dank, gloomy city wrestling with dread.

title: Night at the Museum
tomato_consensus: Parents might call this either a spectacle-filled adventure or a shallow and vapid CG-fest, depending on whether they choose to embrace this on the same level as their kids.

title: Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian
tomato_consensus: Night at the Museum: Battle at the Smithsonian is busy enough to keep the kids interested but the slapstick goes overboard and the special effects (however well executed) throw the production into mania.
wiki_title: Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian

title: Night of the Living Dead
tomato_consensus: George A. Romero's debut set the template for the zombie film, and features tight editing, realistic gore, and a sly political undercurrent.

title: Night of the Living Dead
wiki_title: Night of the Living Dead (1990 film)

title: Nights in Rodanthe
tomato_consensus: Derivative and schmaltzy, Nicholas Sparks' Nights in Rodanthe is strongly mottled by contrivances that even the charisma of stars Diane Lane and Richard Gere can't repair.

title: Nil by Mouth
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 8 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Nim's Island
tomato_consensus: Despite good intentions, Nim's Island flounders under an implausible storyline, simplistic stock characters, and distracting product placement.

title: Ninja Assassin
tomato_consensus: Overly serious and incomprehensibly edited, Ninja Assassin fails to live up to the promise of its title.

title: Ninotchka
tomato_consensus: With Greta Garbo proving her comedy chops in the twilight of her career, Ninotchka is a can't-miss classic.

title: Nixon
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 11 wins & 8 nominations.

title: No Country for Old Men
tomato_consensus: Bolstered by powerful lead performances from Javier Bardem, Josh Brolin, and Tommy Lee Jones, No Country for Old Men finds the Coen brothers spinning cinematic gold out of Cormac McCarthy's grim, darkly funny novel.

title: No Dessert, Dad, Till You Mow the Lawn
wiki_title: No Dessert, Dad, till You Mow the Lawn

title: No Impact Man: The Documentary
tomato_consensus: Half enviro-saving doc, half publicity stunt, No Impact Man is inspiring and fun to both casual activists and hardcore recyclers.

title: No Man's Land
country: Bosnia and Herzegovina, France, Slovenia, Italy, UK, Belgium
tomato_consensus: Bleak and darkly humorous, No Man's Land vividly illustrates the absurdity of war.

title: No Reservations
tomato_consensus: This romantic comedy may look good on paper, but it's too predictable and melancholy for the genre.

title: No Strings Attached
tomato_consensus: It benefits from the presence of Natalie Portman and director Ivan Reitman's steady hand, but No Strings Attached doesn't have the courage or conviction to follow through on its ribald premise.

title: No Way Out
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: No Way Out
tomato_consensus: Roger Donaldson's modern spin on the dense, stylish suspense films of the 1940s features fine work from Gene Hackman and Sean Young, as well as the career-making performance that made Kevin Costner a star.

title: Nobel Son
tomato_consensus: Despite the best efforts of a strong cast, Nobel Son is over-plotted and self-consciously odd.

title: Nobody's Fool
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It's solidly directed by Robert Benton and stacked with fine performances from an impressive cast, but above all, Nobody's Fool is a showcase for some of Paul Newman's best late-period work.

title: Nobody Knows
tomato_consensus: Tragic and haunting, a beautifully heart-wrenching portrait of child abandonment.

title: Noi the Albino
tomato_consensus: A darkly humorous, quirky coming-of-age film, enhanced by its Icelandic setting.

title: Nomad: The Warrior
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 nomination.

title: Norbit
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Coming off his Oscar-nominated performance in Dreamgirls, the talented-but-inconsistent Eddie Murphy plays three roles in Norbit, a cruel, crass, stereotype-filled comedy that's more depressing than funny.

title: Normal
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 13 nominations.

title: North Country
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though sometimes melodramatic and formulaic, North Country is nonetheless a rousing, powerful story of courage and humanity.

title: North Dallas Forty
tomato_consensus: Muddled overall, but perceptive and brutally realistic, North Dallas Forty also benefits from strong performances by Nick Nolte and Charles Durning. Football fans will likely find it fascinating.

title: North by Northwest
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Gripping, suspenseful, and visually iconic, this late-period Hitchcock classic laid the groundwork for countless action thrillers to follow.

title: Northfork
tomato_consensus: Visually poetic, but may be too dramatically inert for some.

title: Nosferatu
tomato_consensus: One of the silent era's most influential masterpieces, Nosferatu's eerie, gothic feel -- and a chilling performance from Max Shrek as the vampire -- set the template for the horror films that followed.

title: Nosferatu the Vampyre
tomato_consensus: Stunning visuals from Werner Herzog and an intense portrayal of the famed bloodsucker from Klaus Kinski make this remake of Nosferatu a horror classic in its own right.

title: Not Another Teen Movie
tomato_consensus: NATM has some funny moments, but the movie requires the audience to have familiarity with the movies being spoofed and a tolerance for toilet and sexual humor to be truly effective.

title: Not Easily Broken
tomato_consensus: Though well-intentioned, Not Easily Broken is bogged down by melodramatic plotting and stereotypical characters.

title: Not as a Stranger
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Notes on a Scandal
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 38 nominations.
tomato_consensus: In this sharp psychological thriller, Judi Dench and Cate Blanchett give fierce, memorable performances as two schoolteachers locked in a battle of wits.

title: Nothing But the Best
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Nothing But the Truth
tomato_consensus: A well-crafted political thriller, Nothing But the Truth features a strong cast that helps the real-life drama make an effortless transition to the big screen.
wiki_title: Nothing but the Truth (2008 American film)

title: Notorious
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Sublime direction from Hitchcock, and terrific central performances from Ingrid Bergman and Cary Grant make this a bona-fide classic worthy of a re-visit.

title: Notorious
tomato_consensus: A biopic that lacks the luster of its subject, Notorious is generic rise-and-fall fare that still functions as a primer for those less familiar with the work and life of the hip hop icon.

title: Notting Hill
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 12 wins & 14 nominations.

title: November
tomato_consensus: Murky and too artsy for its own good, November ends up being a case of style with little substance.

title: Novocaine
tomato_consensus: The quirky Novocaine flirts with both dark comedy and noir suspense, but the result is a jarring mix of tones which never quite mesh.

title: Now You See Me
tomato_consensus: Now You See Me's thinly sketched characters and scattered plot rely on sleight of hand from the director to distract audiences.

title: Nowhere Boy
awards: Nominated for 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 5 wins & 18 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Don't expect any musical insights, but this look at John Lennon's early life benefits from its restrained, low-key approach and some fine acting from Aaron Johnson.

title: Nowhere in Africa
tomato_consensus: A visually lovely epic with compelling, three-dimensional characters.

title: Nine Queens
tomato_consensus: Deliciously twist-filled, Nine Queens is a clever and satisfying crime caper.

title: Nurse Betty
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Quirky in the best sense of the word, Nurse Betty finds director Neil LaBute corralling a talented cast in service of a sharp, imaginative script.

title: Nutty Professor II: The Klumps
tomato_consensus: While Eddie Murphy is still hilarious as the entire Klump family, the movie falls apart because of uneven pacing, a poor script, and skits that rely on being gross rather than funny.

title: O
tomato_consensus: Though well-intentioned and serious in its exploration of teen violence, O is an uneven experiment that doesn't quite succeed.

title: O Brother, Where Art Thou?
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 31 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though not as good as Coen brothers' classics such as Blood Simple, the delightfully loopy O Brother, Where Art Thou? is still a lot of fun.

title: The Man Who Copied
tomato_consensus: Though it has some nice moments, The Man Who Copied spins out of control by the second half and wears out its welcome.

title: O Lucky Man!
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Oasis
tomato_consensus: Lead actress Moon So-ri's stand out performance gives this harrowing film much of its power.

title: The Treasure of the Living Dead
Colonel Redl
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Oblivion
tomato_consensus: Visually striking but thinly scripted, Oblivion benefits greatly from its strong production values and an excellent performance from Tom Cruise.

title: Observe and Report
tomato_consensus: Though it has a mean streak, and does not cater to all tastes, Observe and Report has gut-busting laughs and a fully committed Seth Rogen in irresistible form.

title: Obsessed
tomato_consensus: The inevitable Fatal Attraction comparisons aside, Obsessed is a generic, toothless thriller both instantly predictable and instantly forgettable.

title: Obsession
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Ocean's Eleven
tomato_consensus: As fast-paced, witty, and entertaining as it is star-studded and coolly stylish, Ocean's Eleven offers a well-seasoned serving of popcorn entertainment.

title: Ocean's Thirteen
tomato_consensus: Ocean's Thirteen reverts to the formula of the first installment, and the result is another slick and entertaining heist film.

title: Ocean's Twelve
tomato_consensus: While some have found the latest star-studded heist flick to be a fun, glossy star vehicle, others declare it's lazy, self-satisfied and illogical.

title: October (Ten Days that Shook the World)
wiki_title: October: Ten Days That Shook the World

title: October Sky
tomato_consensus: Rich in sweet sincerity, intelligence, and good old-fashioned inspirational drama, October Sky is a coming-of-age story with a heart to match its Hollywood craftsmanship.

title: Bo ming chan dao duo ming qiang
Of Gods and Men
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 13 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Patient and restrained, Of Gods and Men asks deep, profound questions that will linger in the audience's mind long after the movie.

title: Of Human Bondage
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.

title: Off the Map
tomato_consensus: Excellent performances mark this leisurely paced film.

title: Office Space
tomato_consensus: Mike Judge lampoons the office grind with its inspired mix of sharp dialogue and witty one-liners.

title: Oh! What a Lovely War
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 10 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Oh, God!
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Old Dogs
tomato_consensus: Its cast tries hard, but Old Dogs is a predictable, nearly witless attempt at physical comedy and moral uplift that misses the mark on both counts.

title: Old Joy
tomato_consensus: A serene, melancholy beauty permeates this meditative portrait of deep friendship and faded glory.

title: Old School
tomato_consensus: While not consistently funny, the movie does have its moments.

title: Oldboy
tomato_consensus: Violent and definitely not for the squeamish, Park Chan-Wook's visceral Oldboy is a strange, powerful tale of revenge.

title: Oldboy
tomato_consensus: Suitably grim and bloody yet disappointingly safe and shallow, Spike Lee's Oldboy remake neither surpasses the original nor adds anything new to its impressive legacy.

title: Oliver!
tomato_consensus: It has aged somewhat awkwardly, but the performances are inspired, the songs are memorable, and the film is undeniably influential.

title: Oliver & Company
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Oliver & Company is a decidedly lesser effort in the Disney canon, with lackluster songs, stiff animation, and a thoroughly predictable plot.

title: Oliver Twist
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Olympia Part One: Festival of the Nations
Olympus Has Fallen
tomato_consensus: It's far from original, but Olympus Has Fallen benefits from Antoine Fuqua's tense direction and a strong performance from Gerard Butler -- which might just be enough for action junkies.

title: On a Clear Day
tomato_consensus: Another blue-collar inspirational feel-good British dramedy, On A Clear Day succeeds on the strength of lead actor Peter Mullan's performance and Gaby Dellal's competent direction.

title: On a Clear Day You Can See Forever
wiki_title: On a Clear Day You Can See Forever (film)

title: On the Beach
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 6 nominations.

title: On the Line
tomato_consensus: An inept attempt at a romantic comedy aimed at 'Nsync fans.

title: On the Occasion of Remembering the Turning Gate
wiki_title: On the Occasion of Remembering the Turning Gate

title: On the Riviera
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: On the Road
tomato_consensus: Beautiful to look at but a bit too respectfully crafted, On the Road doesn't capture the energy and inspiration of Jack Kerouac's novel.

title: Up in the Cherry Tree
wiki_title: On the Top of the Cherry Tree

title: On the Waterfront
tomato_consensus: With his electrifying performance in Elia Kazan's thought-provoking, expertly constructed melodrama, Marlon Brando redefined the possibilities of acting for film and helped permanently alter the cinematic landscape.

title: Once
tomato_consensus: A charming, captivating tale of love and music, Once sets the standard for the modern musical. And with Dublin as its backdrop, Once is fun and fresh.

wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in America

title: Once Upon a Time in Anatolia
wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in Anatolia

title: Once Upon a Time in China
wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in China

wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in China II

wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in China VI

title: The Spirit of Jeet Kune Do
wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in High School

title: Once Upon a Time in Mexico
tomato_consensus: Violent, pulpy, loopy fun, with Depp stealing the show.
wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in Mexico

title: Once Upon a Time in the Midlands
tomato_consensus: Though the concept is interesting and quirky, the drama fails to deliver.
wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in the Midlands

title: Once Upon a Time in the West
tomato_consensus: A landmark Sergio Leone spaghetti western masterpiece featuring a classic Morricone score.
wiki_title: Once Upon a Time in the West

title: Once in a Lifetime: The Extraordinary Story of the New York Cosmos
wiki_title: Once in a Lifetime: The Extraordinary Story of the New York Cosmos

title: Once in the Life
tomato_consensus: Once in a Life is a promising directorial effort by Laurence Fishburne. But the story is too conventional and similar to the many ghetto action/dramas that come before it.

title: Ondine
tomato_consensus: Flawed but charming, Ondine reaffirms writer-director Neil Jordan's gift for myth, magic, and wonder.

title: One-Eyed Jacks
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: One Direction: This Is Us
tomato_consensus: It's mostly for the converted, but One Direction: This Is Us will be fun for fans -- and it offers just enough slickly edited concert footage to entertain the casual viewer.

title: One Fine Day
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 5 nominations.

title: 101 Dalmatians
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With plenty of pooches and a memorable villain (Cruella De Vil), this is one of Disney's most enduring, entertaining animated films.

title: One Missed Call
tomato_consensus: One of the weakest entries in the J-horror remake sweepstakes, One Missed Call is undone by bland performances and shopworn shocks.

title: One Night at McCool's
tomato_consensus: Critics say this blend of film noir and screwball comedy seems to think itself more clever and hip than it actually is. Also, the crucial femme fatale role needs a better, more mature actress than Tyler.

title: One Potato, Two Potato
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: One True Thing
tomato_consensus: Solid performances lift this drama to a higher level.

title: One for the Money
tomato_consensus: Dull and unfunny, One For the Money wastes Katherine Heigl's talents on a stunningly generic comic thriller.

title: One from the Heart
tomato_consensus: A misfire from director Francis Ford Coppola.

title: One of Our Aircraft Is Missing
wiki_title: One of Our Aircraft Is Missing

title: Ong-bak
tomato_consensus: While Ong-Bak: The Thai Warrior may be no great shakes as a movie, critics are hailing the emergence of a new star in Tony Jaa, whose athletic performance is drawing comparisons with Bruce Lee, Jackie Chan, and Jet Li.

title: Ong-bak 2
tomato_consensus: It suffers from comparisons to its predecessor -- not to mention Tony Jaa's less-than-nimble direction -- but Ong Bak 2 has all the extravagant violence and playful style that fans of the original will expect.

title: Only God Forgives
tomato_consensus: Director Refn remains as visually stylish as ever, but Only God Forgives fails to add enough narrative smarts or relatable characters to ground its beautifully filmed depravity.

title: Only When I Laugh
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Open Hearts
tomato_consensus: Pulsing with honesty, this film lays bare the rawness of human emotion with a story made all the more believable thanks to its gritty, low-budget approach.

title: Open Range
tomato_consensus: Greatly benefiting from the tremendous chemistry between Kevin Costner and Robert Duvall, Open Range is a sturdy modern Western with classic roots.

title: Open Season
tomato_consensus: Open Season is a cliched palette of tired jokes and CG animal shenanigans that have been seen multiple times this cinematic year.

title: Open Water
tomato_consensus: A low budget thriller with some intense moments.

title: Opening Night
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Opening Night is as dense and difficult as one would expect from John Cassavetes, but even the director's detractors will be unable to deny the power of Gena Rowlands' performance.

title: Operation Petticoat
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Or
tomato_consensus: Prostitution and its effect on a mother-daughter relationship are told in a naturalistic and nonjudgmental style, building to a powerful conclusion.

title: Orange County
tomato_consensus: Smarter than the average teen movie, but a little on the unmemorable side.

title: Ordinary People
tomato_consensus: Though shot through with bitterness and sorrow, Robert Redford's directorial debut is absorbing and well-acted.

title: Original Sin
tomato_consensus: Laughably melodramatic, Original Sin features bad acting, bad dialogue, and bad plotting.

title: Orlando
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Orphan
tomato_consensus: While it has moments of dark humor and the requisite scares, Orphan fails to build on its interesting premise and degenerates into a formulaic, sleazy horror/thriller.

title: Orpheus
tomato_consensus: Heavy with symbolism and deliberately paced, Orpheus may not be for everyone -- but as an example of Jean Cocteau's eccentric genius, it's all but impossible not to recommend.

title: Osama
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Osama is bitterly honest, deeply disturbing, and utterly worth watching.

title: Oscar and Lucinda
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Oslo, August 31st
tomato_consensus: An upfront study of a drug addict confronting his demons, Oslo, August 31st makes this dark journey worthwhile with fantastic directing and equally fantastic acting.

title: Osmosis Jones
tomato_consensus: The animated portion of Osmosis is zippy and fun, but the live-action portion is lethargic.

title: Greedy Guts
tomato_consensus: Though rather overlong, Little Otik is a whimsical, bizarre treat.

title: Othello
tomato_consensus: This ragged take on Othello may take liberties with the source material, but Orson Welles' genius never fails to impress.

title: Othello
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.

title: Our Idiot Brother
tomato_consensus: It's decidedly uneven, but like Paul Rudd's performance in the title role, Our Idiot Brother is too charming to resist.

title: Our Man in Havana
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 nomination.

title: Our Song
tomato_consensus: Graced with such a realistic feel that it resembles a documentary, Our Song is a sensitive portrayal of three teenage girls.

title: Out Cold
tomato_consensus: A party movie that substitutes surfs for snow, Out Cold will leave viewers just that with its gross-out humor and sophomoric plot.

title: Out of Africa
tomato_consensus: Though lensed with stunning cinematography and featuring a pair of winning performances from Meryl Streep and Robert Redford, Out of Africa suffers from excessive length and glacial pacing.

title: Out of Sight
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Steven Soderbergh's intelligently crafted adaptation of the Elmore Leonard novel is witty, sexy, suprisingly entertaining, and a star-making turn for George Clooney.

title: Outfoxed: Rupert Murdoch's War on Journalism
tomato_consensus: Neither fair nor balanced itself, Outfoxed offers an often entertaining indictment of the Fox News Channel.

title: Outland
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.

title: Outlander
tomato_consensus: Schizophrenic in subject and lackluster in execution, Outlander might have trouble finding the cult audience for which it was built.

title: Outside Providence
tomato_consensus: Miscasted performers and humor miss the mark.

title: Over Her Dead Body
tomato_consensus: With few laughs and little romantic chemistry, Over Her Dead Body lacks the ingredients of a successful romantic comedy.

title: Over the Hedge
tomato_consensus: Even if it's not an animation classic, Over the Hedge is clever and fun, and the jokes cater to family members of all ages.

title: Owning Mahowny
tomato_consensus: This story of addiction may lack the typical flash and glamour, but Hoffman makes Mahowny compelling.

title: Oz the Great and Powerful
tomato_consensus: It suffers from some tonal inconsistency and a deflated sense of wonder, but Oz the Great and Powerful still packs enough visual dazzle and clever wit to be entertaining in its own right.

title: The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!
tomato_consensus: The Naked Gun is chock full of gags that are goofy, unapologetically crass, and ultimately hilarious.
wiki_title: The Naked Gun: From the Files of Police Squad!

title: The Naked Gun 2½: The Smell of Fear
tomato_consensus: The slapstick antics of this sequel provide a few laughs, but fail to equal those of the original.
wiki_title: The Naked Gun 2½: The Smell of Fear

title: The Naked Island
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins.

title: The Name of the Rose
awards: Won 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 13 wins & 5 nominations.

title: The Namesake
tomato_consensus: An ambitious exploration of the immigrant experience with a talented cast that serves the material well.

title: The Nasty Girl
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The Nativity Story
tomato_consensus: The Nativity Story is a dull retelling of a well-worn tale with the look and feel of a high-school production.

title: The Natural
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though heavy with sentiment, The Natural is an irresistible classic, and a sincere testament to America's national pastime.

title: The Neverending Story II: The Next Chapter
wiki_title: The NeverEnding Story II: The Next Chapter

title: The NeverEnding Story
tomato_consensus: A magical journey about the power of a young boy's imagination to save a dying fantasy land, The NeverEnding Story remains a much-loved kids adventure.

title: The New Adventures of Pippi Longstocking
wiki_title: The New Adventures of Pippi Longstocking

title: The New Guy
tomato_consensus: Incoherent, silly, and unoriginal, The New Guy offers up the same old teen gross-out comedy cliches.

title: The New World
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite arresting visuals and strong lead performances, The New World suffers from an unfocused narrative that will challenge viewers' attention spans over its 2 1/2 hours.

title: The Next Best Thing
tomato_consensus: Story elements clash and acting falls short.

title: The Next Three Days
tomato_consensus: Russell Crowe and Elizabeth Banks give it their all, but their solid performances aren't quite enough to compensate for The Next Three Days' uneven pace and implausible plot.

title: The Night Listener
tomato_consensus: This psychological thriller compels by blurring the line between truth and fiction; unfortunately, the film itself gets muddled in a hazy account of Maupin's original novel.

title: Street Kings
tomato_consensus: Street Kings contains formulaic violence but no shred of intelligence.

title: The Night of the Following Day
wiki_title: The Night of the Following Day

title: The Night of the Hunter
tomato_consensus: Featuring Robert Mitchum's formidable performance as child-hunting preacher, The Night of the Hunter is a disturbing look at good and evil.

title: The Night of the Shooting Stars
wiki_title: The Night of the Shooting Stars
The Night of the White Pants

title: The Nightmare Before Christmas
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Nightmare Before Christmas is a stunningly original and visually delightful work of stop-motion animation.

title: The Nine Lives of Fritz the Cat
wiki_title: The Nine Lives of Fritz the Cat

title: The Ninth Configuration
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.

title: The Notorious Bettie Page
tomato_consensus: This biopic only skims the surface of Bettie Page's life, leaving her as a cipher, and additionally fails to place her iconic status in historical context.

title: The Nun's Story
awards: Nominated for 8 Oscars. Another 14 wins & 12 nominations.

title: The Oh in Ohio
tomato_consensus: A muddled sex-comedy that feels oddly sexless, The Oh in Ohio packs in too many ideas without establishing a clear identity or objective.

title: Oceans
tomato_consensus: Oceans adds another visually stunning chapter to the Disney Nature library.

title: The Odd Couple
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 6 nominations.

title: The Odd Life of Timothy Green
tomato_consensus: It means well, but The Odd Life of Timothy Green is ultimately too cloyingly sentimental -- and thinly scripted -- to satisfy all but the least demanding viewers.

title: The Omen

awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins.

title: The Oranges
tomato_consensus: Despite the efforts of its accomplished cast, The Oranges suffers from a mediocre script that fails to deliver well-rounded characters, dramatic tension, or sufficient laughs.

title: The Order
tomato_consensus: A religious thriller that's more lethargic and silly than thrilling.

title: The Organizer
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 6 nominations.

title: The Original Kings of Comedy
tomato_consensus: If you want lots of laughs and don't mind some profanity, The Original Kings of Comedy can deliver.

title: The Orphanage
tomato_consensus: When it seems like every horror movie nowadays is a remake or a grisly exercise in sadism, The Orphanage is a breath of fresh air for critics and audiences alike, seamlessly blending in a poignant tale of loss with the scares and blood.

title: The Other Boleyn Girl
tomato_consensus: Though it features some extravagant and entertaining moments, The Other Boleyn Girl feels more like a soap opera than historical drama.

title: The Other Guys
tomato_consensus: A clever parody of cop-buddy action-comedies, The Other Guys delivers several impressive action set pieces and lots of big laughs, thanks to the assured comic chemistry between Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.

title: The Other Man
tomato_consensus: Despite the best efforts of a talented cast, The Other Man is talky, witless, and tension-free.

title: The Other Side of Heaven
tomato_consensus: The Other Side of Heaven preaches to the converted; others will likely consider it simplistic, even offensive, propaganda.

title: The Other Side of the Bed
wiki_title: The Other Side of the Bed

title: The Other Side of the Wind
wiki_title: The Other Side of the Wind

title: The Other Sister
tomato_consensus: Made-for-tv drama evokes anything but real emotion.

title: The Others
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 23 wins & 37 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Others is a spooky thriller that reminds us that a movie doesn't need expensive special effects to be creepy.

title: The Out of Towners
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins.

title: The Outlaw Josey Wales
tomato_consensus: Recreating the essence of his iconic Man With No Name in a post-Civil War Western, director Clint Eastwood delivered the first of his great revisionist works of the genre.

title: The Twilight Saga: New Moon
tomato_consensus: The Twilight Saga's second installment may satisfy hardcore fans of the series, but outsiders are likely to be turned off by its slow pace, relentlessly downcast tone, and excessive length.

title: A Perfect Getaway
tomato_consensus: While smarter than the average slasher film, A Perfect Getaway eventually devolves into a standard, predictable, excessively violent thriller.

title: A Perfect Murder
tomato_consensus: A slick little thriller that relies a bit too much on surprise events to generate suspense.

title: A Perfect World
tomato_consensus: Despite some formulaic touches, Clint Eastwood's haunting, ambiguous crime drama is smart and gritty, and features a bravura performance from Kevin Costner as a prison escapee on the run.

wiki_title: A Personal Journey with Martin Scorsese Through American Movies

wiki_title: A Place Between – The Story of an Adoption

title: A Prairie Home Companion
tomato_consensus: The final film by the great Robert Altman, A Prairie Home Companion, the big screen adaptation of Garrison Keillor's radio broadcast, showcases plenty of the director's strengths: it's got a gigantic cast and plenty of quirky acting and dialogue. Much like the radio show, Companion features clever jokes, rousing tunes, and endearing characters. With strong work from Lindsay Lohan, Meryl Streep, Kevin Kline, and Tommy Lee Jones, it's a worthy swan song from one of the cinema's best.

title: A Private Function
awards: Won 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: A Prophet
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 32 wins & 31 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Featuring an impressive star turn by newcomer Tahar Rahim, A Prophet is a French gangster film filled with arresting, immediate details.

title: Winged Migration
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 12 nominations.

title: P.S.
tomato_consensus: Laura Linney is as watchable as ever, but the melancholy P.S. never finds its footing.

title: P2
tomato_consensus: P2 is full of gore, but low on suspense, featuring a cat-and-mouse plot has been done many times before.

title: Qing chun yuan zhu jiao ji
Pacific Rim
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 21 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It may sport more style than substance, but Pacific Rim is a solid modern creature feature bolstered by fantastical imagery and an irresistible sense of fun.

title: Padre padrone
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 7 wins.

title: Paid in Full
tomato_consensus: Though well-acted and non-exploitative, Paid in Full treads a very well-worn story.

title: Pain & Gain
tomato_consensus: It may be his most thought-provoking film to date, but Michael Bay's Pain & Gain ultimately loses its satirical edge in a stylized flurry of violent spectacle.

title: Paint Your Wagon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Paisan
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Pale Rider
tomato_consensus: Nearly a decade after The Outlaw Josey Wales, Clint Eastwood returns as a director to the genre that made his name with this elegant, spiritual Western that riffs on the classic Shane.

title: Pan's Labyrinth
tomato_consensus: Pan's Labyrinth is Alice in Wonderland for grown-ups, with the horrors of both reality and fantasy blended together into an extraordinary, spellbinding fable.

title: Pandorum
tomato_consensus: While it might prove somewhat satisfying for devout sci-fi fans, Pandorum's bloated, derivative plot ultimately leaves it drifting in space.

title: Panic
tomato_consensus: This quirky little film about a gangster in therapy feels fresh and well-crafted.

title: Panic Room
tomato_consensus: Elevated by Fincher's directorial talent and Foster's performance, Panic Room is a well-crafted, above-average thriller.

title: Paparazzi
tomato_consensus: A crude, ludicrous exploitation movie with a questionable moral.

title: Paper Heart
tomato_consensus: Equal parts charming and refreshing, Paper Heart is a quirky mockumentary led by the endearing Charlyne Yi.

title: Paper Moon
tomato_consensus: Expertly balancing tones, Paper Moon is a deft blend of film nostalgia and finely tuned performances -- especially from Tatum O'Neal, who won an Oscar for her debut.

title: Papillon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Paprika
tomato_consensus: Following its own brand of logic, Paprika is an eye-opening mind trip that is difficult to follow but never fails to dazzle.

title: ParaNorman
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 17 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Beautifully animated and solidly scripted, ParaNorman will entertain (and frighten) older children while providing surprisingly thoughtful fare for their parents.

title: Paradise Lost: The Child Murders at Robin Hood Hills
awards: Won 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 7 wins & 5 nominations.
wiki_title: Paradise Lost: The Child Murders at Robin Hood Hills

title: Paradise Lost 2: Revelations
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 1 win.

title: Paradise Now
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This film delves deeply into the minds of suicide bombers, and the result is unsettling.

title: Paranoia
tomato_consensus: Clich?d and unoriginal, Paranoia is a middling techno-thriller with indifferent performances and a shortage of thrills.

title: Paranoid Park
tomato_consensus: Director Gus Van Sant once again superbly captures the ins and outs of teenage life in Paranoid Park, a quietly devastating portrait of a young man living with guilt and anxiety.

title: Paranormal Activity
tomato_consensus: Using its low-budget effects and mockumentary method to great result, Paranormal Activity turns a simple haunted house story into 90 minutes of relentless suspense.

title: Paranormal Activity 2
tomato_consensus: Paranormal Activity 2 doesn't cover any new ground, but its premise is still scary -- and in some respects, it's a better film than the original.

title: Paranormal Activity 3
tomato_consensus: While the jolts and thrills are undeniably subject to the diminishing returns that plague most horror sequels, Paranormal Activity 3 is a surprisingly spine-tingling treat.

title: Paranormal Activity 4
tomato_consensus: While it does manage to wring a few more screams out of the franchise's surprisingly durable premise, Paranormal Activity 4 provides fans of the series with dismayingly diminishing returns.

title: Parental Guidance
tomato_consensus: Parental Guidance is sweet but milquetoast, an inoffensive trifle that's blandly predictable.

title: Parenthood
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Bolstered by a delightful cast, Parenthood is a funny and thoughtfully crafted look at the best and worst moments of family life that resonates broadly.

title: Paris, Texas
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 16 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Paris, je t'aime
tomato_consensus: Paris Je T'aime is uneven, but there are more than enough delightful moments in this omnibus tribute to the City of Lights to tip the scale in its favor.

title: Parker
tomato_consensus: Jason Statham is game as usual, but Parker is a thoroughly generic and convoluted heist movie.

title: Party Monster
tomato_consensus: The lurid display of camp soon turns tedious.

title: The Party at Kitty and Stud's

title: Passion Fish

title: Pat and Mike

title: Patch Adams

title: Pather Panchali
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 8 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Pathfinder
tomato_consensus: A few rousing action sequences can't make up for Pathfinder's non-existent plot and silly dialogue.

title: Paths of Glory
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Patti Smith: Dream of Life
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Elegiac and personal, Patti Smith: Dream of Life paints an enduring and sometimes rough portrait of the titular chanteuse, complete with footage onstage and at home.

title: Patton
tomato_consensus: George C. Scott's sympathetic, unflinching portrayal of the titular general in this sprawling epic is as definitive as any performance in the history of American biopics.

title: Paul
tomato_consensus: It doesn't measure up to Pegg and Frost's best work, but Paul is an amiably entertaining -- albeit uneven -- road trip comedy with an intergalactic twist.

title: Paul Blart: Mall Cop
tomato_consensus: Paul Blart: Mall Cop has some laughs, but its plot is flimsy and lacking in any sustained comic momentum.

tomato_consensus: Pay It Forward has strong performances from Spacey, Hunt, and Osment, but the movie itself is too emotionally manipulative and the ending is bad.

title: Payback
tomato_consensus: Sadistic violence and rote humor saddle a predictable action premise.

title: Paycheck
tomato_consensus: Though Dick's short story has an intriguing premise, Woo reduces it to a lot of meaningless chases, shoot-outs, and explosions.

title: Peaceful Warrior
tomato_consensus: Based on a best-selling memoir, Peaceful Warrior loses something in the transition from page to screen. It hits the viewer over the head with philosophical jargon, and ultimately fails to live up to its source material.

wiki_title: Peach Blossom Weeps Tears of Blood

title: Peeping Tom
tomato_consensus: Peeping Tom is a chilling, methodical look at the psychology of a killer, and a classic work of voyeuristic cinema.

title: Peggy Sue Got Married
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Penelope
tomato_consensus: Though Penelope has a charming cast and an appealing message, it ultimately suffers from faulty narrative and sloppy direction.

title: Pennies from Heaven
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A complicated little musical, Pennies from Heaven is a dazzling, tragic spectacle.

title: People I Know
tomato_consensus: The derivative plot fails to cohere or draw the viewer in.

title: People Like Us
tomato_consensus: Though calculated and melodramatic, People Like Us benefits from a pair of solid leads and its rare screenplay that caters to adult filmgoers.

title: Pepe
awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Percy Jackson & the Olympians: The Lightning Thief

wiki_title: Perfume: The Story of a Murderer (film)

title: Permanent Midnight
tomato_consensus: Aimless storytelling undermines the gripping, unsettling subject of this film.

title: Persepolis

tomato_consensus: Persepolis is an emotionally powerful, dramatically enthralling autobiographical gem, and the film's simple black-and-white images are effective and bold.

title: Persona
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 8 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Arguably Bergman's finest film, Persona explores the human condition with intense curiosity, immense technical skill, and beguiling warmth.

tomato_consensus: Boring and slow, this is a lesser Disney work, though the animation isn't without its charms.

title: Peter Pan
tomato_consensus: Though it doesn't delve deeply into the darkness of J.M. Barrie's tale, Peter Pan is a heartwarming, exuberant film with some great tunes.

title: Peter Pan
tomato_consensus: Solid if far from definitive, this version of Peter Pan is visually impressive, psychologically complex and faithful to its original source.

wiki_title: Phantom of the Mall: Eric's Revenge

title: Pinocchio
tomato_consensus: Ambitious, adventurous, and sometimes frightening, Pinocchio arguably represents the pinnacle of Disney's collected works -- it's beautifully crafted and emotionally resonant.

wiki_title: Pinocchio and the Emperor of the Night

tomato_consensus: It strains to up the gore and self-awareness of it predecessor, and -- despite some game celebrity cameos -- the result is a dispiriting echo of 2010's horror-comedy.

tomato_consensus: The good cast and rollicking soundtrack eventually drown when this comic homage to pirate radio loses its quippy steam.

tomato_consensus: Despite an interesting premise (and a starmaking turn from Vin Diesel), Pitch Black is too derivative and formulaic to recommend to sci-fi or action fans.

title: Pitch Perfect
tomato_consensus: Pitch Perfect's plot is formulaic, but the performances are excellent and the musical numbers are toe-tapping as well.

title: Pixote
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 10 wins.

title: Piñero
tomato_consensus: Though Bratt is great in the title role, the biopic itself is messy and Pi?ero grows tiresome.

title: Plan 9 from Outer Space
tomato_consensus: The epitome of so-bad-it's-good cinema, Plan 9 From Outer Space is an unintentionally hilarious sci-fi "thriller" from anti-genius Ed Wood that is justly celebrated for its staggering ineptitude.

title: Planes
tomato_consensus: Planes has enough bright colors, goofy voices, and slick animation to distract some young viewers for 92 minutes -- and probably sell plenty of toys in the bargain -- but on nearly every other level, it's a Disney disappointment.

title: Planet 51
tomato_consensus: Planet 51 squanders an interesting premise with an overly familiar storyline, stock characters, and humor that alternates between curious and potentially offensive.

title: Planet of the Apes
tomato_consensus: Planet of the Apes raises thought-provoking questions about our culture without letting social commentary get in the way of the drama and action.

title: Planet of the Apes
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 9 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This remake of Planet of the Apes can't compare to the original in some critics' mind, but the striking visuals and B-movie charms may win you over.

title: Platoon
tomato_consensus: Informed by director Oliver Stone's personal experiences in Vietnam, Platoon forgoes easy sermonizing in favor of a harrowing, ground-level view of war, bolstered by no-holds-barred performances from Charlie Sheen and Willem Dafoe.

title: Play It to the Bone
tomato_consensus: Flat characters and uninspired comedy yield forgettable results.

title: Play Misty for Me
tomato_consensus: A coolly calculating psychological thriller that manages to scare the audience even if it is just using textbook thrills.

title: Playing for Keeps
tomato_consensus: Witless, unfocused, and arguably misogynistic, Playing for Keeps is a dispiriting, lowest-common-denominator Hollywood rom-com.

title: Playtime
tomato_consensus: A remarkable achievement, Playtime's packs every scene with sight gags and characters that both celebrates and satirizes the urbanization of modern life.

title: Pleasantville
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 23 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Filled with lighthearted humor, timely social commentary, and dazzling visuals, Pleasantville is an artful blend of subversive satire and well-executed Hollywood formula.

title: Please Give
tomato_consensus: Nicole Holofcener's newest might seem slight in places, but its rendering of complex characters in a conflicted economic landscape is varied, natural, and touching all the same.

title: Pocahontas
tomato_consensus: Pocahontas means well, and has moments of startling beauty, but it's largely a bland, uninspired effort, with uneven plotting and an unfortunate lack of fun.

wiki_title: Pocahontas II: Journey to a New World

tomato_consensus: Critics say that the third Pokemon movie has a better plot than its two predecessors. This is not enough, however, to recommend it to those not already fans of the franchise.

tomato_consensus: This big-budget sword-and-sandal adventure lacks the energy and storytelling heft to amount to more than a guilty pleasure.

tomato_consensus: A charming and delightful walk through the Hundred Acres Woods for young viewers.

title: Pootie Tang
tomato_consensus: Based as it is on a short skit, Pootie Tang overstays its welcome.

title: Popeye
tomato_consensus: Altman's take on the iconic cartoon is messy and wildly uneven, but its robust humor and manic charm are hard to resist.

title: Poseidon
tomato_consensus: This remake of The Poseidon Adventure delivers dazzling special effects. Unfortunately, it doesn't seem that any of the budget was left over to devote to the script.

title: Possession

tomato_consensus: Van Sant's pointless remake neither improves or illuminates Hitchcock's original.
