tomato_consensus: Akira Kurosawa's sprawling, epic take on King Lear should be required viewing for fans of westerns, war movies, or period films in general.

title: Random Hearts
tomato_consensus: Even Harrison Ford could not save the dull plot and the slow pacing of the movie.

title: Rang De Basanti
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 16 wins & 18 nominations.

title: Rango
tomato_consensus: Rango is a smart, giddily creative burst of beautifully animated entertainment, and Johnny Depp gives a colorful vocal performance as a household pet in an unfamiliar world.

title: Ransom
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Tangled
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While far from Disney's greatest film, Tangled is a visually stunning, thoroughly entertaining addition to the studio's classic animated canon.

title: Rashomon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Rat Race
tomato_consensus: Rat Race moves from one sight gag to another, but only a handful of them are genuinely funny.

title: Ratatouille
tomato_consensus: Pixar succeeds again with Ratatouille, a stunningly animated film with fast pacing, memorable characters, and overall good humor.

title: Ray
tomato_consensus: An engrossing and energetic portrait of a great musician's achievements and foibles, Ray is anchored by Jamie Foxx's stunning performance as Ray Charles.

title: Re-Animator
tomato_consensus: Perfectly mixing humor and horror, the only thing more effective than Re-Animator's gory scares are its dry, deadpan jokes.

title: Reach for the Sky
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 nominations.

title: Ready to Rumble
tomato_consensus: Humor at its lowest that isn't funny for kids and is insulting to adults.

title: Real Steel
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Silly premise notwithstanding, this is a well-made Hollywood movie: Thrilling and exciting action with just enough characterization.

title: Real Women Have Curves
tomato_consensus: Even though Real Women is another coming-of-age tale, it's a real charmer.

title: Rear Window
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Hitchcock exerted full potential of suspense in this masterpiece.

title: Rebecca
tomato_consensus: Hitchcock's first American film (and his only Best Picture winner), Rebecca is a masterpiece of haunting atmosphere, Gothic thrills, and gripping suspense.

title: Rebel Without a Cause
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Rebound
tomato_consensus: Rebound ought to entertain its target audience, but there's nothing here for those who've seen The Bad News Bears or its countless derivatives.

title: Recess: School's Out
tomato_consensus: Though basically a TV cartoon stretched out to movie-length, Recess has enough successful jokes and smart writing to make it a worthwhile view.

title: Red
tomato_consensus: This vengeance film leans heavily on attack-and-avenge scenarios but performances by Brian Cox's and Tom Sizemore's take the stink out of any weaker scripting.

title: RED
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It may not be the killer thrill ride you'd expect from an action movie with a cast of this caliber, but Red still thoroughly outshines most of its big-budget counterparts with its wit and style.

title: Red Beard
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 10 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Red Cliff
country: China, Hong Kong, Japan, Taiwan, South Korea
tomato_consensus: Featuring some impressively grand battlefield action, John Woo returns to Asia and returns to form in the process for this lavish and slick historical epic.

title: Red Dawn
tomato_consensus: The rebooted Red Dawn lacks the original's topicality, but at least pays tribute in delivering the same short shrift to character development and general logic.

title: Red Dragon
tomato_consensus: Competently made, but everything is a bit too familiar.

title: Red Eye
tomato_consensus: With solid performances and tight direction from Wes Craven, Red Eye is a brisk, economic thriller.

title: Red Hill
tomato_consensus: Though its attempts to rework genre conventions may fall flat with some, Red Hill is a beautifully shot, tightly paced thriller that marks a strong debut for director Patrick Hughes.

title: Red Planet
tomato_consensus: While the special effects are impressive, the movie suffers from a lack of energy and interesting characters.

title: Red Riding Hood
tomato_consensus: Amanda Seyfried is magnetic in Red Riding Hood's starring role, but she's let down by her uninspired leading men and a painfully cliched script.

title: Red River
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Red Road
tomato_consensus: Red Road director Andrea Arnold skillfully parses out just enough plot details at a time to keep the audience engrossed in this seductive thriller.

title: Red Sonja
tomato_consensus: Dull, poorly directed, and badly miscast, Red Sonja is an uninspired conclusion to Schwarzenegger's barbarian trilogy.

title: Red State
tomato_consensus: Red State is an audacious and brash affair that ultimately fails to provide competent scares or thrills.

title: Red Tails
tomato_consensus: Despite a worthy fact-based story and obvious good intentions, Red Tails suffers from one-dimensional characters, corny dialogue, and heaps of clich?s.

title: Redacted
tomato_consensus: Despite DePalma's obvious commitment to the material and passion for the issues at hand, Redacted suffers from stereotypical characters and a forced faux-doc style.

title: Redbelt
tomato_consensus: Mamet's mixed marital arts morality play weaves between action and intellect but doesn't always hit its target.

title: Redline
tomato_consensus: Redline has plenty of bad acting, laughable dialogue, and luxury cars.

title: Reefer Madness: The Movie Musical
awards: Won 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 3 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Reign Over Me
tomato_consensus: Reign Over Me is a charming, affecting tale of friendship and loss, with solid performances from Adam Sandler as a broken, grief-stricken man and Don Cheadle as his old friend and savior.

title: Reign of Fire
tomato_consensus: An enjoyable B-movie if you don't use your brain.

title: Reindeer Games
tomato_consensus: Despite a decent cast, subpar acting and a contrived plot disappointed reviewers.

title: Religulous
tomato_consensus: Religulous is funny and offensive in equal measure, and aims less to change hearts and minds than to inspire conversation.

title: Remember Me
tomato_consensus: Its leads are likeable, but Remember Me suffers from an overly maudlin script and a borderline offensive final twist.

title: Remember the Titans
tomato_consensus: An inspirational crowd-pleaser with a healthy dose of social commentary, Remember the Titans may be predictable, but it's also well-crafted and features terrific performances.

title: Renaissance
tomato_consensus: Renaissance attempts to blend sci-fi wonder with stark noir animation, but is often more fun to look at than to watch.

title: Rendition
tomato_consensus: The impressive cast cannot rescue Rendition, which explores complex issues in woefully simplified terms.

title: Reno 911!: Miami
tomato_consensus: Reno 911!'s anarchic brand of comedy loses much in translation to the big screen where it feels slapdash and shallow.

title: Rent
tomato_consensus: Fans of the stage musical may forgive Rent its flaws, but weak direction, inescapable staginess and an irritating faux-boho pretension prevent the film from connecting on screen.

title: Repo! The Genetic Opera
tomato_consensus: Bombastic and intentionally gross, Repo! The Genetic Opera has a unique style but lacks the wit and substance to be involving.

title: Repo Man
tomato_consensus: Repo Man is many things: an alien-invasion film, a punk-rock musical, a send-up of consumerism. One thing it isn't is boring.

title: Repo Men
tomato_consensus: Repo Men has an intriguing premise, as well as a likable pair of leads, but they're wasted on a rote screenplay, indifferent direction, and mind-numbing gore.

title: Repulsion
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Roman Polanski's first English film follows a schizophrenic woman's descent into madness, and makes the audience feel as claustrophobic as the character.

title: Requiem for a Dream
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 27 wins & 36 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though the movie may be too intense for some to stomach, the wonderful performances and the bleak imagery are hard to forget.

title: Rescue Dawn
tomato_consensus: Director Werner Herzog has once again made a compelling tale of man versus nature, and Christian Bale completely immerses himself in the role of fighter pilot (and prisoner of war) Dieter Dengler.

title: Reservation Road
tomato_consensus: While the performances are fine, Reservation Road quickly adopts an excessively maudlin tone along with highly improbable plot turns.

title: Resident Evil: Afterlife
tomato_consensus: As dim-witted and lifeless as its undead antagonists, Resident Evil: Afterlife is a wholly unnecessary addition to the franchise.

title: Resident Evil: Apocalypse
tomato_consensus: Resident Evil: Apocalypse has lots of action, but not much in terms of plot or creativity.

title: Resident Evil: Extinction
tomato_consensus: Resident Evil: Extinction is more of the same; its few impressive action sequences unable to compensate for the pedestrian plot.

title: Resident Evil: Retribution
tomato_consensus: Another predictable entry in the Resident Evil franchise that seems to get more cynical and lazy with each film.

title: Resident Evil
tomato_consensus: Like other video game adapations, Resident Evil is loud, violent, formulaic, and cheesy.

title: Respiro
tomato_consensus: A sweet, but slight picture filled with beautiful people and locations.

title: Restrepo
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Forsaking narrative structure for pure visceral power, Restrepo plunges viewers into the experiences of soldiers on the front lines of the Afghan War.

title: Resurrecting the Champ
tomato_consensus: While sluggish in spots, Resurrecting the Champ is a sports/newsroom drama elevated by high-caliber performances by Samuel Jackson, Josh Hartnet, and Alan Alda.

title: Resurrection of the Little Match Girl
wiki_title: Resurrection of the Little Match Girl

title: Return of the Living Dead III
Return of the Living Dead 2
wiki_title: Return of the Living Dead Part II

title: Return to House on Haunted Hill
wiki_title: Return to House on Haunted Hill

title: Return to Me
tomato_consensus: David Duchovny and Minnie Driver provide heart-warming romance and comedy in this solid debut by Director Bonnie Hunt.

title: Return to Never Land
tomato_consensus: With its forgettable songs and lackluster story, this new Pan will surely entertain kids, but will feel more like a retread to adults.

title: Return to the Batcave: The Misadventures of Adam and Burt
wiki_title: Return to the Batcave: The Misadventures of Adam and Burt

title: Reuben, Reuben
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 4 nominations.

title: Revanche
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With Revanche, G?tz Spielmann has crafted a debut as surprising as it is suspenseful.

title: Revenge of the Nerds II: Nerds in Paradise
tomato_consensus: It reunites most of the original cast and rounds them up for a trip to Fort Lauderdale for spring break, but Revenge of the Nerds II: Nerds in Paradise forgets to pack enough jokes or compelling characters to make it through its 89-minute running time.
wiki_title: Revenge of the Nerds II: Nerds in Paradise

title: Revolutionary Road
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Brilliantly acted and emotionally powerful, Revolutionary Road is a handsome adaptation of Richard Yates' celebrated novel.

title: Revolver
tomato_consensus: In attempting to meld his successful previous formulas with philosophical musings, Guy Ritchie has produced an incoherent misfire.

title: Richard III
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Richard III
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This re-imagining of Shakespeare's Crookback King relocates the story in 1930 and features an indelible star turn for Ian McKellen as the monstrous and magnetic King Richard.

title: Ri¢hie Ri¢h
tomato_consensus: With Macaulay Culkin barely registering any emotion, Richie Rich feels disjointed and free of a sense of fun and wonderment.

title: Ride the High Country
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Ride with the Devil
tomato_consensus: A well-acted, eccentric Civil War film, Ang Lee's Ride With the Devil is often more visually striking than it is emotionally engaging.

title: Ridicule
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 20 wins & 13 nominations.

title: Riding Alone for Thousands of Miles
tomato_consensus: Doesn't reach the heights of Zhang Yimou's best, but this is still a heartwarming tale of love and forgiveness from the acclaimed Chinese director.
wiki_title: Riding Alone for Thousands of Miles

title: Riding Giants
tomato_consensus: A great addition to the existing surfing documentaries.

title: Riding in Cars with Boys
tomato_consensus: Riding in Cars With Boys suffers from mixing grit and pathos with cuteness and comedy. Ironically, many critics found Zahn's character more compelling and three-dimensional than Barrymore's.

title: Right at Your Door
tomato_consensus: Though Right at Your Door dips into melodrama at the end, it's an otherwise tense, effective, and eerily plausible doomsday scenario.

title: Righteous Kill
tomato_consensus: Al Pacino and Robert De Niro do their best to elevate this dowdy genre exercise, but even these two greats can't resuscitate the film's hackneyed script.

title: Ring
tomato_consensus: Ringu combines supernatural elements with anxieties about modern technology in a truly frightening and unnerving way.

title: Ringmaster
tomato_consensus: A crude, idiotic mess of a film.

title: Rio
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 22 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This straightforward movie reaches great heights thanks to its colorful visual palette, catchy music, and funny vocal performances.

title: Rio Lobo
tomato_consensus: Howard Hawks and John Wayne reunite to riff on their own Rio Bravo, and while the results are less memorable the movie does offer a curiously cynical perspective.

title: Rise of the Guardians
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 21 nominations.

title: Rise of the Planet of the Apes
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Led by Rupert Wyatt's stylish direction, some impressive special effects, and a mesmerizing performance by Andy Serkis, Rise of the Planet of the Apes breathes unlikely new life into a long-running franchise.
wiki_title: Rise of the Planet of the Apes

title: Risky Business
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Featuring one of Tom Cruise's best early performances, Risky Business is a sharp, funny examination of teen angst that doesn't stop short of exploring dark themes.

title: Rize
tomato_consensus: The dances in Rize are electric even if the documentary doesn't go that deeply into the performers' lives.

title: Road to Perdition
tomato_consensus: Somber, stately, and beautifully mounted, Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition is a well-crafted mob movie that explores the ties between fathers and sons.

title: Rob Roy
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Rob Roy is an old-fashioned swashbuckler that benefits greatly from fine performances by Liam Neeson, Jessica Lange, and Tim Roth.

title: Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 17 nominations.

title: Robin Hood
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: One of the weaker Disney adaptations, Robin Hood is cute and colorful but lacks the majesty and excitement of the studio's earlier efforts.

title: Robin Hood
tomato_consensus: Ridley Scott's revisionist take on this oft-told tale offers some fine acting and a few gripping action sequences, but it's missing the thrill of adventure that made Robin Hood a legend in the first place.

title: RoboCop
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 11 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While over-the-top and gory, Robocop is also a surprisingly smart sci-fi flick that uses ultraviolence to disguise its satire of American culture.

title: RoboCop
tomato_consensus: While it's far better than it could have been, Jos? Padilha's RoboCop remake fails to offer a significant improvement over the original.

title: Robot & Frank
tomato_consensus: Led by a brilliant performance from star Frank Langella, Robot & Frank works as both a quirky indie drama and as a smart, thoughtful meditation on aging.

title: Robot Stories
tomato_consensus: Although its 4 stories vary in quality, Robot Stories is still worth a look for Twilight Zone fans.

title: Robots
tomato_consensus: Robots delights on a visual level, but the story feels like it came off an assembly line.

title: Rocco and His Brothers
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 9 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Rock n' Roll Cops 2: The Adventure Begins
wiki_title: Rock n' Roll Cops 2: The Adventure Begins

title: Rock of Ages
tomato_consensus: Its exuberant silliness is almost enough to make up for its utter inconsequentiality, but Rock of Ages is ultimately too bland and overlong to justify its trip to the big screen.

title: Rocket Science
tomato_consensus: Though Rocket Science appears to be a typically quirky indie, the well-rounded performances and director Jeffrey Blitz's clear affection for his characters gives the film its proper human spark.

title: RocknRolla
tomato_consensus: Mixed reviews for Guy Ritchie's return to his London-based cockney wideboy gangster movie roots, but most agree, it's a step in the right direction following two major turkeys.

title: Rocky
tomato_consensus: This story of a down-on-his-luck boxer is thoroughly predictable, but Sylvester Stallone's script and stunning performance in the title role brush aside complaints.

title: Rocky Balboa
tomato_consensus: Implausible but entertaining and poignant, Rocky Balboa finds the champ in fighting form for the first time in years.

title: Rocky III
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 7 nominations.

title: Roger Dodger
tomato_consensus: The movie could have benefited from a more experienced director, but a great cast and script overcome any first time jitters the director may have had.

title: Role Models
tomato_consensus: Role Models is a frequently crude, always funny comedy with the cast providing solid work throughout.

title: Rollerball
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Rollerball
tomato_consensus: Removing the social critique of the original, this updated version of Rollerball is violent, confusing, and choppy. Klein makes for a bland hero.

title: Roma
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Roman Holiday
tomato_consensus: With Audrey Hepburn luminous in her American debut, Roman Holiday is as funny as it is beautiful, and sets the standard for the modern romantic comedy.

title: Romance & Cigarettes
tomato_consensus: This movie musical aims for fun and modern, but Romance and Cigarettes is too scattered and uneven to achieve either.

title: Xixiang ji
wiki_title: Romance of the Western Chamber (1927 film)

title: Romancing the Stone
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Romancing the Stone reaches back to the classic Saturday morning serials of old with an action-filled adventure enlivened by the sparkling chemistry between its well-matched leads.

title: Romeo + Juliet
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 13 wins & 20 nominations.

title: Romeo Must Die
tomato_consensus: In his second Hollywood movie, Jet Li impresses. Unfortunately, when he's not on screen, the movie slows to a crawl. Though there's some spark between Jet and Aaliyah, there isn't any threat of a fire. And as impressive as the action sequences are, some critics feel they are over-edited.

title: Romeo and Juliet
tomato_consensus: The solid leads and arresting visuals make a case for Zeffirelli's Romeo and Juliet as the definitive cinematic adaptation of the play.

title: Romeo & Juliet
tomato_consensus: Shakespeare's classic romance gets a so-so adaptation that's short on passion and energy.

title: Romy and Michele's High School Reunion
wiki_title: Romy and Michele's High School Reunion

title: Ronin
tomato_consensus: This is comparable to French Connection with great action, dynamic road chase scenes, and solid performances.

title: Rose Kennedy: A Life to Remember
wiki_title: Rose Kennedy: A Life to Remember

title: Roswell
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 nominations.

title: Rounders
tomato_consensus: Richly atmospheric and colorful performances contributed to the movie's entertainment value.

title: Roving Mars
tomato_consensus: Roving Mars is a decent thrill ride even when it starts feeling like a commercial plug for NASA's failing space program.

title: Roxanne
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Though its sweetness borders on sappiness, Roxanne is an unabashedly romantic comedy that remains one of Steve Martin's funniest.

title: Royal Wedding
tomato_consensus: Vintage MGM musical stuff, characterized by Stanley Donen's fleet direction and some amazing dance performances from star Fred Astaire.

title: Rubber
tomato_consensus: A clever premise gets plenty of comic blood and violence, but its hampered by some questionable storytelling techniques from director Quentin Dupieux.

title: Ruby Sparks
tomato_consensus: Cleverly written and wonderfully acted, Ruby Sparks overcomes its occasional lags in pace with an abundance of charm and wit.

title: Rudo y Cursi
tomato_consensus: Despite its fair share of sports movie cliches, Rudo y Cursi marks an auspicious directing debut for Carlos Cuar?n, and features strong performances from Garc?a Bernal and Luna.

title: Rudy
tomato_consensus: Though undeniably sentimental and predictable, Rudy succeeds with an uplifting spirit and determination.

title: Rugrats Go Wild
tomato_consensus: The Rugrats franchise has gone from fresh to formulaic.

title: Rugrats in Paris: The Movie
tomato_consensus: When the Rugrats go to Paris, the result is Nickelodeon-style fun. The plot is effectively character-driven, and features catchy songs and great celebrity voice-acting.

title: Rules of Engagement
tomato_consensus: The script is unconvincing and the courtroom action is unegaging.

title: Rumble Fish
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Rumble in the Bronx
tomato_consensus: An entertaining Jackie Chan stunt-fest in which the impressive action sequences overcome the low production value and by-the-numbers plot.

title: Rumor Has It...
tomato_consensus: This riff on The Graduate has a solid cast, but is too lightweight to fully register.

title: Run, Fatboy, Run
tomato_consensus: Run, Fat Boy, Run features sporadic laughs, but is ultimately too formulaic and predictable.

title: Run Lola Run
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 28 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: More fun than a barrel of Jean-Paul Sartre, pic's energy riffs on an engaging love story and really human performances while offering a series of what-ifs and a blood-stirring soundtrack.

title: Runaway Bride
tomato_consensus: Cliche story with lack of chemistry between Richard Gere and Julia Roberts.

title: Runaway Jury
tomato_consensus: An implausible but entertaining legal thriller.

title: Runaway Train
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Runner Runner
tomato_consensus: It has an impressive cast and an intriguing premise, but Runner Runner wastes them on a bland, haphazardly assembled thriller with very little payoff.

title: Running Scared
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins.

title: Running Scared
tomato_consensus: This film runs with frenetic energy punctuated by gratuitous violence but sorely lacks in plot, character development and stylistic flair.

title: Running on Empty
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Running with Scissors
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Despite a few great performances, the film lacks the sincerity and emotional edge of Burroughs' well-loved memoir.

title: Rush
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Rush
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 33 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A sleek, slick, well-oiled machine, Rush is a finely crafted sports drama with exhilarating race sequences and strong performances from Chris Hemsworth and Daniel Br?hl.

title: Rush Hour
tomato_consensus: A kick-ass addition to the cop-buddy film genre.

title: Rush Hour 2
tomato_consensus: Rush Hour 2 doesn't feel as fresh or funny as the first, and the stunts lack some of the intricacy normally seen in Chan's films.

title: Rush Hour 3
tomato_consensus: Rush Hour 3 is a tired rehash of the earlier films, and a change of scenery can't hide a lack of new ideas.

title: Rushmore
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 14 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This cult favorite is a quirky coming of age story, with fine, off-kilter performances from Jason Schwartzman and Bill Murray.

title: Russian Ark
country: Russia, Germany, Japan, Canada, Finland, Denmark
tomato_consensus: As successful as it is ambitious, Russian Ark condenses three centuries of Russian history into a single, uninterrupted, 87-minute take.

title: Rust and Bone
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 22 wins & 36 nominations.

title: Ruthless People
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It's sometimes crude and tasteless, but Ruthless People wrings acid-soaked laughs out of its dark premise and gleefully misanthropic characters.

title: Star Wars: Episode VI - Return of the Jedi
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though failing to reach the cinematic heights of its predecessors, Return of the Jedi remains an entertaining sci-fi adventure and a fitting end to the classic trilogy.
wiki_title: Star Wars Episode VI: Return of the Jedi

title: The Queen
tomato_consensus: Full of wit, humor, and pathos, Stephen Frears' moving portrait of the British royals during the period after Princess Diana's death features not one but two remarkable performances, that of Helen Mirren as Queen Elizabeth II and Michael Sheen as the newly-ordained Prime Minister Tony Blair. They embody their characters and lay bare the motivations behind these prominent people, giving viewers a glimpse into the inner workings of the British monarchy.

title: The Queen of Versailles
tomato_consensus: The Queen of Versailles is a timely, engaging, and richly drawn portrait of the American Dream improbably composed of equal parts compassion and schadenfreude.

title: The Quick and the Dead
wiki_title: The Quick and the Dead (1995 film)

title: The Quiet
tomato_consensus: This psychological thriller's talented cast is undercut by leaden pacing and a problematic plot.

title: The Quiet American
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Thoughtful and wonderfully acted, The Quiet American manages to capture the spirit of Green's novel.

title: The Quiet Man
tomato_consensus: Director John Ford and star John Wayne depart the Western for the Irish countryside, and the result is a beautifully photographed, often comedic romance.

title: The Quiller Memorandum
awards: Nominated for 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 nomination.

title: The Raid: Redemption
tomato_consensus: No frills and all thrills, The Raid: Redemption is an inventive action film expertly paced and edited for maximum entertainment.

title: The Railway Children
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 nomination.

title: The Rainmaker
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.

title: The Rainmaker
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Invigorated by its talented cast and Francis Ford Coppola's strong direction, The Rainmaker is a satisfying legal drama -- and arguably the best of Hollywood's many John Grisham adaptations.

title: The Rat Pack
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 17 nominations.

title: The Raven
tomato_consensus: Thinly scripted, unevenly acted, and overall preposterous, The Raven disgraces the legacy of Edgar Allen Poe with a rote murder mystery that's more silly than scary.

title: The Reader
tomato_consensus: Despite Kate Winslet's superb portrayal, The Reader suggests an emotionally distant, Oscar-baiting historical drama.

title: The Real Cancun
tomato_consensus: The footage is predictable and rather tame, and most of the people are uninteresting.

title: The Reaping
tomato_consensus: It may feature such accomplished actors as Hilary Swank and Stephen Rea, but The Reaping also boasts the apropos tagline "What hath God wrought?" It's schlocky, spiritually shallow, and scare-free.

title: Record of a Tenement Gentleman
wiki_title: The Record of a Tenement Gentleman

title: The Recruit
tomato_consensus: This polished thriller is engaging until it takes one twist too many into the predictable.

title: The Red Badge of Courage
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win.

title: The Red Baron
tomato_consensus: It doesn't lack ambition, and it boasts undeniably thrilling source material, but The Red Baron is brought down by its overly sentimental script and a number of historical inaccuracies.

title: The Ref
tomato_consensus: Undeniably uneven and too dark for some, The Ref nonetheless boasts strong turns from Denis Leary, Judy Davis, and Kevin Spacey, as well as a sharply funny script.

title: The Relic
country: UK, Germany, Japan, New Zealand, USA

title: The Reluctant Fundamentalist
tomato_consensus: The Reluctant Fundamentalist is technically proficient, with solid acting and cinematography, but its message is so ambitious and heavy-handed that some of its power is robbed.

title: The Remains of the Day
awards: Nominated for 8 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 19 nominations.

title: The Replacements
tomato_consensus: The cliched characters and obvious outcome make all the fun and excitement amount to nothing.

tomato_consensus: Though its story is second-rate, The Rescuers Down Under redeems itself with some remarkable production values -- particularly its flight scenes.

title: The Return
tomato_consensus: Unoriginality may be an acceptable risk in the Horror genre, but boredom is never okay.

tomato_consensus: Ring Two serves up horror cliches, and not even Hideo Nakata, the director of the movies from which this one is based, can save the movie from a dull screenplay full of absurdities.

title: The Ringer
tomato_consensus: Despite a few laughs and good intentions, The Ringer is too predictable to really score the points it aims for.

title: The Rite
tomato_consensus: Anthony Hopkins is as excellent as ever, but he's no match for The Rite's dawdling pace and lack of chills -- or Colin O'Donoghue's tentative performance in the leading role.

tomato_consensus: Predictable story and thin characters made the movie flat.

title: A Serious Man

tomato_consensus: Safe House stars Washington and Reynolds are let down by a thin script and choppily edited action sequences.

tomato_consensus: Safety Not Guaranteed's ostensibly modest ambitions are outmatched by the movie's strong performances, beguiling charm, and heartfelt story.

tomato_consensus: While it draws heavily on war movie conventions, Saints and Soldiers has strong performances and a compelling central plot.

title: Salt

tomato_consensus: Angelina Jolie gives it her all in the title role, and her seasoned performance is almost enough to save Salt from its predictable and ludicrous plot.

tomato_consensus: One of Disney's lesser-known animated films, Saludos Amigos may be slight stuff, but it's still a spirited, energetic travelogue.

tomato_consensus: Those unfamiliar with Alejandro Jodorowsky's style may find it overwhelming, but Santa Sangre is a provocative psychedelic journey featuring the director's signature touches of violence, vulgarity, and an oddly personal moral center.

title: Sapphire
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Fellini Satyricon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Savage Grace
tomato_consensus: Though visually compelling, the lamentable characters in Savage Grace make for difficult viewing.

title: Savages
tomato_consensus: It's undeniably messy, but Savages finds Oliver Stone returning to dark, fearlessly lurid form.

title: Save the Green Planet!
tomato_consensus: A funny and wildly inventive hybrid of various genres, Save the Green Planet! is definitely a unique viewing experience.

title: Saved!
tomato_consensus: A satirical teen comedy that, unfortunately, pulls its punches.

title: Saving Face
tomato_consensus: A charming tale of a love affair that overcomes cultural taboos.

title: Saving Grace
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The plot and basis for jokes are slight, but Saving Grace is indeed saved by some charming performances, most notably Brenda Blethyn's.

title: Saving Mr. Banks
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 44 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Aggressively likable and sentimental to a fault, Saving Mr. Banks pays tribute to the Disney legacy with excellent performances and sweet, high-spirited charm.

title: Saving Private Ryan
tomato_consensus: Anchored by another winning performance from Hanks, Spielberg's unflinchingly realistic war film virtually redefines the genre.

title: Saving Silverman
tomato_consensus: Dragged down by a plot lacking any sense of logic and obnoxious, unsympathetic characters, this comedy is more crude and mean-spirited than funny.

title: Saw
tomato_consensus: A twisted and gory horror film that's not for the squeamish.

title: Saw 3D: The Final Chapter
tomato_consensus: Sloppily filmed, poorly acted, and illogically plotted, Saw 3D leaves viewers trapped in the most lackluster installment of the series.

title: Saw II
tomato_consensus: Saw II is likely to please the gore-happy fans of the original, though it may be too gruesome for those not familiar with first film's premise.

title: Saw III
tomato_consensus: Saw III does little beyond repeating its predecessor's tropes on a gorier level.

title: Saw IV
tomato_consensus: Saw IV is more disturbing than compelling, with material already seen in the prior installments.

title: Saw V
tomato_consensus: If its plot were as interesting as its torture devices, or its violence less painful than its performances, perhaps Saw V might not feel like it was running on fumes.

title: Saw VI
tomato_consensus: It won't earn the franchise many new fans, but Saw VI is a surprising step up for what has become an intricately grisly annual tradition.

title: Say Anything...
tomato_consensus: One of the definitive Generation X movies, Say Anything is equally funny and heartfelt -- and it established John Cusack as an icon for left-of-center types everywhere.

title: Say It Isn't So
tomato_consensus: Those that haven't tired from Farrelly brothers' brand of comedy may still find some laughs here. Otherwise, the slow pacing and unimaginative shock gags will start to wear on the viewer.

title: Scandal
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Scarface
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 nominations.

title: Scary Movie
tomato_consensus: Critics say Scary Movie overloads on crudity and grossness to get its laughs.

title: Scary Movie 2
tomato_consensus: Instead of being funny, this gross-out sequel plays like a sloppy, rushed-out product.

title: Scary Movie 4
tomato_consensus: Sure to inspire a few chuckles, but not enough to compensate for the recycled material from its predecessors.

title: Scary Movie 5
tomato_consensus: Juvenile even by Scary Movie standards, this fifth installment offers stale pop culture gags that generate few laughs.

title: Scenes from a Marriage
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 13 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Scent of a Woman
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 3 nominations.

tomato_consensus: It might soar on Al Pacino's performance more than the drama itself, but what a performance it is -- big, bold, occasionally over-the-top, and finally giving the Academy pause to award the star his first Oscar.

title: Schindler's List
tomato_consensus: Schindler's List blends the abject horror of the Holocaust with Steven Spielberg's signature tender humanism to create the director's dramatic masterpiece.

title: School for Scoundrels
tomato_consensus: School for Scoundrels squanders its talented cast with a formulaic, unfocused attempt at a romantic comedy that's neither romantic nor funny.

title: School of Rock

title: Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed
tomato_consensus: Only the very young will get the most out of this silly trifle.

title: Scoop
tomato_consensus: Rehashing old plot lines and characters, Scoop is a tiresome dipper and another disappointing addition to Woody Allen's repertoire.

title: Scotland, Pa.
tomato_consensus: Though it's not as good as it could have been, Scotland PA shows cleverness at utilizing its premise.

title: Scott Pilgrim vs. the World
tomato_consensus: Its script may not be as dazzling as its eye-popping visuals, but Scott Pilgrim vs. the World is fast, funny, and inventive.

title: Scott of the Antarctic
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.

title: Scream
tomato_consensus: A great mixed of bone chilling suspense and witty dialogues.

title: Scream 2
tomato_consensus: It is scarier and funnier than the original.

title: Scream 2
tomato_consensus: It is scarier and funnier than the original.

title: Scream 4
tomato_consensus: The franchise is showing its age, but Scream 4 is undeniably an improvement over its predecessor, with just enough meta humor and clever kills.

tomato_consensus: Despite having real comics in the cast, this tedious and painfully unfunny movie desperately needs a screenplay.

tomato_consensus: A fascinating portrait of a forgotten musical pioneer, Searching for Sugar Man is by turns informative and mysterious.

tomato_consensus: Slow, cheap-looking, and dull, Season of the Witch fails even as unintentional comedy.

title: Seconds

awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.

tomato_consensus: Depp is quirkily entertaining, but the movie runs out of steam by the end.
