title: Shame
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 27 wins & 53 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Boasting stellar performances by Michael Fassbender and Carey Mulligan, Shame is a powerful plunge into the mania of addiction affliction.

title: Shanghai Knights
tomato_consensus: A silly, anachronistic mess, but the pairing of Chan and Wilson makes the movie fun.

title: Shanghai Noon
tomato_consensus: Although the plot is really nothing to brag about, Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson work well together. The cinematography looks great, and Jackie delivers a hilarious performance. This is an old-fashioned crowd-pleaser.

title: Shanghai Triad
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Shaolin Soccer
tomato_consensus: The plot is utterly ridiculous, and the soccer in the movie is unlike any ever played anywhere on Earth, but watching Shaolin Soccer, you will probably find it impossible to care.

title: Shark Night 3D
tomato_consensus: A joyless excursion into the water that doesn't even produce good gore or nudity thanks to the neutered PG-13 rating.

title: Shark Tale
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Derivative and full of pop culture in-jokes.

title: Shattered Glass
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 12 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A compelling look at Stephen Glass' fall from grace.

title: Shaun of the Dead
tomato_consensus: Shaun of the Dead cleverly balances scares and witty satire, making for a bloody good zombie movie with loads of wit.

title: She's All That
tomato_consensus: Despite its charming young leads, She's All That can't overcome its predictable, inconsistently funny script.

title: She's Out of My League
tomato_consensus: She's Out of My League has moments of humor and insight, but it's bogged down by excessive vulgarity and cartoonishness.

title: She Hate Me
tomato_consensus: She Hate Me can't decide if it wants to be a commentary on corporate greed or a sex farce.

title: Shenandoah
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows
tomato_consensus: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows is a good yarn thanks to its well-matched leading men but overall stumbles duplicating the well-oiled thrills of the original.
wiki_title: Sherlock Holmes: A Game of Shadows

title: Sherlock Holmes
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 9 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Guy Ritchie's directorial style might not be quite the best fit for an update on the legendary detective, but Sherlock Holmes benefits from the elementary appeal of a strong performance by Robert Downey, Jr.

title: Sherlock Holmes and the Secret Weapon
wiki_title: Sherlock Holmes and the Secret Weapon

title: Sherlock Holmes and the Voice of Terror
wiki_title: Sherlock Holmes and the Voice of Terror

title: Sherrybaby
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Shine
tomato_consensus: Featuring a strong performance from Geoffrey Rush, Shine succeeds in telling a compelling, inspirational story without resorting to cheap sentimentality.

title: Shine a Light
tomato_consensus: It may offer little new for fans, but Martin Scorsese's document of the Rolling Stones' electrifying live show should provide satisfaction to audiences.

title: Fifty-Fifty
tomato_consensus: A stark and moving coming-of-age tale and crime thriller, Schizo gives viewers a peek into the lives of Kazakhstan's poor.

title: Shock Corridor
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins.

title: Shocking Asia II: The Last Taboos
wiki_title: Shocking Asia II: The Last Taboos

title: Shoot 'Em Up
tomato_consensus: As preposterous and over-the-top as Shoot 'Em Up may be, its humor and non-stop action make for a very enjoyable film.

title: Shoot the Moon
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Shooter
tomato_consensus: With an implausible story and numerous plot holes, Shooter fails to distinguish itself from other mindless action-thrillers.

title: Shopgirl
tomato_consensus: Shopgirl is precariously slight, but it has some intriguing moments, and Danes is luminous.

title: Short Circuit
tomato_consensus: Amiable and good-natured but also shallow and predictable, Short Circuit is hardly as deep or emotionally resonant as E.T. -- though Johnny Five makes for a charming robot protagonist.

title: Short Cuts
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 23 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Robert Altman's ensemble drama deftly integrates its disparate characters and episodes into a funny, poignant, emotionally satisfying whole.

title: Shortbus
tomato_consensus: The sex may be explicit, but Mitchell integrates it into the characters' lives and serves the whole story up with a generous dose of sweetness and wit.

title: Shorts
tomato_consensus: Shorts has imagination and energy, but most viewers beyond elementary school will likely tire of the kiddie humor and sensory overload.

title: Show Boat
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Showtime
tomato_consensus: Showtime starts out as a promising satire of the buddy cop genre. Unfortunately, it ends up becoming the type of movies it is satirizing.

title: Shrek
tomato_consensus: While simultaneously embracing and subverting fairy tales, the irreverent Shrek also manages to tweak Disney's nose, provide a moral message to children, and offer viewers a funny, fast-paced ride.

title: Shrek 2
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 16 wins & 35 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It may not be as fresh as the original, but topical humor and colorful secondary characters make Shrek 2 a winner in its own right.

title: Shrek Forever After
tomato_consensus: While not without its moments, Shrek Forever After too often feels like a rote rehashing of the franchise's earlier entries.

title: Shrek the Third
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 4 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Shrek the Third has pop culture potshots galore, but at the expense of the heart, charm, and wit that made the first two Shreks classics.

title: Shriek If You Know What I Did Last Friday the Thirteenth
wiki_title: Shriek If You Know What I Did Last Friday the Thirteenth

title: Shrink
tomato_consensus: Kevin Spacey's performance is almost sharp enough to save this Hollywood dramedy from itself, but in the end, he's dragged down by a cliched script and indifferent direction.

title: Shut Up and Play the Hits
wiki_title: Shut Up and Play the Hits

title: Shutter
tomato_consensus: Being a remake of a Thai horror film instead of Japanese doesn't prevent Shutter from being another lame Asian horror remake.

title: Shutter Island
tomato_consensus: It may not rank with Scorsese's best work, but Shutter Island's gleefully unapologetic genre thrills represent the director at his most unrestrained.

title: Shuttle
tomato_consensus: While this debut by Edward Anderson is economical and occasionally effective, Shuttle offers little catharsis after its tense ride.

title: Sick: The Life & Death of Bob Flanagan, Supermasochist
wiki_title: Sick: The Life and Death of Bob Flanagan, Supermasochist

title: Sicko
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Driven by Michael Moore's sincere humanism, Sicko is a devastating, convincing, and very entertaining documentary about the state of America's health care.

title: Sid and Nancy
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 5 wins.
tomato_consensus: Visceral, energetic, and often very sad, Sid & Nancy is also a surprisingly touching love story, and Gary Oldman is outstanding as the late punk rock icon Sid Vicious.

title: Side Effects
tomato_consensus: A smart, clever thriller with plenty of disquieting twists, Side Effects is yet another assured effort from director Steven Soderbergh.

title: Sidewalks of New York
tomato_consensus: Though well-acted, Sidewalks of New York generally comes off as a second-rate Woody Allen film. The characters seem self-absorbed, the problems trite.

title: The Birds, the Bees and the Italians
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 7 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Signs
tomato_consensus: With Signs, Shyamalan proves once again an expert at building suspense and giving audiences the chills.

title: Silent Hill: Revelation 3D
tomato_consensus: Mediocre effort even by the standards of video game adaptations, Silent Hill: Revelation 3D features weak characters and an incomprehensible plot with a shortage of scares.

title: Silent Hill
tomato_consensus: Silent Hill is visually impressive, but as with many video game adaptations, it's plagued by inane dialogue, a muddled plot, and an overlong runtime.

title: Silent House
tomato_consensus: Silent House is more technically proficient and ambitious than most fright-fests, but it also suffers from a disappointing payoff.

title: Silent Movie
awards: Nominated for 4 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Silent Night, Deadly Night III: Better Watch Out!
wiki_title: Silent Night, Deadly Night 3: Better Watch Out!

title: Silent Night, Deadly Night 5: The Toy Maker
wiki_title: Silent Night, Deadly Night 5: The Toy Maker

title: Silk
tomato_consensus: Silk contains a simple love triangle story but director Francois Gerard goes to painstaking lengths to turn it into a protracted and wearisome art film.

title: Silk Stockings
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Silkwood
awards: Nominated for 5 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 8 nominations.

title: Silver Linings Playbook
tomato_consensus: Silver Linings Playbook walks a tricky thematic tightrope, but David O. Russell's sensitive direction and some sharp work from a talented cast gives it true balance.

title: Silver Streak
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Silverado
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Boasting rich detail and well-told story, Silverado is a rare example of an '80s Hollywood Western done right.

title: Simon Birch
tomato_consensus: Overly mushy; tries too hard to pull at the heart-strings.

title: Simpatico
tomato_consensus: Critics say Simpatico's lengthy plot is too unfocused; the movie becomes confusing and tedious to watch.

title: Sin City: A Dame to Kill For
wiki_title: Sin City: A Dame to Kill For

title: Sin City
tomato_consensus: Visually groundbreaking and terrifically violent, Sin City brings the dark world of Frank Miller's graphic novel to vivid life.

title: Sin Nombre
tomato_consensus: Part harrowing immigration tale, part gangster story, this debut by writer/director Cary Fukunaga is sensitive, insightful and deeply authentic.

title: Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas
wiki_title: Sinbad: Legend of the Seven Seas

title: Sinbad and the Eye of the Tiger
wiki_title: Sinbad and the Eye of the Tiger

title: Since Otar Left
tomato_consensus: A drama that's both funny and moving.

title: Singin' in the Rain
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Clever, incisive, and funny, Singin' in the Rain is a masterpiece of the classical Hollywood musical.

title: Sinister
tomato_consensus: Its plot hinges on typically implausible horror-movie behavior and recycles countless genre cliches, but Sinister delivers a surprising number of fresh, diabolical twists.

title: Sister Act
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 7 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Sister Act 2: Back in the Habit
wiki_title: Sister Act 2: Back in the Habit

title: Sisters, or The Balance of Happiness
wiki_title: Sisters, or the Balance of Happiness

title: Skin
tomato_consensus: Sophie Okonedo, Sam Neill, and Alice Krige do wonderful work in Skin, delivering performances whose strength is underlined by the incredible real-life events upon which the movie is based.

title: Skinwalkers
tomato_consensus: Skinwalkers is an atrociously-acted project whose unoriginal and ineptly-staged action sequences remind viewers of far better werewolf and action movies.

title: Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow
tomato_consensus: Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow is slim on plot and characterization, but the visuals more than make up for it.
wiki_title: Sky Captain and the World of Tomorrow

title: Sky High
tomato_consensus: This highly derivative superhero coming-of-age flick is moderately entertaining, family-friendly fluff.

title: Skyline
tomato_consensus: A middling sci-fi entry, Skyline offers proof that solid special effects alone cannot overcome a flat storyline filled with uninspired dialogue.

title: Slackers
tomato_consensus: Another teen comedy with little on its mind but moving to the next gross-out gag, Slackers strains for laughs and features grating characters.

title: Slap Shot
tomato_consensus: Raunchy, violent, and very funny, Slap Shot is ultimately set apart by a wonderful comic performance by Paul Newman.

title: Slaughterhouse-Five
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Sleeper
tomato_consensus: In Sleeper, Woody Allen's madcap futurist comedy, practically each joke and one-liner hits it target.

title: Sleepers
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Sleeping Beauty
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This Disney dreamscape contains moments of grandeur, with its lush colors, magical air, one of the most menacing villains in the Disney canon.

title: Sleeping Dogs Lie
tomato_consensus: Though Sleeping Dogs Lie treats its subject and characters humanely, it's unable to overcome the low-budget production and Bobcat Goldthwait's pedestrian directing.

title: Dragon Ball: Sleeping Princess in Devil's Castle
Sleepless in Seattle
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Sleepover
tomato_consensus: 'Tween girls will enjoy this sugar coated fluff, but others will find Sleepover a snooze.

title: Sleepy Hollow
tomato_consensus: Sleepy Hollow entertains with its stunning visuals and creepy atmosphere.

title: Sleuth
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Sleuth
tomato_consensus: Sleuth is so obvious and coarse, rather than suspenseful and action-packed, that it does nothing to improve on the original version

title: Sliding Doors
tomato_consensus: Despite the gimmicky feel of the split narratives, the movie is watch-able due to the winning performances by the cast.

title: Sling Blade
tomato_consensus: You will see what's coming, but the masterful performances, especially Thornton's, will leave you riveted.

title: Slipstream
tomato_consensus: Slipstream is a failed experiment; confusing instead of coherent.

title: Slither
tomato_consensus: A slimy, rotten B-movie homage oozing with affection for low-budget horror films, Slither is a tale of creepy crawly little beasts that invade Smalltown, USA. Equally creepy and funny, critics say it's one of the most enjoyable of its type in years -- if you've got the stomach for this sort of thing. Slither is a wicked good time: it'll make you squirm -- when you're not busting a gut laughing.

title: Slow Burn
tomato_consensus: With wooden acting and hammy, overheated dialogue, Slow Burn isn't so much a noir as it is a mediocre parody of one.

title: Slumdog Millionaire
tomato_consensus: Visually dazzling and emotionally resonant, Slumdog Millionaire is a film that's both entertaining and powerful.

title: Small Change
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Small Sacrifices
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: Small Time Crooks
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Woody Allen rises from his recent slump with Small Time Crooks. A simple, funny movie, Crooks proves Allen still has the touch that made his name synonymous with off-beat comedy.

title: Smart People
tomato_consensus: Despite its sharp cast and a few laughs, Smart People is too thinly plotted to fully resonate.

title: Smash-Up: The Story of a Woman
wiki_title: Smash-Up, the Story of a Woman

title: Smiles of a Summer Night
awards: Nominated for 3 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Smiley Face
tomato_consensus: Although many of the jokes have been done before, Anna Faris's bright performance and Gregg Araki's sharp direction make Smiley Face more than your average stoner comedy.

title: Smokin' Aces
tomato_consensus: A violent mess of a movie, Smokin' Aces has some Quentin Tarantino's style but not much of his wit or humor.

title: Snake and Crane Arts of Shaolin
Snakes on a Plane
tomato_consensus: Snakes on a Plane lives up to its title, featuring snakes on a plane. It isn't perfect, but then again, it doesn't need to be.

title: Snatch.
tomato_consensus: Though perhaps a case of style over substance, Guy Ritchie's second crime caper is full of snappy dialogue, dark comedy, and interesting characters.

title: Snitch
tomato_consensus: Though it features one of Dwayne Johnson's more thoughtful performances, the presentation of Snitch's underlying message is muddled by lackluster storytelling and some tonal inconsistencies.

title: Snow Angels
tomato_consensus: With fine acting and considerable emotional depth, Snow Angels aptly captures the highs, and especially the lows of human relationships.

title: Snow Cake
tomato_consensus: Sigourney Weaver gracefully undertakes a difficult role, while the rest of the cast lifts the histrionic plot into something worthwhile.

title: Snow Day
tomato_consensus: Weak assembly of characters and story lines made this movie forgettable and silly.

title: Snow Dogs
tomato_consensus: A mediocre live-action children's movie, Snow Dogs is filled with cliched dialogue, tiresome pratfalls, and stale fish-out-of-water jokes.

title: Snow Falling on Cedars
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though Snow Falling on Cedars is beautiful to look at, critics say the story becomes dull and tedious to sit through.

title: Snow White and the Huntsman
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 10 wins & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While it offers an appropriately dark take on the fairy tale that inspired it, Snow White and the Huntsman is undone by uneven acting, problematic pacing, and a confused script.

title: Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 3 nominations.
wiki_title: Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)

title: Snow White and the Three Stooges
wiki_title: Snow White and the Three Stooges

title: The Snowtown Murders
tomato_consensus: It's a bleak and brutal endurance test, but for viewers with the strength and patience to make it to the end, Snowtown will prove an uncommonly powerful viewing experience.

title: So Close
tomato_consensus: This HK actioner oozes with style.

title: So I Married an Axe Murderer
wiki_title: So I Married an Axe Murderer

title: Solaris
tomato_consensus: Solaris is a haunting, meditative film that uses sci-fi to raise complex questions about humanity and existence.

title: Solaris
tomato_consensus: Slow-moving, cerebral, and ambiguous, Solaris is not a movie for everyone, but it offers intriguing issues to ponder.

title: Soldier's Girl
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Soldier
tomato_consensus: A boring genre film and a waste of a good set.

title: Soldier of Orange
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.

title: Solitary Man
tomato_consensus: Built around a singularly unpleasant main character, Solitary Man needed a flawless central performance to succeed -- and Michael Douglas delivers.

title: Solo
tomato_consensus: Featuring hammy performances and bland characters, Solo is an all too straightforward actioner that's both predictable and instantly forgettable.

title: Somebody Up There Likes Me
wiki_title: Somebody Up There Likes Me (1956 film)

title: Someone Like You...
tomato_consensus: A light and predictable, if somewhat shallow, romantic comedy that's easy to sit through because of the charming leads.

title: Someone to Watch Over Me
tomato_consensus: Its plot is sometimes hard to swallow, but some fine acting and director Ridley Scott's stylish visual flair make Someone to Watch Over Me an engaging police thriller.

title: Somersault
tomato_consensus: A poignant coming-of-age tale marked by a breakout lead performance from Abbie Cornish and a successful directorial debut from Cate Shortland.

title: Something's Gotta Give
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Keaton shines in this smartly funny romantic comedy.

title: Something New
tomato_consensus: Something New tackles serious questions about race and interracial relationships with genuine appeal and an alluring romance that develops as naturally as the plot.

title: Something Wicked This Way Comes
wiki_title: Something Wicked This Way Comes (1983 film)

title: Something Wild
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Something to Talk About
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 nominations.

title: Somewhere
tomato_consensus: It covers familiar territory for Sofia Coppola, but Somewhere remains a hypnotic, seductively pensive meditation on the nature of celebrity, anchored by charming performances from Stephen Dorff and Elle Fanning.

title: Somewhere in Time
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Son of Rambow
tomato_consensus: Undeniable heart and charming young leads save the film's nostalgic storyline from suffering at the hands predictability.

title: Son of the Mask
tomato_consensus: Overly frantic, painfully unfunny, and sorely missing the presence of Jim Carrey.

title: Songcatcher
tomato_consensus: The story may be a bit too melodramatic, but great performances abound in Songcatcher. The real reason to see the movie, however, is the hypnotic music.

title: Scenes of City Life
wiki_title: Sons and Daughters in a Time of Storm

title: Sophie Scholl: The Final Days
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 19 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A film that begs the audience to reflect upon their own courage and strength of character in light of this young heroine's daring story.

title: Sorority Babes in the Slimeball Bowl-O-Rama
wiki_title: Sorority Babes in the Slimeball Bowl-O-Rama

title: Sorority Boys
tomato_consensus: A sloppy fratboy movie, Sorority Boys offers up a parade of gross-out gags and sex jokes, while insulting and ogling women.

title: Sorority Row
tomato_consensus: Though it's slick and stylish, Sorority Row offers nothing new to the slasher genre and misses the mark both in its attempts at humor and thrills.

title: Soul Plane
tomato_consensus: A raunchy sendup of Airplane! that never really takes off.

title: Soul Surfer
tomato_consensus: There's an amazing true story at the heart of Soul Surfer -- and unfortunately, it's drowned by waves of Hollywood cheese.

title: Soul Survivors
tomato_consensus: Soul Survivors' stock characters and utter lack of suspense gives viewers little reason to attempt deciphering the confusing plot.

title: Sound City
tomato_consensus: Smart, affectionate, and unabashedly sincere, Sound City pairs a great soundtrack with a well-argued ode to one of rock 'n' roll's most fondly remembered bygone eras.

title: Sounder
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Source Code
tomato_consensus: Finding the human story amidst the action, director Duncan Jones and charming Jake Gyllenhaal craft a smart, satisfying sci-fi thriller.

title: South Park: Bigger Longer & Uncut
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its jokes are profoundly bold and rude but incredibly funny at the same time.

title: Southern Comfort
awards: Nominated for 1 Primetime Emmy. Another 6 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Space Chimps
tomato_consensus: Space Chimps' cheap animation and overabundance of monkey puns feels especially dated in a post-Wall-E world.

title: Space Cowboys
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While the plot is overly cliched, the suberb acting by the stars (especially the tense interactions between Clint Eastwood and Tommy Lee Jones) and the spectacular special effects make this a movie worth seeing.

title: Space Jam
tomato_consensus: A harmless mishmash of basketball and animation that'll entertain kids but leave adults less than thrilled.

title: Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone
wiki_title: Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone

title: Spanglish
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 4 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Paz Vega shines, and Adam Sandler gives a performance of thoughtfulness and depth, but Spanglish is ultimately undermined by sitcommy plotting and unearned uplift.

title: Sparkle
tomato_consensus: While undeniably melodramatic and old-fashioned, Sparkle transcends its formulaic trappings thanks to Salim Akil's empathetic direction and strong performances from a committed cast.

title: Spartacus
tomato_consensus: Featuring terrific performances and epic action, Kubrick's restored swords-and-sandals epic is a true classic.

title: Spartan
tomato_consensus: A good cast and Mamet's mastery over the written language elevate an otherwise conventional thriller.

title: Spawn
tomato_consensus: Spawn is an overbearing, over-violent film that adds little to the comic book adaptation genre.

title: Speed
tomato_consensus: A terrific popcorn thriller, Speed is taut, tense, and energetic, with outstanding performances from Keanu Reeves, Dennis Hopper, and Sandra Bullock.

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
tomato_consensus: Speed 2 falls far short of its predecessor, thanks to laughable dialogue, thin characterization, unsurprisingly familiar plot devices, and action sequences that fail to generate any excitement.

title: Speed Racer
tomato_consensus: The Wachowski Brothers have overloaded Speed Racer with headache-inducing special effects, and neglected to develop a coherent storyline.

title: Spellbound
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 16 wins & 8 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A suspenseful, gripping documentary that features an engaging cross section of American children.

title: Sphere
tomato_consensus: Sphere features an A-level cast working with B-grade material, with a story seen previously in superior science-fiction films.

title: Spider-Man
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 44 nominations.

title: Spider-Man 2
tomato_consensus: Boasting an entertaining villain and deeper emotional focus, this is a nimble sequel that improves upon the original.

title: Spider-Man 3
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win & 26 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though there are more characters and plotlines, and the action sequences still dazzle, Spider-Man 3 nonetheless isn't quite as refined as the first two.

title: Spider
tomato_consensus: Ralph Fiennes is brilliant in this accomplished and haunting David Cronenberg film.

title: Spider Baby or, The Maddest Story Ever Told
Spirit: Stallion of the Cimarron
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 15 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A visually stunning film that may be too predictable and politically correct for adults, but should serve children well.

title: Spirited Away
tomato_consensus: Spirited Away is a dazzling, enchanting, and gorgeously drawn fairy tale that will leave viewers a little more curious and fascinated by the world around them.

title: Splash
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A perfectly light, warmly funny romantic comedy that's kept afloat by Ron Howard's unobtrusive direction and charming performances from Tom Hanks and Daryl Hannah.

title: Splice
tomato_consensus: It doesn't take its terrific premise quite as far as it should, but Splice is a smart, well-acted treat for horror fans.

title: Spread
tomato_consensus: Despite occasional detours into surprisingly dark territory, Spread overall is an ineffectual celebration of vacuous Los Angeles high life rather than a deconstruction of it.

title: Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring
tomato_consensus: A visually stunning and contemplative piece of work.
wiki_title: Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter... and Spring

title: Spring Breakers
tomato_consensus: Spring Breakers blends stinging social commentary with bikini cheesecake and a bravura James Franco performance.

title: Springtime in a Small Town
tomato_consensus: Director Tian Zhuangzhuang's remake of the 1949 Chinese classic may be too measured in pace for some audiences, but it's a visually sumptuous, well-acted piece.

title: Spun
tomato_consensus: A chaotic drug movie that has little substance behind the stylistic flash.

title: Spy Game
tomato_consensus: The outcome of the kinetic Spy Game is never in doubt, but it is fun watching Robert Redford and Brad Pitt work.

title: Spy Hard
tomato_consensus: Leslie Nielsen's comic gifts are undisputed, but Spy Hard's lazy script and slapdash direction fail to take advantage of them.

title: Spy Kids
tomato_consensus: A kinetic and fun movie that's sure to thrill children of all ages.

title: Spy Kids: All the Time in the World in 4D
tomato_consensus: Burdened by a rote plot and unfunny scatological humor, All the Time in the World suggests that the Spy Kids franchise has run its course.
wiki_title: Spy Kids: All the Time in the World in 4D

title: Spy Kids 2: Island of Lost Dreams
tomato_consensus: Though the concept is no longer fresh, Spy Kids 2 is still an agreeable and energetic romp.
wiki_title: Spy Kids 2: The Island of Lost Dreams

title: Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over
tomato_consensus: The movie will be found wanting if one is not taken in by the 3-D visuals.

title: St. Trinian's
tomato_consensus: Both naughtier and campier than Ronald Searle's original post war series, this St. Trinian's leans on high jinks instead of performances or witty dialogue.

title: Stacy: Attack of the Schoolgirl Zombies
Stake Land
tomato_consensus: Though the genre is well worn at this point, director Jim Mickle focuses on strong characterization and eerie atmosphere to craft an effective apocalyptic vampire chiller that also manages to pack a mean punch.

title: Stalag 17
tomato_consensus: Stalag 17 survives the jump from stage to screen with flying colors, thanks to Billy Wilder's typically sterling direction and a darkly funny script.

title: Stalker
tomato_consensus: Stalker is a complex, oblique parable that draws unforgettable images and philosophical musings from its sci-fi/thriller setting.

title: Stand Up Guys
tomato_consensus: Stand Up Guys largely wastes its talented cast in a resolutely mediocre comedy hampered by messy direction and a perfunctory script.

title: Stand by Me
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 10 nominations.

title: Stander
tomato_consensus: An unsatisfying account of Stander's life.

title: Standing in the Shadows of Motown
tomato_consensus: A toe-tapping tribute to the band that gave Motown its sound.
wiki_title: Standing in the Shadows of Motown (film)

title: Star!
awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 1 win & 4 nominations.

title: Star 80
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Star Trek: First Contact
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While fans of the series will surely appreciate it, First Contact is exciting, engaging, and visually appealing enough to entertain Star Trek novices.

title: Star Trek: Insurrection
tomato_consensus: Although not terrible, the sluggishly paced Insurrection plays like an extended episode of the TV series.

title: Star Trek: Nemesis
tomato_consensus: Nemesis has an interesting premise and some good action scenes, but the whole affair feels a bit tired.

title: Star Trek: The Motion Picture
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 15 nominations.

title: Star Trek
tomato_consensus: Star Trek reignites a classic franchise with action, humor, a strong story, and brilliant visuals, and will please traditional Trekkies and new fans alike.

title: Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan
tomato_consensus: Considered by many fans to be the best of the Star Trek movies, Khan features a strong plot, increased tension, and a sharp supporting performance from Ricardo Montalban.
wiki_title: Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan

title: Star Trek III: The Search for Spock
tomato_consensus: Though it may be short on dazzling special effects, The Search for Spock is still a strong Star Trek installment, thanks to affecting performances by its iconic cast.
wiki_title: Star Trek III: The Search for Spock

title: Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home is perhaps the lightest and most purely enjoyable entry of the long-running series, emphasizing the eccentricities of the Enterprise's crew.
wiki_title: Star Trek IV: The Voyage Home

title: Star Trek Into Darkness
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 28 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Visually spectacular and suitably action packed, Star Trek Into Darkness is a rock-solid installment in the venerable sci-fi franchise, even if it's not as fresh as its predecessor.

title: Star Trek V: The Final Frontier
tomato_consensus: Filled with dull action sequences and an underdeveloped storyline, this fifth Trek movie is probably the worst of the series.
wiki_title: Star Trek V: The Final Frontier

title: Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Undiscovered Country is a strong cinematic send-off for the original Trek crew, featuring some remarkable visuals and an intriguing, character-driven mystery plot.
wiki_title: Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country

title: Star Wars: The Clone Wars
tomato_consensus: Mechanical animation and a less-than stellar script make The Clone Wars a pale shadow of George Lucas' once great franchise.

title: Star Wars: Episode I - The Phantom Menace
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 52 nominations.
wiki_title: Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace

title: Star Wars: Episode II - Attack of the Clones
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 11 wins & 41 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though it still suffers from an overabundance of exposition, the action quotient is upped considerably in Star Wars: Episode II - Attack of the Clones, which makes it an improvement over The Phantom Menace.
wiki_title: Star Wars Episode II: Attack of the Clones

title: Star Wars: Episode III - Revenge of the Sith
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 29 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This sixth and final installment of George Lucas' epic space opera will please die-hard fanatics and non-believers alike -- largely due to awesome digital effects and the sheer power of the mythology.
wiki_title: Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith

title: Star Wars: Episode IV - A New Hope
tomato_consensus: A legendarily expansive and ambitious start to the sci-fi saga, George Lucas opened our eyes to the possiblites of blockbuster filmmaking and things have never been the same.
wiki_title: Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope

title: Stardust
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Stardust
tomato_consensus: A faithful interpretation that captures the spirit of whimsy, action, and off-kilter humor of Neil Gaiman, Stardust juggles multiple genres and tones to create a fantastical experience.

title: Starman
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: What initially begins as sci-fi transforms into a surprisingly sweet, offbeat drama, courtesy of John Carpenter's careful direction.

title: Starship Troopers
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A fun movie...if you can accept the excessive gore and wooden acting.

title: Starship Troopers 2: Hero of the Federation
wiki_title: Starship Troopers 2: Hero of the Federation

title: Starter for 10
tomato_consensus: Starter For 10 is a spirited coming-of-age tale that remains charming and witty even as it veers into darker teritory. The unique setting of a quiz show makes the film wittier than your average romantic comedy.

title: Startup.com
tomato_consensus: Startup.com is more than just a look at the rise and fall of the new economy. At its center is a friendship being tested to the limit, and that's what makes it worth viewing.

title: State and Main
tomato_consensus: State and Main offers plenty of wit and laughs in its lampoons of the movie industry.

title: State of Play
tomato_consensus: A taut, well-acted political thriller, State of Play overcomes some unsubtle plot twists with an intelligent script and swift direction.

title: Stay
tomato_consensus: A muddled brain-teaser, Stay has a solid cast and innovative visuals but little beneath the surface.

title: Stay Alive
tomato_consensus: A by-the-numbers teen horror flick, Stay Alive fails to exploit its premise for any real scares.

title: Staying Alive
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This sequel to Saturday Night Fever is shockingly embarrassing and unnecessary, trading the original's dramatic depth for a series of uninspired dance sequences.

title: Steal This Movie
tomato_consensus: D'Onofrio's performance fails to do justice to Hoffman, and the depiction of the 60s also rings false.

title: Stealing Harvard
tomato_consensus: There are laughs Stealing Harvard, but they are few and far between. Tom Green's antics grow old fast.

title: Stealth
tomato_consensus: Loud, preposterous, and predictable, Stealth borrows heavily and unsucessfully from Top Gun and 2001.

title: Steamboy
tomato_consensus: The story isn't the greatest, but there's an abundance of sci-fi eye candy to compensate.

title: Steel
tomato_consensus: Steel is a badly-acted movie that indulges not only in superhero cliches, but also the sappy TV-movie-of-the-week ones.

title: Steel Magnolias
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Step Brothers
tomato_consensus: The relentless immaturity of the humor is not a total handicap for this film, which features the consistently well-matched talents of Will Ferrell and John C. Reilly.

title: Step Into Liquid
tomato_consensus: A perfect companion piece to The Endless Summer.

title: Step Up
tomato_consensus: This trite teen romance has too little plot and not enough dancing.

title: Step Up 2: The Streets
tomato_consensus: There's a kinetic appeal to the handsome cast and their smooth moves, but everything else about Step Up 2 the Streets is been there, danced that.

title: Step Up 3D
tomato_consensus: It may not contain believable acting or a memorable plot, but Step Up 3-D delivers solid choreography and stunning visuals.

title: Step Up Revolution
tomato_consensus: Step Up Revolution treads familiar territory by surrounding its lively and kinetic dance sequences with a predictably generic story.

title: Stephanie Daley
tomato_consensus: The premise has all the trappings of melodrama, but the excellent performances give the characters complexity and empathy.

title: Stepmom
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 5 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Great performances from the leads can't save this factory mill tearjerker.

title: Stevie
tomato_consensus: Poignant documentary that's hard to forget.

title: Family Guy Presents Stewie Griffin: The Untold Story
Stick It
tomato_consensus: Director Jessica Bendinger is unable to transfer her winning Bring It On formula to the world of gymnastics, despite Missy Peregrym's strong lead performance.

title: Stigmata
tomato_consensus: The story is unconvincing and the acting is weak.

title: Still Crazy
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Still Life
tomato_consensus: Zhangke spellbindingly captures the human cost of rapid industrialization in modern China.

title: Still Walking
tomato_consensus: Hirokazu Kore-eda's film may seem modest at first, but this family drama casts a delicate, entrancing spell.

title: Stir of Echoes
tomato_consensus: Kevin Bacon's acting is so genuine that it's creepy and director David Keopp knows how to create true suspense.

title: Stoker
tomato_consensus: Its script doesn't quite carry the dramatic heft of his earlier work, but Park Chan-wook's Stoker showcases his eye for sumptuous imagery and his affection for dark, atmospheric narratives populated by mysterious characters.

title: Stolen Kisses
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Stolen Kisses is a fine feature follow-up to The 400 Blows, transforming Antoine Doinel into a sympathetic, silly, and romantic figure that carries to the series' end.

title: Stolen Summer
tomato_consensus: Stolen Summer feels like a sugary after-school special stretched out to feature length.

title: Stomp the Yard
tomato_consensus: While Stomp the Yard contains impressive musical and dance numbers, it loses its momentum during the intervening soap opera-style subplots.

title: Stone
tomato_consensus: Stone boasts a cast that includes Robert De Niro, Edward Norton, and Milla Jovovich, and it features strong dialogue, but it's ultimately undone by its heavy-handed symbolism and overabundant plot twists.

title: Stop! Or My Mom Will Shoot
wiki_title: Stop! Or My Mom Will Shoot

title: Stop-Loss
tomato_consensus: Stop-Loss is sincere and complex, and features strong performances, even if it tries to cover too much ground.

title: Alex Rider: Operation Stormbreaker
tomato_consensus: Alex Rider: Operation Stormbreaker is strictly children's fare, as it lacks originality, excitement, and believabiltity.

title: Story of Women
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 13 wins & 5 nominations.

title: The Adventures of Bob & Doug McKenzie: Strange Brew
tomato_consensus: Though lowbrow in intent and outcome, Strange Brew effectively mines laughs from its unique premise and likeable stars.

title: Strange Wilderness
tomato_consensus: Strange Wilderness is a laugh-free comedy that's both aimless and overly crass.

title: Stranger Than Fiction
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A fun, whimsical tale about an office drone trying to save his life from his narrator, Stranger Than Fiction features a subdued performances from Will Ferrell that contributes mightily to its quirky, mind-bending affect.

title: Strangers on a Train
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: A provocative premise and inventive set design lights the way for Hitchcock diabolically entertaining masterpiece.

title: Strangers with Candy
tomato_consensus: Occasionally funny, but little more than a jumbled, overextended episode of the TV show. Still, Candy devotees won't be disappointed.

title: Straw Dogs
tomato_consensus: A violent, provocative meditation on manhood with some of the most controversial scenes ever shot for a mainstream movie.

title: Straw Dogs
tomato_consensus: This remakes streamlines the plot but ultimately makes a fatal mistake: It celebrates violence.

title: Strawberry Shortcake: The Sweet Dreams Movie
wiki_title: Strawberry Shortcake: The Sweet Dreams Movie

title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li
tomato_consensus: The combination of a shallow plot and miscast performers renders Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun Li a perfectly forgettable video game adaptation.
wiki_title: Street Fighter: The Legend of Chun-Li

title: Street Fighter
tomato_consensus: Though it offers mild entertainment through campy one-liners and the overacting of the late Raul Julia, Street Fighter's nonstop action sequences are not enough to make up for a predictable, uneven storyline.

title: Street Fighter II: The Animated Movie
wiki_title: Street Fighter II: The Animated Movie

title: Street Kings
tomato_consensus: Street Kings contains formulaic violence but no shred of intelligence.

title: Strictly Ballroom
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 18 wins & 11 nominations.

title: Stuart Little 2
tomato_consensus: Stuart Little 2 is a sweet, visually impressive sequel that provides wholesome entertainment for kids.

title: Stuart Little 3: Call of the Wild
wiki_title: Stuart Little 3: Call of the Wild

title: Stuck
tomato_consensus: Steeped in gallows humor, Stuck is a taut, tense examination of a tragic accident.

title: Stuck in Love
tomato_consensus: It struggles to enliven its uneven script, but Stuck in Love boasts enough winning performances from its solid veteran cast to offer an appealing diversion for rom-com enthusiasts.

title: Submarine
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 6 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Funny, stylish, and ringing with adolescent truth, Submarine marks Richard Ayoade as a talent to watch.

title: Subway
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 11 nominations.

title: Sucker Punch
tomato_consensus: It's technically impressive and loaded with eye-catching images, but without characters or a plot to support them, all of Sucker Punch's visual thrills are for naught.

title: Sudden Fear
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Sugar & Spice
tomato_consensus: Though this cheerleader comedy has an intriguing premise, it's too empty-headed and saddled with too many lame jokes to live up to it. Also, some critics say the movie is irresponsible in its depiction of teens and guns.

title: Sugar
tomato_consensus: Sugar is an exceptionally-crafted film -- part sports flick, part immigrant tale -- with touching and poignant drama highlighted by splendid performances.

title: Sukiyaki Western Django
tomato_consensus: Inventive and off-kilter, the newest feast from J-Horror director Takashi Miike is super-sensory, self-referential and somewhat excessive.

title: Summer Catch
tomato_consensus: Cliched and predictable, Summer Catch is a reminder of better films.

title: Summer Hours
tomato_consensus: Olivier Assayas' contemplative family drama handles lofty ideas about art and culture with elegance and lightness.

title: Summer Palace
tomato_consensus: Though it suffers from excessive length and inconsistent pacing, Summer Palace is held aloft by Hao Lei's riveting performance.

title: Summertime
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Sunday Bloody Sunday
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Sunrise
tomato_consensus: Boasting masterful cinematography to match its well-acted, wonderfully romantic storyline, Sunrise is perhaps the final -- and arguably definitive -- statement of the silent era.
wiki_title: Sunrise: A Song of Two Humans

title: Sunrise at Campobello
awards: Nominated for 4 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Sunset
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Sunset Blvd.
tomato_consensus: Arguably the greatest movie about Hollywood, Billy Wilder's masterpiece Sunset Boulevard is a tremendously entertaining combination of noir, black comedy, and character study.

title: Sunshine Cleaning
tomato_consensus: Despite a sometimes overly familiar plot, Sunshine Cleaning benefits from the lively performances of its two stars.

title: Sunshine State
tomato_consensus: Wonderfully acted, but the story and pacing can use a little work.

title: Super 8
tomato_consensus: It may evoke memories of classic summer blockbusters a little too eagerly for some, but Super 8 has thrills, visual dazzle, and emotional depth to spare.

title: Super Size Me
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 6 nominations.

title: Super Troopers
tomato_consensus: A more-miss -than-hit affair, Super Troopers will most likely appeal to those looking for something silly.

title: Superbabies: Baby Geniuses 2
tomato_consensus: A startling lack of taste pervades Superbabies, a sequel offering further proof that bad jokes still aren't funny when coming from the mouths of babes.

title: Superbad
tomato_consensus: Deftly balancing vulgarity and sincerity while placing its protagonists in excessive situations, Superbad is an authentic take on friendship and the overarching awkwardness of the high school experience.

title: Supercop
tomato_consensus: Blending hand-to-hand combat with breathtaking stunts and slapstick comedy, Supercop reminds us why Jackie Chan is one of the world's great entertainers.

title: Supercross
tomato_consensus: While it showcases some cool stunts, Supercross feels like an infomercial for its titular sport, with undeveloped characters and a shopworn plot.

title: Supergirl
tomato_consensus: The effects are cheesy and Supergirl's wide-eyed, cheery heroine simply isn't interesting to watch for an hour and a half.

title: Superhero Movie
tomato_consensus: Superhero Movie is not the worst of the spoof genre, but relies on tired gags and lame pop culture references all the same.

title: Superman
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Superman deftly blends humor and gravitas, taking advantage of the perfectly cast Christopher Reeve to craft a loving, nostalgic tribute to an American pop culture icon.

title: Superman II
tomato_consensus: The humor occasionally stumbles into slapstick territory, and the special effects are dated, but Superman II meets, if not exceeds, the standard set by its predecessor.

title: Superman II
wiki_title: Superman II: The Richard Donner Cut

title: Superman III
tomato_consensus: When not overusing sight gags, slapstick, and Richard Pryor, Superman III resorts to plot points rehashed from the previous Superman flicks.

title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace
tomato_consensus: The Superman series bottoms out here: the action is boring, the special effects look cheaper, and none of the actors appear interested in where the plot's going.
wiki_title: Superman IV: The Quest for Peace

title: Superman Returns
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 10 wins & 22 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Bryan Singer's reverent and visually decadent adaptation gives the Man of Steel welcome emotional complexity. The result: a satisfying stick-to-your-ribs adaptation.

title: Supernova
tomato_consensus: This is an insult to the Sci-fi genre with no excitement and bad FX.

title: Superstar
tomato_consensus: Dumb script and flat jokes made this another SNL misfire.

title: Read My Lips
tomato_consensus: A clever and offbeat character study about two people discovering each other.

title: Surf's Up
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Surf's Up is a laid back, visually stunning animated movie that brings a fresh twist to some familiar conventions. Its witty mockumentary format is fun and inventive, and the CGI is breathtakingly realistic.

title: Surrogates
tomato_consensus: Though it sports a slick look and feel, Surrogates fails to capitalize on a promising premise, relying instead on mindless action and a poor script.

title: Surveillance
tomato_consensus: This dark psycho-thriller from Jennifer Lynch, is violent, sharp and baffling, but not to everyone's taste.

title: Survival of the Dead
tomato_consensus: Survival of the Dead offers glimmers of Romero's savage wit, but not nearly enough to make up for his unusually uninspired directing and a lack of new ideas

title: Surviving Christmas
tomato_consensus: Surviving Christmas is unpleasant characters attacking each other for 90 minutes before delivering a typical, hollow anti-consumerist message

title: Suspect Zero
tomato_consensus: Other than Ben Kingsley, there's not much to like in this preposterous thriller.

title: Suspiria
tomato_consensus: The blood pours freely in Argento's classic Suspiria, a giallo horror as grandiose and glossy as it is gory.

title: Swamp Thing
tomato_consensus: Unabashedly campy -- often to its detriment -- Swamp Thing is not without its charms, among them Adrienne Barbeau as the damsel in distress.

title: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street
wiki_title: Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street (1936 film)

title: Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street
tomato_consensus: Full of pith and Grand Guignol grossness, this macabre musical is perfectly helmed and highly entertaining. Tim Burton masterfully stages the musical in a way that will make you think he has done this many times before.
wiki_title: Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street (2007 film)

title: Sweet Charity
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Sweet Home Alabama
tomato_consensus: Reese Witherspoon is charming enough, but the road to Alabama is well-traveled.

title: Sweet Land
tomato_consensus: Finding the right balance between subtle and sentimental, Sweet Land moves beyond other similarly-themed dramas with evocative cinematography that plays an equal role to the talented cast.

title: Sweet November
tomato_consensus: Bad acting and direction plague this version of Sweet November. The story is unrealistic, as is the chemistry between Theron and Reeves.

title: Sweet Sixteen
tomato_consensus: A bleak, but heartbreaking coming-of-age tale that resonates with truth.

title: Sweet Smell of Success
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Sweet Smell of Success boasts a top-notch cast, sharp direction, atmospheric cinematography, and an appropriately jazzy score, making it one of the best noir crime thrillers ever made.

title: John Lennon and the Plastic Ono Band: Sweet Toronto
Sweet and Lowdown
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Critics praise Woody Allen's Sweet and Lowdown for its charming, light-hearted comedy and quality acting.

title: Swept Away
tomato_consensus: Muddled and lacking the political context of the original, Swept Away offers further proof that Madonna can't act.

title: Swept Away
wiki_title: Swept Away by an Unusual Destiny in the Blue Sea of August

title: Swimfan
tomato_consensus: A Fatal Attraction rip-off, Swimfan is a predictable, mediocre thriller.

title: Swimming Pool
tomato_consensus: A sensual thriller with two engaging performers demanding our undivided attention.

title: Swimming with Sharks
tomato_consensus: Swimming With Sharks is a smart, merciless Hollywood satire that's darkly hilarious and observant, thanks to Kevin Spacey's performance as ruthless studio mogul Buddy Ackerman.

title: Swing Shift
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Swing Vote
tomato_consensus: Despite Kevin Costner providing his most charismatic performance in years, Swing Vote fails to find the right mix of political satire and heartfelt drama.

title: Swingers
tomato_consensus: Funny, heartfelt, and effortlessly cool, Swingers made stars out of Vince Vaughn and Jon Favreau, established Doug Liman as a director to watch.

title: Switch
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 nominations.

title: Sword of the Valiant: The Legend of Sir Gawain and the Green Knight
wiki_title: Sword of the Valiant: The Legend of Sir Gawain and the Green Knight

title: Swordfish
tomato_consensus: Swordfish is big on explosions, but critics dislike how it skimps on plot and logic. Also, the sight of a person typing at a computer just isn't that interesting.

title: The Swordsman in Double Flag Town
Sydney White
tomato_consensus: Amanda Bynes is charming, but Sydney White is a poorly adapted take on Snow White, relying on tired ethnic stereotypes laughs.

title: Sylvia
tomato_consensus: This biopic about Sylvia Plath doesn't rise above the level of highbrow melodrama.

title: Lady Vengeance
tomato_consensus: Stylistically flashy and gruesomely violent, Sympathy for Lady Vengeance fits in nicely with the other two films of Park's revenge trilogy.

title: Sympathy for Mr. Vengeance
tomato_consensus: Though Park directs with stylistic flair, this revenge thriller is more excessively gruesome than thrilling.

title: Syndromes and a Century
tomato_consensus: Despite having little in the way of narrative, Apichatpong Weerasethakul's Syndromes is a poignant and mesmerizing memoir.

title: Synecdoche, New York
tomato_consensus: Charlie Kaufman's ambitious directorial debut occasionally strains to connect, but ultimately provides fascinating insight into a writer's mind.

title: Syriana
tomato_consensus: Ambitious, complicated, intellectual, and demanding of its audience, Syriana is both a gripping geopolitical thriller and wake-up call to the complacent.

title: Seance on a Wet Afternoon
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 8 wins & 3 nominations.

title: Love in the Time of Hysteria
Scamper the Penguin
wiki_title: The Adventures of Scamper the Penguin

title: Sax Rohmer's The Castle of Fu Manchu
country: West Germany, Italy, Spain, UK, Liechtenstein

title: The Sacrifice
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 8 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Saddest Music in the World
tomato_consensus: Guy Maddin perfectly recreates the look and feel of a 1930s in this bizarre picture.
wiki_title: The Saddest Music in the World

title: The Safety of Objects
tomato_consensus: The large cast of characters and scripting are too unwieldy, and the suburban angst theme feels tired.

title: The Saga of the Viking Women and Their Voyage to the Waters of the Great Sea Serpent
wiki_title: The Saga of the Viking Women and Their Voyage to the Waters of the Great Sea Serpent

title: The Saint
tomato_consensus: The Saint is watchable thanks to Kilmer and Shue, but the muddled screenplay stretches credulity.

title: The Salton Sea
tomato_consensus: A slick Tarantino-inspired movie that is not for everyone.

title: The Samaritan
tomato_consensus: The Samaritan is a ludicrous neo-noir starring a seemingly bored Samuel L. Jackson.

title: The Sand Pebbles
awards: Nominated for 8 Oscars. Another 5 wins & 10 nominations.

title: The Sandlot
tomato_consensus: It may be shamelessly derivative and overly nostalgic, but The Sandlot is nevertheless a genuinely sweet and funny coming-of-age adventure.

title: The Santa Clause
tomato_consensus: The Santa Clause is utterly undemanding, but it's firmly rooted in the sort of good old-fashioned holiday spirit missing from too many modern yuletide films.

title: The Santa Clause 2
tomato_consensus: Though it's harmless as family entertainment and has moments of charm, The Santa Clause 2 is also predictable and forgettable.

title: The Santa Clause 3: The Escape Clause
tomato_consensus: Playing Jack Frost as an evil cross between Liza Minnelli and Liberace, Martin Short is a welcome presence, but this tired series continues drawing from its bag of bland gags and dumb slapstick.
wiki_title: The Santa Clause 3: The Escape Clause

title: The Savages
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Thanks to a tender, funny script from director Tamara Jenkins, and fine performances from Philip Seymour Hoffman and Laura Linney, this film delivers a nuanced, beautifully three-dimensional look at the struggles and comforts of family bonds.

title: The Scalphunters
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: The Scent of Green Papaya
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Science of Sleep
tomato_consensus: Lovely and diffuse, Sleep isn't as immediately absorbing as Gondry's previous work, but its messy beauty is its own reward.

title: The Score
tomato_consensus: Though the movie treads familar ground in the heist/caper genre, DeNiro, Norton, and Brando make the movie worth watching.

title: The Scorpion King
tomato_consensus: Action adventure doesn't get much cheesier than The Scorpion King.

title: The Scorpion King: Rise of a Warrior
wiki_title: The Scorpion King 2: Rise of a Warrior

title: The Sea Inside
tomato_consensus: Held aloft by a transfixing performance from Javier Bardem as a terminally ill man who chooses to die, The Sea Inside transcends its melodramatic story with tenderness and grace.

title: The Second Jungle Book: Mowgli & Baloo
wiki_title: The Second Jungle Book: Mowgli & Baloo

title: The Secret Garden
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 3 wins & 5 nominations.

title: The Secret Life of Bees
tomato_consensus: The Secret Life of Bees has moments of charm, but is largely too maudlin and sticky-sweet.

title: The Secret Life of Walter Mitty
wiki_title: The Secret Life of Walter Mitty (1947 film)

title: The Secret Life of Words
tomato_consensus: The Secret Life of Words is a slow, mannered drama, but with a revelatory and powerful ending that rewards the patient viewer.

title: The Secret Lives of Dentists
tomato_consensus: A witty and honest look at marriage in decay.

title: The Secret War of Harry Frigg
wiki_title: The Secret War of Harry Frigg

title: The Secret World of Arrietty

title: The Secret of Kells

tomato_consensus: Beautifully drawn and refreshingly calm, The Secret of Kells hearkens back to animation's golden age with an enchanting tale inspired by Irish mythology.

wiki_title: The Secret of NIMH 2: Timmy to the Rescue

title: The Secret of the Grain
tomato_consensus: A complex portrait of an immigrant family, The Secret of the Grain is a sprawling, intimate film with many fine performances.

title: The Seeker: The Dark Is Rising
wiki_title: The Seeker: The Dark Is Rising

title: The Sentinel
tomato_consensus: The Sentinel starts off well enough but quickly wears thin with too many plot holes and conventional action sequences.

title: The Sessions

tomato_consensus: Tender, funny, and touching, The Sessions provides an acting showcase for its talented stars and proves it's possible for Hollywood to produce a grown-up movie about sex.

title: The Seven-Per-Cent Solution
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: The Shadow
tomato_consensus: Bringing a classic pulp character to the big screen, The Shadow features impressive visual effects, but the story ultimately fails to strike a memorable chord.

title: The Shaggy Dog
tomato_consensus: This Disney retread has neither inspiration nor originality, but may please moviegoers under the age of ten.

title: The Shawshank Redemption
awards: Nominated for 7 Oscars. Another 15 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Shawshank Redemption is an uplifting, deeply satisfying prison drama with sensitive direction and fine performances.

title: The Sheltering Sky
awards: Won 1 Golden Globe. Another 8 wins & 3 nominations.

title: The Shining
tomato_consensus: Though it deviates from Stephen King's novel, Stanley Kubrick's The Shining is a chilling, often baroque journey into madness -- exemplified by an unforgettable turn from Jack Nicholson

title: The Shipping News
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 2 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though solidly made and acted, The Shipping News is rather heavy-handed and dull, especially given the nature of its protagonist.

title: The Shoes of the Fisherman

title: The Shootist
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: The Shop Around the Corner
tomato_consensus: Deftly directed by Ernst Lubitsch from a smart, funny script by Samson Raphaelson, The Shop Around the Corner is a romantic comedy in the finest sense of the term.

title: The Signal
tomato_consensus: The Signal is gruesome, funny, and has big thoughts about society, but those disparate elements fail to come together convincingly.

title: The Silence of the Lambs
tomato_consensus: Director Jonathan Demme's smart, taut thriller teeters on the edge between psychological study and all-out horror, and benefits greatly from stellar performances by Anthony Hopkins and Jodie Foster.

title: The Simpsons Movie
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Simpsons Movie contains the hearty laughs, biting satire, and honest portrayal of an American family that makes the show so popular. And it boasts slicker animation and polished writing that hearkens back to the show's glory days.

title: The Singing Detective
tomato_consensus: Delightful performance from Robert Downey Jr. can't save The Singing Detective's transition from TV to the big screen.

title: The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants
tomato_consensus: This adaptation of a beloved novel charms with its heartwarming tale of friendship and young adulthood; realistic portrayals of the lives of teenage girls lend the comedy-drama sincerity, and may capture hearts outside the female-centric demographic.
wiki_title: The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)

title: The Sitter
tomato_consensus: With its recycled plot, misguided gags, and formula performance from Jonah Hill, The Sitter adds up to another disappointing entry from director David Gordon Green.

title: The Skeleton Key
tomato_consensus: Thanks to its creaky and formulaic script, The Skeleton Key is more mumbo-jumbo than hoodoo and more dull than scary.

title: The Skin I Live In
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 22 wins & 38 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The Skin I Live In lacks Almodovar's famously charged romance, replaced with a wonderfully bizarre and unpredictable detour into arthouse ick.

title: The Skulls
tomato_consensus: The Skulls is full of nonsense and empty of good script and plot.

title: The Slaughter Rule
tomato_consensus: A bleak but original indie, The Slaughter Rule benefits from outstanding performances by Ryan Gosling and David Morse.

title: The Slipper and the Rose: The Story of Cinderella
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 9 nominations.

title: The Smurfs 2
tomato_consensus: Like its predecessor, Smurfs 2 may amuse small children, but it's largely an unambitious, charm-free collection of slapstick gags and one-liners.

title: The Snows of Kilimanjaro
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: The Social Network
tomato_consensus: Impeccably scripted, beautifully directed, and filled with fine performances, The Social Network is a riveting, ambitious example of modern filmmaking at its finest.

title: The Soloist
tomato_consensus: Though it features strong performances by its lead players, a lack of narrative focus prevents The Soloist from hitting its mark.

title: Led Zeppelin: The Song Remains the Same

tomato_consensus: Taken 2 is largely bereft of the kinetic thrills -- and surprises -- that made the original a hit.

tomato_consensus: Takers boasts some gripping set pieces and keeps things moving quickly, but its two-dimensional characters, clich?d script, and brazenly derivative plot make it hard to recommend.

title: Taking Off

tomato_consensus: Silly and unfunny remake of a French movie of the same name.

tomato_consensus: Team America will either offend you or leave you in stitches. It'll probably do both.

tomato_consensus: Not only is the movie's juvenile dialogue unbearable for adults, but the turtles' dopey and casual attitude towards physical violence makes them poor kids' role models.

tomato_consensus: It's a case of one sequel too many for the heroes in a half shell, with a tired time-travel plot gimmick failing to save the franchise from rapidly diminishing returns.

wiki_title: The Thousand Eyes of Dr. Mabuse

title: The Three Caballeros
tomato_consensus: One of Disney's more abstract creations, The Three Caballeros is a dazzling, colorful picture that shows the company at an artistic acme.

title: The Three Stooges

title: The Three Stooges Go Around the World in a Daze
wiki_title: The Three Stooges Go Around the World in a Daze

title: The Tigger Movie
tomato_consensus: Tigger Movie may lack the technological flash and underlying adult sophistication of other recent animated movies, but it's fun and charming.

title: The Time Traveler's Wife
tomato_consensus: Though it may satisfy fans of the novel, The Time Traveler's Wife's plot contrivances and illogical narrative hamper its big screen effectiveness.

title: The Tourist
awards: Nominated for 3 Golden Globes. Another 3 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: The scenery and the stars are undeniably beautiful, but they can't make up for The Tourist's slow, muddled plot, or the lack of chemistry between Johnny Depp and Angelina Jolie.

title: The Town
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 24 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Tense, smartly written, and wonderfully cast, The Town proves that Ben Affleck has rediscovered his muse -- and that he's a director to be reckoned with.

wiki_title: The Toxic Avenger Part III: The Last Temptation of Toxie

title: The Tracey Fragments

title: The Trail of the Lonesome Pine
wiki_title: The Trail of the Lonesome Pine (1936 film)

title: The Train
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: The Transporter

tomato_consensus: Terrence Malick's singularly deliberate style may prove unrewarding for some, but for patient viewers, Tree of Life is an emotional as well as visual treat.

title: The Truman Show
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 32 wins & 37 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A funny, tender, and thought-provoking film, The Truman Show is all the more noteworthy for its remarkably prescient vision of runaway celebrity culture and a nation with an insatiable thirst for the private details of ordinary lives.

title: The Trumpet of the Swan
tomato_consensus: An uninspired E.B. White adaptation that's targeted at the very young.

title: The Truth About Cats & Dogs

title: The Turning Point
awards: Nominated for 11 Oscars. Another 11 wins & 7 nominations.

title: The Tuxedo
tomato_consensus: Chan is as charming as ever, but his talents are squandered by special effects and bad writing.

title: The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 1
tomato_consensus: Slow, joyless, and loaded with unintentionally humorous moments, Breaking Dawn Part 1 may satisfy the Twilight faithful, but it's strictly for fans of the franchise.
wiki_title: The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 1

title: The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 2
tomato_consensus: It's the most entertaining Twilight, but that's not enough to make Breaking Dawn Part 2 worth watching for filmgoers who don't already count themselves among the franchise converts.
wiki_title: The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Part 2

title: The Twilight Saga: Eclipse
tomato_consensus: Stuffed with characters and overly reliant on uninspired dialogue, Eclipse won't win The Twilight Saga many new converts, despite an improved blend of romance and action fantasy.

title: The Twilight Samurai

tomato_consensus: Samurai epic as a touching drama.

title: The Two Faces of Dr. Jekyll
wiki_title: The Two Faces of Dr. Jekyll

title: Theatre of Blood
tomato_consensus: Deliciously campy and wonderfully funny, Theater of Blood features Vincent Price at his melodramatic best.

title: Thelma & Louise
tomato_consensus: Simultaneously funny, heartbreaking, and peppered with action, Ridley Scott's Thelma & Louise is a potent, well-acted road movie that transcends the feminist message at its core.

title: Them!
tomato_consensus: One of the best creature features of the early atomic age, Them! features effectively menacing special effects and avoids the self-parody that would taint later monster movies.

title: Them
tomato_consensus: Suspenseful and tense from start to finish, the French horror film Them proves that a lack of gore doesn't mean a dearth of scares.

title: Then She Found Me
tomato_consensus: A threadbare story anchored by strong performances, Then She Found Me is a mostly successful directorial debut by Helen Hunt.

title: There's No Business Like Show Business
wiki_title: There's No Business Like Show Business (film)

title: There Will Be Blood
tomato_consensus: Widely touted as a masterpiece, this sparse and sprawling epic about the underhanded "heroes" of capitalism boasts incredible performances by leads Daniel Day-Lewis and Paul Dano, and is director Paul Thomas Anderson's best work to date.

title: There Will Be No Leave Today
wiki_title: There Will Be No Leave Today

title: They

title: They Died with Their Boots On

title: They Live
tomato_consensus: A politically subversive blend of horror and sci fi, They Live is an underrated genre film from John Carpenter.

wiki_title: Things You Can Tell Just by Looking at Her

title: Things to Do in Denver When You're Dead
wiki_title: Things to Do in Denver When You're Dead

title: Think Like a Man
tomato_consensus: In Think Like a Man, an otherwise standard rom-com is partially elevated by a committed -- and attractive -- cast, resulting in a funny take on modern romance.

title: Thirteen Conversations About One Thing
tomato_consensus: Thirteen Conversations About One Thing is an intelligent and poignant look at lives intersecting.

tomato_consensus: This Christmas features strong performances and a sharp portrayal of family dynamics, but relies too heavily on holiday movie clich?s.

wiki_title: This Film Is Not Yet Rated

title: Thor

tomato_consensus: Timecrimes is a low-budget thriller that's well-crafted and loaded with dark humor and bizarre twists.

tomato_consensus: This incoherently plotted addition to the time-travel genre looks and sounds cheesy.

wiki_title: Tom and Jerry: The Magic Ring

tomato_consensus: A thoroughly entertaining character study and a great success for Mike Leigh.

title: Tormented
tomato_consensus: It relies too heavily on American slasher cliches, but Tormented is a timely, funny, and even somewhat touching entry in the high school horror genre.

title: Torque
tomato_consensus: Silly and noisy, Torque is stylish fun for the MTV crowd.

title: Torremolinos 73
tomato_consensus: A light tale that's big on heart, this spicy snapshot of domestic sexuality in '70s Spain treats its wacky protagonists with enough gentle humanity to be delightfully entertaining.

title: Torrente, el brazo tonto de la ley
wiki_title: Torrente, el brazo tonto de la ley

title: Tortilla Soup
tomato_consensus: An English remake of Ang Lee's Eat Drink Man Woman, Tortilla Soup is as charming and flavorful as the dishes it features.

title: Total Recall
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 7 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Under Paul Verhoeven's frenetic direction, Total Recall is a fast-paced rush of violence, gore, and humor that never slacks.

title: Total Recall
tomato_consensus: While it boasts some impressive action sequences, Total Recall lacks the intricate plotting, wry humor, and fleshed out characters that made the original a sci-fi classic.

title: Touch of Pink
tomato_consensus: Kyle MacLachlan does a very good imitation Cary Grant in this forced and contrived tale.

title: Touching the Void
tomato_consensus: Gripping even though the outcome is known.

title: Towelhead
tomato_consensus: This story of politics, race and, sexual awakening has moments that pack a punch, but overall, Towelhead never quite achieves the nuance of helmer Alan Ball's television work.

title: Tower Heist
tomato_consensus: Tower Heist is a true Brett Ratner joint: little brains to this caper, but it's fun fluff, exciting to watch, and showcases a welcome return to form for Eddie Murphy.

title: Town & Country
tomato_consensus: Afflicted with extensive re-editing and re-writing, this sex comedy feels confusingly choppy. Also, the main characters are so wealthy and privileged that it's difficult to feel sympathy for their problems.

title: Toy Story
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 19 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: As entertaining as it is innovative, Toy Story kicked off Pixar's unprecedented run of quality pictures, reinvigorating animated film in the process.

title: Toy Story 2
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 20 wins & 20 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Toy Story 2 employs inventive storytelling, gorgeous animation, and a top notch voice cast to deliver another rich moviegoing experience for all ages, one that's arguably even better than its predecessor.

title: Trade
tomato_consensus: With an exploitative style that seems more suited for TV shows like CSI, Trade's message about the reality of child exploitation is easily lost.

title: Trading Places
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Featuring deft interplay between Eddie Murphy and Dan Dan Aykroyd, Trading Places is an immensely appealing social satire.

title: Trailer Park Boys: The Movie
tomato_consensus: Trailer Park Boys suffers from its small-screen origins, and its tasteless humor is not for everyone, but it will satisfy fans of the genre.

title: Training Day
tomato_consensus: The ending may be less than satisfying, but Denzel Washington reminds us why he's such a great actor in this taut and brutal police drama.

title: Trainspotting
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 19 wins & 16 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A brutal, often times funny, other times terrifying portrayal of drug addiction in Edinburgh. Not for the faint of heart, but well worth viewing as a realistic and entertaining reminder of the horrors of drug use.

title: Traitor
tomato_consensus: Despite another reliable performance from Don Cheadle, Traitor suffers from too many cliches and an unfocused narrative.

title: Transamerica
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 28 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A terrific performance by Felicity Huffman carries this unconventional but touching transgender road movie.

title: Transformers: Dark of the Moon
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 27 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Its special effects -- and 3D shots -- are undeniably impressive, but they aren't enough to fill up its loud, bloated running time, or mask its thin, indifferent script.

title: Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen is a noisy, underplotted, and overlong special effects extravaganza that lacks a human touch.

title: Transformers
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 12 wins & 30 nominations.

title: Transporter 3
tomato_consensus: This middling installment in the Transporter franchise is a few steps down from its predecessors, featuring generic stunts and a lack of energy.

title: Transsiberian
tomato_consensus: Traditional in form yet effective in execution, this taut thriller updates the "danger on a train" scenario with atmospheric sense.

title: Trapped
tomato_consensus: With its plot about child kidnapping and endangerment, Trapped is an exploitative thriller, more queasy than suspenseful.

title: Treasure Island
country: France, Italy, Spain, UK, West Germany

title: Treasure Planet
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 10 nominations.

title: Tribute
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 12 nominations.

title: Tristan + Isolde
tomato_consensus: Competent but somewhat static, Tristan & Isolde doesn't achieve the sweeping romanticism that it aims for.

title: Tristana
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 9 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Trouble with the Curve

title: Troy
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A brawny, entertaining spectacle, but lacking emotional resonance.

title: True Lies

title: Tucker: The Man and His Dream
