title: Turn It Up
tomato_consensus: Reviewers say Turn It Up has a derivative feel, running through too many urban movie cliches.

tomato_consensus: Full of disorienting visual effects, Carl Theodor Dreyer's Vampyr is as theoretically unsettling as it is conceptually disturbing.

title: Van Wilder 2: The Rise of Taj
tomato_consensus: A low-brow comedy, minus the comedy.
wiki_title: Van Wilder 2: Rise of the Taj

title: Vanilla Sky
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An ambitious mix of genres, Vanilla Sky collapses into an incoherent jumble. Cruise's performance lacks depth, and it's hard to feel sympathy for his narcissistic character.

title: Vanity Fair
tomato_consensus: A more likable Becky Sharp makes for a less interesting movie.

title: Vantage Point
tomato_consensus: Vantage Point has an interesting premise that is completely undermined by fractured storytelling and wooden performances.

title: Vanya on 42nd Street
tomato_consensus: Beautiful performances and the subtle hand of master Louis Malle make this adaptation of Chekov's Uncle Vanya an eccentric presentation of an enduring classic.

title: Varsity Blues
tomato_consensus: This is a predictable football movie that lacks intensity.

title: Vatel
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Velvet Goldmine
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Venom
tomato_consensus: A voodoo horror flick without the mojo, Venom is chock full of gory impalings of interchangeable teenage girls and hunky guys by an unstoppable zombie whose unimaginative rampage quickly lulls us to sleep.

title: Venus
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Audiences may attend to witness Peter O'Toole's Oscar-worthy performance, but they'll also be treated to a humane, tender exploration of maturing with both dignity and irreverence.

title: Vera Drake
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 36 wins & 28 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With a piercingly powerful performance by Imelda Staunton, Vera Drake brings teeming humanity to the controversial subject of abortion.

title: Veronica Guerin
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 13 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Cate Blanchett gives another great performance in a movie that doesn't shed much light on its title character.

title: Vertical Limit
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 2 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: The plot in Vertical Limit is ludicrously contrived and cliched. Meanwhile, the action sequences are so over-the-top and piled one on top of another, they lessen the impact on the viewer.

title: The Vertical Ray of the Sun
tomato_consensus: The Vertical Ray of the Sun is gorgeously, poetically composed, lulling the viewer into its story of everyday life.

title: Vertigo
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An unpredictable scary thriller that doubles as a mournful meditation on love, loss, and human comfort.

title: Vicky Cristina Barcelona
tomato_consensus: A beguiling tragicomedy, Vicky Cristina Barcelona charms with beautiful views of the Spanish city and a marvelously well-matched cast.

title: Victim
awards: Nominated for 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 nomination.

title: Victor Victoria
tomato_consensus: Driven by a fantastic lead turn from Julie Andrews, Blake Edwards' musical gender-bender is sharp, funny and all-round entertaining.

title: Videodrome
tomato_consensus: Visually audacious, disorienting, and just plain weird, Videodrome's musings on technology, entertainment, and politics still feel fresh today.

title: View from the Top
tomato_consensus: Uneven in tone and badly edited, A View From the Top wastes the talents of its cast and condescends to its characters.

title: Village of the Damned
tomato_consensus: Chilling performances and a restrained, eerie atmosphere make this British horror both an unnerving parable of its era and a timeless classic.

title: Virgin Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors
wiki_title: Virgin Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors

title: Virginia
tomato_consensus: Brave, autobiographical, but also completely off the mark, Virginia is a frantic drama that fails to pull the viewer in.

title: Virus
tomato_consensus: Despite its great special effects, this movie's predictability greatly undermines its intensity.

title: Viva Maria!
awards: Won 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 nomination.

title: Innocent Voices
tomato_consensus: Innocent Voices is a passionately told dramatization of an ugly issue of war -- its impact on children.

title: Volver
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 55 wins & 53 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Volver catches director Pedro Almodovar and star Penelope Cruz at the peak of their respective powers, in service of a layered, thought-provoking film. This magical tragicomic melodrama may be Almodovar's most restrained work to date, but it still features his trademarks: a strong attention to color and detail, a celebration of the trials and tribulations of women, and, of course, the inestimable Carmen Maura. The lovely Penelope Cruz hasn't shone more brightly as she does here.

title: Von Ryan's Express
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 1 nomination.

title: Voyage of the Damned
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 1 win & 6 nominations.

title: Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea
wiki_title: Voyage to the Bottom of the Sea

title: Voyage to the Planet of Prehistoric Women
wiki_title: Voyage to the Planet of Prehistoric Women

title: The Return
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 27 wins & 12 nominations.

title: Vulgar
tomato_consensus: Vulgar more than lives up to its title.

title: W.E.
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 3 nominations.

title: W.
country: USA, Australia, Hong Kong, Switzerland, China
tomato_consensus: A surprisingly sympathetic portrayal of the 43rd American president, W. is fascinating in spots, but merely rudimentary as a whole.

title: WALL·E
tomato_consensus: Charming, audacious, and timely, Wall-E's lighthearted magic and stellar visuals testify once again to Pixar's ingenuity.

title: Wadjda
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 18 wins & 17 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Transgressive in the best possible way, Wadjda presents a startlingly assured new voice from a corner of the globe where cinema has been all but silenced.

title: Wag the Dog
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 3 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Smart, well-acted, and uncomfortably prescient political satire from director Barry Levinson and and all-star cast.

title: Wagons East
tomato_consensus: Wagons East! is a witless, toothless satire of Westerns that falls far below the standard set by Blazing Saddles, and is notable only for being John Candy's final screen performance.

title: Wah-Wah
tomato_consensus: The ensemble cast is strong, but they get overpowered by the muddled stew of melodrama.

title: Waist Deep
tomato_consensus: A well-meaning B-movie that suffers from a cliche-ridden script and poorly drawn characters that fail to inspire much sympathy.

title: Wait Until Dark
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 3 nominations.

title: Waiting...
tomato_consensus: Waiting... is a gross-out comedy that is more gross than comic.

title: Waiting for 'Superman'
tomato_consensus: Gripping, heartbreaking, and ultimately hopeful, Waiting for Superman is an impassioned indictment of the American school system from An Inconvenient Truth director Davis Guggenheim.

title: Waiting for Guffman
tomato_consensus: This riotously deadpan mockumentary about aspiring community theater performers never stoops to ridicule oft-ridiculous characters.

title: Waitress
tomato_consensus: Sweet, smart, and quirky, Waitress hits the right, bittersweet notes through this romantic comedy through its witty script and a superb performance by Keri Russell.

title: Wake Me When the War Is Over
wiki_title: Wake Me When the War Is Over

title: Waking Life
tomato_consensus: The talky, animated Waking Life is a unique, cerebral experience.

title: Wal-Mart: The High Cost of Low Price
wiki_title: Wal-Mart: The High Cost of Low Price

title: Walk Hard: The Dewey Cox Story
awards: Nominated for 2 Golden Globes. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A parody that pokes fun at rock stars and reductive biopics alike, this comedy sings in large part because of stellar performances and clever original music.
wiki_title: Walk Hard: The Dewey Cox Story

title: Walk on Water
tomato_consensus: Politically complex and ambitious, Walk on Water delivers a memorable story of guilt, revenge, and human connectivity.

title: Walk the Line
tomato_consensus: Superior acting and authentic crooning capture the emotional subtleties of the legend of Johnny Cash and his inevitable downfall with a freshness that is a pleasure to watch.

title: Walking Tall
tomato_consensus: The Rock makes a competent hero, but the movie is content to let a 2x4 do all the talking.

title: Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.
tomato_consensus: It's more entertaining than many sequels, but with Oliver Stone directing, a terrific cast, and a timely storyline that picks up where the original left off, Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps should be better.

title: Wallace & Gromit: The Best of Aardman Animation
wiki_title: Wallace & Gromit: The Best of Aardman Animation

title: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit
tomato_consensus: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit is a subtly touching and wonderfully eccentric adventure featuring Wallace and Gromit.
wiki_title: Wallace & Gromit: The Curse of the Were-Rabbit

title: The Wrong Trousers
wiki_title: Wallace & Gromit in The Wrong Trousers

title: A Close Shave
wiki_title: Wallace and Gromit in A Close Shave

title: Waltz with Bashir
country: Israel, France, Germany, USA, Finland, Switzerland, Belgium, Australia
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 41 wins & 27 nominations.
tomato_consensus: A wholly innovative, original, and vital history lesson, with pioneering animation, Waltz With Bashir delivers its message about the Middle East in a mesmerizing fashion.

title: Wanderlust
tomato_consensus: It isn't always as funny as it should be, but Wanderlust benefits from an extremely talented cast and some of David Wain's most confident, assured work behind the camera.

title: Little Prince and the Eight Headed Dragon
Wanted
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Wanted is a fast-paced, crackling thrill ride tailor-made for the Summer audience.

title: War, Inc.
tomato_consensus: War, Inc. attempts to satirize the military industrial complex, but more often than not it misses its target.

title: WarGames
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 11 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Part delightfully tense techno-thriller, part refreshingly unpatronizing teen drama, WarGames is one of the more inventive -- and genuinely suspenseful -- Cold War movies of the 1980s.

title: War Horse
awards: Nominated for 6 Oscars. Another 8 wins & 43 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Technically superb, proudly sentimental, and unabashedly old-fashioned, War Horse is an emotional drama that tugs the heartstrings with Spielberg's customary flair.

title: War Photographer
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 6 wins & 3 nominations.

title: War and Peace
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 6 wins & 8 nominations.

title: War of the Worlds
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 13 wins & 19 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Steven Spielberg's adaptation of War of the Worlds delivers on the thrill and paranoia of H.G. Wells' classic novel while impressively updating the action and effects for modern audiences.

title: War of the Worlds 2: The Next Wave
wiki_title: War of the Worlds 2: The Next Wave

title: Warm Bodies
tomato_consensus: Warm Bodies offers a sweet, well-acted spin on a genre that all too often lives down to its brain-dead protagonists.

title: Warm Water Under a Red Bridge
wiki_title: Warm Water Under a Red Bridge

title: Warrior
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 10 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Warrior relies on many of the clich?s that critics of the genre love to mock -- and it transcends them with gripping action, powerful acting, and heart.

title: Wassup Rockers
tomato_consensus: As usual with Clark's films, the fixation on kids is rather creepy, plus the plot eventually runs off the rails into camp.

title: Watchmen
tomato_consensus: Gritty and visually striking, Watchmen is a faithful adaptation of Alan Moore's graphic novel, but its complex narrative structure may make it difficult for it to appeal to viewers not already familiar with the source material.

title: Water
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 14 wins & 12 nominations.
tomato_consensus: This compassionate work of social criticism is also luminous, due to both its lyrical imagery and cast.

title: Water for Elephants
tomato_consensus: It's a tale tastefully told and beautifully filmed, but Water for Elephants suffers from a pronounced lack of chemistry between its leads.

title: Waterloo
awards: Won 2 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 win & 2 nominations.

title: Watermarks
tomato_consensus: Watermarks is a moving and fascinating look at how the Nazi-fication of Germany in the 1930s affect a group of Jewish women swimmers.

title: Watermelon Man
awards: Nominated for 1 BAFTA Film Award. Another 1 win.

title: Watership Down
tomato_consensus: Aimed at adults perhaps more than children, this is a respectful, beautifully animated adaptation of Richard Adams' beloved book.

title: Waterworld
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 5 wins & 6 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Though it suffered from toxic buzz at the time of its release, Waterworld is ultimately an ambitious misfire: an extravagant sci-fi flick with some decent moments and a lot of silly ones.

title: Wax, or the Discovery of Television Among the Bees
wiki_title: Wax or the Discovery of Television Among the Bees

title: Wayne's World
tomato_consensus: An oddball comedy that revels in its silliness and memorable catch phrases, Wayne's World is also fondly regarded because of its endearing characters.

title: Wayne's World 2
tomato_consensus: The characters are still endearing, but the jokes in Wayne's World 2 are more hit-and-miss the second time around.

title: We're the Millers
tomato_consensus: We're the Millers squanders its potential with an uneven, lazily assembled story..

title: We Are Marshall
tomato_consensus: Matthew McConaughey almost runs We Are Marshall to the end zone, but can't stop it from taking the easy, feel-good route in memorializing this historic event in American sports.

title: We Bought a Zoo
tomato_consensus: We Bought a Zoo is a transparently cloying effort by director Cameron Crowe, but Matt Damon makes for a sympathetic central character.

title: We Don't Live Here Anymore
tomato_consensus: We Don't Live Here Anymore is often overly moody and grim, but it's made watchable by the strong performances for its four principal actors.

title: We Need to Talk About Kevin
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 20 wins & 31 nominations.
tomato_consensus: We Need to Talk About Kevin is a masterful blend of drama and horror, with fantastic performances across the board (Tilda Swinton especially, delivering one of her very best).
wiki_title: We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)

title: We Own the Night
tomato_consensus: Bland characters, clich?d dialogue and rickety plotting ensure We Own The Night never lives up to its potential.

title: We Were Soldiers
tomato_consensus: The war cliches are laid on a bit thick, but the movie succeeds at putting a human face on soldiers of both sides in the Vietnam War.

title: Wedding Crashers
tomato_consensus: Wedding Crashers is both raunchy and sweet, and features top-notch comic performances from Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson.

title: Weekend
tomato_consensus: It may be a chamber piece but Weekend's revelations on modern sexuality expand far beyond the modest setting.

title: Weird Science
tomato_consensus: Hardly in the same league as John Hughes' other teen movies, the resolutely goofy Weird Science nonetheless gets some laughs via its ridiculous premise and enjoyable performances.

title: Welcome Home, Roscoe Jenkins
tomato_consensus: Welcome Home Roscoe Jenkins has moments of comic inspiration -- and long stretches of overdone slapstick.

title: Welcome to Collinwood
tomato_consensus: Contains some funny moments, but it's still a very lightweight comedy.

title: Welcome to Mooseport
tomato_consensus: A bland comedy that squanders a talented cast.

title: Welcome to the Rileys
tomato_consensus: Despite earnest performances, Welcome to the Rileys cannot escape its belabored over-sentimentality and sluggish delivery.

title: Wendy and Lucy
tomato_consensus: Michelle Williams gives a heartbreaking performance in Wendy and Lucy, a timely portrait of loneliness and struggle.

title: West Side Story
tomato_consensus: Buoyed by Robert Wise's dazzling direction, Leonard Bernstein's score, and Stephen Sondheim's lyrics, West Side Story remains perhaps the most iconic of all the Shakespeare adaptations to visit the big screen.

title: The Clash: Westway to the World
Westworld
tomato_consensus: Yul Brynner gives a memorable performance as a robotic cowboy in this amusing sci-fi/western hybrid.

title: Wet Hot American Summer
tomato_consensus: As comedy, Wet Hot American Summer is a slapdash, fragmented affair that misses more often than hits. As parody, it fails because it attempts to satirize something ridiculous and self-parodying in itself.

title: Whale Rider
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 29 wins & 28 nominations.
tomato_consensus: An empowering and uplifting movie, with a wonderful performance by Castle-Hughes.

title: What's Cooking?
tomato_consensus: What's Cooking? is well-acted, but the scenes sometimes sink into melodrama as characters scream at each other, and the movie as a whole is too lightweight and forgettable.

title: What's Eating Gilbert Grape
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 7 wins & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: It's sentimental and somewhat predictable, but those are small complaints, given the tender atmosphere and moving performances at the heart of What's Eating Gilbert Grape.

title: What's Love Got to Do with It
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 4 wins & 9 nominations.
tomato_consensus: With a fascinating real-life story and powerhouse performances from Angela Bassett and Laurence Fishburne, What's Love Got to Do With It? is a can't miss biopic.
wiki_title: What's Love Got to Do with It (film)

title: What's Up, Doc?
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win.
tomato_consensus: Barbra Streisand was never more likable than in this energetic, often hilarious screwball farce from director Peter Bogdanovich.

title: What's Your Number?
tomato_consensus: The comic timing of Anna Faris is sharp as always, but it's wasted away in this predictable, boilerplate comedy.

title: What's a Nice Girl Like You Doing in a Place Like This?
wiki_title: What's a Nice Girl Like You Doing in a Place Like This?

title: What's the Worst That Could Happen?
tomato_consensus: Talented cast is squandered by an uninvolving script filled with unfunny gags.
wiki_title: What's the Worst That Could Happen?

title: What About Bob?
tomato_consensus: Bill Murray and Richard Dreyfuss' chemistry helps make the most of a familiar yet durable premise, elevating What About Bob? into the upper ranks of '90s comedies.

title: What Dreams May Come
tomato_consensus: An insubstantial plot overshadows the beautiful, surreal scenery.

title: What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?
wiki_title: What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)

title: What Happens in Vegas
tomato_consensus: What Happens in Vegas has a few laughs, but mostly settles for derivative romantic comedy conventions and receives little help from a pair of unlikable leads.

title: What Have I Done to Deserve This?
wiki_title: What Have I Done to Deserve This? (film)

title: What Have You Done to Solange?
wiki_title: What Have You Done to Solange?

title: What Just Happened
tomato_consensus: What Just Happened has some inspired comic moments, but this inside-baseball take on Hollywood lacks satirical bite.

title: What Lies Beneath
tomato_consensus: Robert Zemeckis is unable to salvage an uncompelling and unoriginal film.

title: What Maisie Knew
tomato_consensus: It's undeniably difficult to watch at times, but What Maisie Knew ultimately rises on the strength of its solidly sourced script, powerful performances, and empathetic direction.

title: What Planet Are You From?
tomato_consensus: Though What Planet Are You From? has some laughs, it's too inconsistent and bland for critics to give it their recommendations.

title: What Time Is It Over There?
tomato_consensus: Though it requires patience to view, What Time Is It There?'s exploration of loneliness is both elegant and haunting.

title: What to Do in Case of Fire
wiki_title: What To Do In Case Of Fire

title: What Women Want
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 7 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Even though Gibson is a good sport in his role, What Women Want is a rather conventional, fluffy comedy-romance that doesn't make good use of its premise.

title: What a Girl Wants
tomato_consensus: Little girls will definitely enjoy it, but it's too syrupy and predictable for adults.

title: What a Way to Go!
awards: Nominated for 2 Oscars. Another 1 win & 5 nominations.

title: What the #$*! Do We (K)now!?
tomato_consensus: Educational, but as entertainment, it'll have viewers asking, 'What the bleep?'
wiki_title: What the Bleep Do We Know?!

title: What to Expect When You're Expecting
tomato_consensus: The cast is stocked with likable performers, but What to Expect When You're Expecting is too disjointed -- and too reliant on stock rom-com cliches -- to live up to its distinguished literary namesake.
wiki_title: What to Expect When You're Expecting (film)

title: Whatever It Takes
tomato_consensus: Whatever It Takes is another run-of-the-mill teeny-bopper romance flick. Cliche jokes and a tired plot capture few laughs.

title: Whatever Works
tomato_consensus: Based upon a script written in the 1970s, Woody Allen's Whatever Works suffers from a lack of fresh ideas.

title: When Father Was Away on Business
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 3 wins & 3 nominations.
wiki_title: When Father Was Away on Business

title: When Harry Met Sally...
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 4 wins & 14 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Rob Reiner's touching, funny film set a new standard for romantic comedies, and he was ably abetted by the sharp interplay between Billy Crystal and Meg Ryan.

title: When I Fall in Love... with Both
wiki_title: When I Fall in Love... with Both

title: When Knighthood Was in Flower
wiki_title: When Knighthood Was in Flower (1922 film)

title: When We Were Kings
tomato_consensus: An engrossing documentary that's as much about at time and a place as it is about a fight.

title: When Will I Be Loved
tomato_consensus: Neve Campbell bares all in this seemingly misogynistic trifle.

title: When a Man Loves a Woman
wiki_title: When a Man Loves a Woman (film)

title: When a Stranger Calls
tomato_consensus: What's fitting punishment for running up the phone bill? Why have that person baby sit; that'll teach them. Or better yet, make that person through this poorly acted, fright-free remake of the 1979 movie of the same name. Camilla Belle is a looker, but she got nothing on Carol Kane, the actress who originally played the part, when it comes to range. The final straw is that the payoff isn't worth the tedium that comes before. Just hang up on this one.

wiki_title: When a Woman Ascends the Stairs

title: When in Rome
tomato_consensus: A pair of young, attractive leads can't overcome When in Rome's reliance on unfunny gags and threadbare rom-com clich?s.

title: When the Last Sword is Drawn
wiki_title: When the Last Sword Is Drawn

title: Where the Heart Is
tomato_consensus: Poor script and messy plot undermines the decent cast.

title: Where the Money Is
tomato_consensus: The acting in Where the Money Is is excellent. However, the movie feels like a made-for-TV movie that's plain and forgettable.

title: Where the Wild Things Are
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 5 wins & 25 nominations.
tomato_consensus: Some may find its dark tone and slender narrative off-putting, but Spike Jonze's heartfelt adaptation of the classic children's book is as beautiful as it is uncompromising.

title: While You Were Sleeping
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 4 nominations.
tomato_consensus: While You Were Sleeping is built wholly from familiar ingredients, but assembled with such skill -- and with such a charming performance from Sandra Bullock -- that it gives formula a good name.

title: Whip It
tomato_consensus: While made from overly familiar ingredients, Drew Barrymore's directorial debut has enough charm, energy, and good-natured humor to transcend its many cliches.

title: Whipped
tomato_consensus: The sex jokes in Whipped are tiresomely vulgar and unfunny. Critics also condemn the movie as cynical and mean-spirited, with no likable characters.

title: Whistle Down the Wind
awards: Nominated for 4 BAFTA Film Awards. Another 1 win.

title: White Chicks
tomato_consensus: Scattershot comedy that's silly and obvious.

title: White Christmas
tomato_consensus: It may be too sweet for some, but this unabashedly sentimental holiday favorite is too cheerful to resist.

title: White Heat
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.
tomato_consensus: Raoul Walsh's crime drama goes further into the psychology of a gangster than most fear to tread and James Cagney's portrayal of the tragic anti-hero is constantly volatile.

title: White House Down
tomato_consensus: White House Down benefits from the leads' chemistry, but director Roland Emmerich smothers the film with narrative clich?s and choppily edited action.

title: White Hunter Black Heart
tomato_consensus: White Hunter Black Heart is powerful, intelligent, and subtly moving, a fascinating meditation on masculinity and the insecurities of artists.

title: White Men Can't Jump
tomato_consensus: White Men Can't Jump provides a fresh take on the sports comedy genre, with a clever script and a charismatic trio of leads.

title: White Noise
tomato_consensus: While there are some built-in scares, the movie is muddled and unsatisfying.

title: White Oleander
tomato_consensus: Strong performances by the lead actresses make White Oleander a compelling female melodrama.

title: White Palace
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: White Squall
tomato_consensus: Though it gets occasionally bogged down by touchy-feely sentiment, White Squall benefits greatly from Jeff Bridges' assured lead performance and Ridley Scott's visceral, exciting direction.

title: The White Sun of the Desert
Whiteout
tomato_consensus: Kate Beckinsale is as lovely as ever, and does her best with the material, but moribund pacing and an uninspired plot leave Whiteout in the cold.

title: Who's That Girl
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Who's That Knocking at My Door
wiki_title: Who's That Knocking at My Door

title: Who's Your Caddy?
tomato_consensus: A juvenile, uninspired retread of Caddyshack, Who's Your Caddy? is unoriginal, unfunny, and just plain forgettable.

title: Who Framed Roger Rabbit

title: Who Is Cletis Tout?

title: Who Is Harry Kellerman and Why Is He Saying Those Terrible Things About Me?
wiki_title: Who Is Harry Kellerman and Why Is He Saying Those Terrible Things About Me?

title: Who Killed the Electric Car?

title: Why Did I Get Married Too?

wiki_title: Why Did I Get Married Too?

title: Why Do Fools Fall in Love
tomato_consensus: This is a fun comedy with delightful musical numbers.
wiki_title: Why Do Fools Fall in Love (film)

title: Why We Fight
tomato_consensus: A provocative and timely film that explores the military/industrial complex and the motivating forces that lead us to war.

title: Wicker Park
tomato_consensus: Implausible coincidences and an overly convoluted structure make the movie hard to follow or believe.

title: Wilbur Wants to Kill Himself

title: Wild Hogs
tomato_consensus: Wild Hogs is a dreadful combination of fish-out-of-water jokes, slapstick, and lazy stereotypes.

title: Wild Is the Wind
awards: Nominated for 3 Oscars. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Wild Strawberries
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 12 wins & 2 nominations.

title: Wild Target
tomato_consensus: An ineptly staged farce that dishonors the original film and squanders the comedic potential of its fine actors.

title: Wild Things: Diamonds in the Rough
wiki_title: Wild Things: Diamonds in the Rough

title: Wild Wild West
tomato_consensus: Bombastic, manic, and largely laugh-free, Wild Wild West is a bizarre misfire in which greater care was lavished upon the special effects than on the script.

title: Wild at Heart
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 2 wins & 5 nominations.

title: Wild in the Streets
awards: Nominated for 1 Oscar. Another 1 win & 1 nomination.

title: Wilde
awards: Nominated for 1 Golden Globe. Another 3 wins & 7 nominations.

title: Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter?

title: Wordplay
tomato_consensus: You see them hunched over with their brows furrowed, folded newspaper in hand as they attempt to complete the crossword puzzle. This may even describe you. This ingeniously edited documentary introduces viewers to some of the more dedicated fans of this solitary pastime, none more well-known the puzzle editor for the New York Times, Will Shortz. This underground world provides a surprising amount of crowd-pleasing entertainment and suspense, especially at the annual crossword tournament. Didn't know there was one, did you?

title: World's Greatest Dad
